<FIRST>r a PM-NaziScience     05-12 0704</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nazi Science,0721</SECOND>
<HEAD>Researcher Plans To Republish Nazi Data</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM KRATTENMAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A scientist is planning to use Nazi studies of concentration camp prisoners deliberately frozen to death to further his research about hypothermia. But some scientists and <PERSON> Jewish </PERSON> leaders have sharply criticized his intention to use data obtained during the Holocaust. Dr. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Pozos </PERSON>, director of the hypothermia research laboratory at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Duluth </LOCATION>, says he plans to analyze and republish `` The Treatment of Shock from Prolonged Exposure to Cold,'' a study by doctors at <LOCATION> Dachau </LOCATION>. It includes observation and physiological measurements of people placed in vats of freezing liquid, often to the point of death, according to those familiar with the study. `` We should under no circumstances use the information. It was gained in an immoral way,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Callahan </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Hastings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, a medical ethics think tank in <LOCATION> Briarcliff </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Manor </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION> `` I think it goes to legitimizing the evil done. I think the findings are tainted by the horror and misery,'' said <PERSON> Abraham </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Foxman </PERSON>, national director of the <ORGANIZATION> Anti-Defamation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION>. Because mammals differ widely in their physiological response to cold, hypothermia research is uniquely dependent on human test subjects, says <PERSON> Pozos </PERSON>, a specialist in the field for 12 years. `` It could advance my work in that it takes human subjects farther than we're willing,'' he said. Several medical ethicists contend study of the Nazi research could save lives and, if published with a condemnation of the methods, call attention to the plight of the Jews, Poles and Gypsies killed in the experiments. Because the Egyptians used slave labor, `` does that mean we should never gaze at the pyramids?'' asked Dr. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Murray </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Biomedical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ethics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> at </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Case </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION>. `` It sends a chill down every normal human being's spine to think of the horrible things the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> did there, but I'm separating the results and the circumstances,'' said <PERSON> Ephraim </PERSON> <PERSON> Zuroff </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> representative to the <ORGANIZATION> Simon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wiesenthal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> `` Actually, if the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> doctor dedicated his study to the memory of those victims of the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION>, it would serve as a nice way of reminding people about the horrible experiments.'' Use of Nazi science by post-World War II researchers is rare but not unprecedented. After facing a similar quandary this year, the federal <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> deleted references to Nazi research in its own draft report on a toxic gas. <PERSON> Pozos </PERSON>, 45, says he decided to use the Nazi hypothermia data after seeing a resurgence of public and scientific curiosity about it. He says copies of a 1945 English translation of the <LOCATION> Dachau </LOCATION> study have been available in about a dozen libraries around the country. Motivated in part by the loss of pilots in the frigid <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>, the Germans used 100 to 300 prisoners to test the body's response to extreme cold, <PERSON> Pozos </PERSON> said; how many died is unclear. Besides testing the phenomenon of freezing, the doctors experimented with warming techniques ranging from body-to-body contact to alcohol ingestion, <PERSON> Pozos </PERSON> said. Word of Pozos' plans for the old Nazi experiments spread after he contacted <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION> medical ethicist <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Caplan </PERSON> for advice. <PERSON> Caplan </PERSON> wrote a newspaper column about the issue. <PERSON> Pozos </PERSON> said he has had a generally positive response, including calls from about a half-dozen Holocaust survivors. `` They said I should get something out of this so these people would not have died in vain,'' said <PERSON> Pozos </PERSON>. Within two months, <PERSON> Pozos </PERSON> said, he hopes to republish the German study in a scientific journal with his own analysis of its quality and application to modern hypothermia research. While calling the study `` a record of unimaginable horror and cruelty,'' <PERSON> Caplan </PERSON> said he believes <PERSON> Pozos </PERSON> should be allowed to republish it under strict guidelines. Among other stipulations, <PERSON> Caplan </PERSON> urges omission of the <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> doctors' names to ensure no credit is conferred. `` If the data can prevent a single death, then it is worth tolerating the stench of past deaths that will cling to each page,'' <PERSON> Caplan </PERSON> wrote. <PERSON> Caplan </PERSON> has organized an international symposium on <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> science, tentatively scheduled for May 1989 at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
