<HEAD>Chrysler Workers Narrowly Approve Two-Year Settlement</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with contract approved. No pickup. Version
also moving on financial wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday ratified a contract giving 66,000 <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> employees in 15 states greater job protection, the union said. The two-year contract was approved by about 54 percent of those voting, according to union officials who spoke on condition they not be identified. Two former <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> locals in <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> also voted Wednesday, approving separate pacts reached during the national contract talks at <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s Highland Park headquarters. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> bought AMC in August. The <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> and the No. 3 automaker reached the agreement May 4 after 2 -LCB- weeks of early negotiations aimed at mending a series of conflicts. Talks normally would have begun in July or August. The contract, which replaces a three-year agreement that would have have expired Sept. 14, mirrors that signed last fall at <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. The Big Three contract prevents layoffs except when production is cut because of slow sales, forbids plant closings not announced before talks began and makes it harder for companies to transfer work to outside companies or foreign countries. The Chrysler contract also provides 3 percent lump-sum bonuses in 1989 and 1990, a $ 1,000 signing bonus and, for the first time, profit-sharing according to the formula that has generated thousands of dollars for <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> workers. But the <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> pact also prevents the company from paying cash or stock bonuses to executives in years when a profit-sharing formula included in the contract generates no payout for workers. The <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> was angered in the past two years when <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> workers received no profit-sharing while executives were awarded generous bonuses. Union leaders, including Vice President <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON>, have said they expected the pact, approved last week by local union leaders on the <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION>'s 140-member <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> bargaining council, to be ratified by a comfortable margin. However, the contract was rejected at several large locals, including <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>'s Jefferson Avenue assembly plant and Mound Road engine plant and a stamping plant in <LOCATION> Sterling </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Heights </LOCATION>, union officials said. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s 3,500-worker Warren Truck plant approved the contract with 65 percent in favor, said Local 140 President <PERSON> Gil </PERSON> <PERSON> Wojcik </PERSON>. `` I'm surprised. I'm flabbergasted. I thought it would pass by a wider margin,'' said <PERSON> Wojcik </PERSON>, chairman of the elected 10-member bargaining committee. Unlike the <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> pacts, the <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> contract also protects 2,200 workers at four closing <ORGANIZATION> Acustar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> parts plants from layoff. When any of the plants are closed, workers will be paid their regular wages and placed in a job bank. If any of the four plants _ one in <LOCATION> Van </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wert </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, and three in the <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> area _ are sold instead, workers can choose whether to go into the job bank and wait for a <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> opening or go with the new employer.
