<HEAD>Fans Put on the Ritz for Berlin's 100th Birthday</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with Carnegie Hall concert,
picking up 3rd graf `At midday ...' Changes byline.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY201</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 From <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinatra </PERSON> to <PERSON> Isaac </PERSON> <PERSON> Stern </PERSON>, show business put on the <ORGANIZATION> Ritz </ORGANIZATION> for <LOCATION> Irving </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> and raised a classy, schmaltzy salute to the songwriter Wednesday on his 100th birthday. The creator of thousands of tunes was not in Carnegie Hall for the three-hour concert, but family members filled a row. The event started big and ended bigger, with the Army Chorus and soldiers from Ft.. Dix, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, filling the stage in front of a 30-piece orchestra, Boy Scouts and Girl Scouts standing in the aisles and <PERSON> Marilyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Horne </PERSON>'s mezzo-soprano voice soaring above them in <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>'s `` God Bless America. Then the evening's performers filed in the audience stood, and everybody sang a lusty `` There's No Business Like Show Business,'' still another <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> classic. The artists included <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> and <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Bernstein </PERSON> on piano. It was <PERSON> Bernstein </PERSON>'s <PERSON> Carnegie </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> singing debut with <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>'s `` Russian Lullaby. Director-choreographer <PERSON> Tommy </PERSON> <PERSON> Tune </PERSON> tapdanced to `` Puttin' on the Ritz,'' and <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>, in formal black with a black cowboy hat, brought his band for `` Blue Skies.'' `` We would n't think of doing a show without including it,'' <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Sinatra </PERSON> sang `` Always'' and `` When I Lost You,'' <PERSON> Nell </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> did `` <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON>'s Ragtime Band,'' <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Orbach </PERSON> and <PERSON> Maureen </PERSON> <PERSON> McGovern </PERSON> `` Easter Parade,'' and <PERSON> Rosemary </PERSON> <PERSON> Clooney 