<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than 100 descendants of colonial planter <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Drayton </PERSON> are expected at his plantation this weekend to celebrate the 250th anniversary of the family homestead. <PERSON> Drayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>, a two-story brick Georgian structure northwest of <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>, has passed through seven generations of the <PERSON> Drayton </PERSON> family. Now it is one of 13 sites maintained by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Historic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Preservation </ORGANIZATION> that is open to the public. It attracts more than 52,000 visitors a year. The <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Drayton </PERSON> family settled in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> in 1679 _ nine years after the founding of <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>. The youngest son, <PERSON> John </PERSON>, began construction of <PERSON> Drayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> in 1738. It was completed four years later. His father lived at nearby <LOCATION> Magnolia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plantation </LOCATION>, which also is a popular tourist attraction. There are an estimated 4,000 descendants of <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Drayton </PERSON> scattered around the world, and at least 100 are expected for the celebration, which will include dancing under the stars and workshops on archaeology, said <PERSON> Meg </PERSON> <PERSON> Lavin </PERSON>, curator at <PERSON> Drayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>. <PERSON> Drayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> is the only <LOCATION> Ashley </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> plantation to survive the Civil War intact. Two small flanking buildings _ one used as a kitchen and one as a utility building _ were destroyed in the 1886 <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION> earthquake and a hurricane seven years later. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Neil </PERSON>, assistant director of <PERSON> Drayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>, said that according to family legend, the house emerged from the Civil War unscathed because of the quick thinking of its occupant, Dr. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Drayton </PERSON>. As Union troops marched through toward the end of the war, <PERSON> Drayton </PERSON> had the house posted with flags signifying it was being used to treat smallpox patients. However, it's not known whether it actually was used as a hospital. `` The story comes down both through the owners and slave descendants. Whether it was a ruse or not is unclear,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Lavin </PERSON>. The builder of the house was a successful planter who owned up to 125 slaves and acquired 30 other properties including townhouses in <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>. The cost of building the manor, located on a 125-acre tract, is not known, said <PERSON> Neil </PERSON>. However, in the later part of the 18th Century the house was referred to as `` Mr. <PERSON> Drayton </PERSON>'s Palace.''
