<HEAD>Donald Regan Calls For Steps to Quell Market Problems</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Regan </PERSON> took time off from discussing his book on the inner workings of President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> to tell <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> that financial markets and the government must act quickly to reassure the nation's investors. The former <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> secretary said Wednesday that `` there should have been more prompt action'' after last October's stock market crash. `` This thing happened over seven months ago,'' he said. <PERSON> Regan </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> that a form of computerized trading called index arbitrage should be prohibited, and that all transactions involving stock index futures should be temporarily halted. Both practices, he said, make the markets excessively volatile and have scared worried individual investors off. `` A stock market whose main participants are speculators and their programs can not be a healthy market, and an unhealthy Wall Street will sooner or later drag down the real economy,'' said <PERSON> Regan </PERSON>, the former chief executive officer of <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co. The banking panel has been holding hearings on the dramatic price swings that have dominated the markets since Oct. 19, when the Dow Jones Industrial Average fell a record 508 points. <PERSON> Regan </PERSON>, who was White House chief of staff for two years after being treasury secretary, has spent most of his time recently talking about his new book, `` For the Record: From Wall Street to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>.'' In it, he says first lady <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> often consults astrologers when planning the president's schedule and making other decisions. <PERSON> Regan </PERSON> declined to discuss his book Wednesday with reporters. But he did blame computer-driven trading, especially index arbitrage, for the market's problems. Traders conducting index arbitrage use computers to profit from price discrepancies between the stock and futures markets by simultaneously buying in one market and selling in the other. `` In my mind, we should start by banning index option arbitrage, and then proceed with other reforms which will restore public confidence in the financial markets,'' <PERSON> Regan </PERSON> said. He said problems also have been caused by stock futures, which are traded in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. In a stock index futures transaction, an amount of cash equal to the value of a collection of stocks changes hands, with an agreement that the portfolio will be bought back at whatever those stocks' values are at a specific future date. Opponents of the practice say the massive amounts of money involved add unpredictability to the stock market when traders buy or sell equities to protect their futures transactions. `` I think there should be a pause'' in index futures trading, <PERSON> Regan </PERSON> told reporters after his testimony. `` It wo n't hurt very much for a three-month or six-month pause here while we take a look at the instrument itself and how it's used to see whether or not it should be permitted to continue.'' <PERSON> Regan </PERSON> told the senators the nation's financial markets, or the federal agencies that regulate them, should initiate the steps he recommended. If not, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> should act, he said. At the same hearing, <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ball </PERSON>, chairman and chief executive officer of <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said the abolition of stock index futures should be considered. `` Most knowledgeable professionals agree that if it were not for index futures, stock market moves would be far less wild, sudden or irrationally large,'' he said. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwab </PERSON>, who owns the discount brokerage firm that bears his name, also told the lawmakers that program trading should be abolished if other steps to restore market confidence do n't work. `` In surveys we have conducted, we hear over and over again the theme that individual investors fear they can not compete in markets that are so dominated by the volatility introduced by program trading and index arbitrage,'' he said. Earlier, <PERSON> Leo </PERSON> <PERSON> Melamed </PERSON>, chairman of the executive committee of the board of governors of the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, told reporters that index arbitrage helps stabilize the markets by ensuring that stock and futures prices closely track each other. `` I'm not going to defend perception,'' he said. `` The reality is it is not a factor'' in the volatility.
