<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 There's a creaky plank in the platform President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> stands on when he sounds off against legislation aimed at protecting workers against sudden plant closings. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, speaking against the provision recently, said that `` as an old labor union president, I suggest that's a matter that belongs in the management-labor contracts between the unions and the people.'' But that suggests organized labor plays a larger-than-life role in today's economy. Many government statisticians, unionists and even business executives know better. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> headed the Screen Actors Guild in <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> in the late 1940s, when unions were far more powerful than they are today, representing roughly a third of all workers. Because unions now represent only about 15 percent of all workers, and about 20 percent in manufacturing, it does n't necessarily follow that plant notification protections can be left for employers and unions to settle Doing that would leave open the question of who takes care of the interests of the other 80 percent of blue-collar workers. What's happened is that the administration has essentially accepted the boardroom argument that executives must be free to make their own decisions, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s shopworn argument notwithstanding. And Labor Secretary <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> McLaughlin </PERSON> conceded to a manfacturer's audience Tuesday that this may prove politically costly, especially if <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s expected veto of the bill is sustained `` The polls have indicated that, from the people I've talked to, 62 percent of the people think that plant notification is the right way to go,'' she said. `` This issue is going to drive us kicking and screaming for the next five months.'' The plant-closing provision in the 1,000-page trade bill was the product of heavy lobbying by the <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION>, and many Democrats were unwilling to see it pulled from the bill. `` The workers who do not have the benefit of a union are treated like dogs,'' said <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON>, assistant to <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Industrial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. `` The fact is that, although a lot of companies talk a good game and a lot of them do a good game, the overwhelming fact is that many workers do not get sufficient notice,'' <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> said. He cited a <ORGANIZATION> Government </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> study which found that workers hit by plant closings but not represented by unions had an average of only two days warning. <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Bernardo </PERSON>, special counsel for domestic policy at the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> is correct in opposing any move by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to legislate worker notification protections. `` Eighty-eight percent of the employers do give some notice and more and more employers are giving more, whether they have unions or not,'' he said. `` But it's not always possible for businesses in financial turmoil.'' Plant closing legislation, he said, `` would handcuff employers at a time which is particularly troubled and turbulent.'' <PERSON> Audrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Freeman </PERSON>, a labor economist at the <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, a business research organization in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, challenged arguments used by government, business and labor on this issue. Referring to <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s statement about leaving plant-closing protection to companies and unions, she said, `` I think that's a cynical response that you're getting from the White House.'' `` The strength of unions tends to be more and more in government and government-affected employment,'' rather than in manufacturing, she said. `` The whole plant-closing thing is kind of artificial,'' she said. `` I have the impression that they're -LRB- the opponents and proponents -RRB- just acting in front of a painted scenery.'' Ms. <PERSON> Freeman </PERSON> said she thinks business overstates its concern about governmental interference and that organized labor merely is trying to get back a greater say in the decision-making process.
</TEXT>
