<SECOND>PM-Jeds Reunion,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Old Soldiers Recall Adventure Helping European Resistance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 They're all old men now, but the soldiers of the multinational `` Jedburgh'' unit today are remembering the days in World War II when they parachuted behind enemy lines with a radio and a small fortune. `` We're getting a bit thinner every year,'' said <PERSON> Ivor </PERSON> <PERSON> Hooker </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Haverhill </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, after some of the old soldiers chanted a raunchy put-down of superior officers in the <LOCATION> Dulles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> waiting area on Wednesday. The American and British veterans welcomed their French comrades, along with widows and family members of some who have died. In what is billed as probably their last full reunion, the 51 American, 26 French and 18 British `` Jeds'' _ some have not seen each other for 44 years _ were beginning activities today that would include wreath-laying ceremonies at <ORGANIZATION> Arlington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cemetery </ORGANIZATION>, honors at the British and French embassies and a visit with President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> on Friday. Some are bragging a little. Others speak softly of lost comrades in one of the most heroic and secretive exploits of the war. The `` top secret'' classification for hundreds of boxes of government documents on the unit was only lifted in 1985. In teams of three, 279 Jeds were dropped across <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> The </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, to help lead the resistance against German occupation. Their name comes from a town in <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> where `` Jedburgh justice'' for sheep rustlers meant `` hang them first and question them afterwards.'' <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Bazata </PERSON>, who said he is still involved in government work and accepts the description `` red-headed soldier of fortune'' even though his hair is now pure white, asked another <PERSON> Jed </PERSON> at the airport if he'd ever lost any of the money they were given to aid the resistance around the time of the June 6, 1944, <LOCATION> Normandy </LOCATION> landings. <PERSON> Bazata </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Bethesda </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, said he parachuted in with $ 300,000 in cash. `` I loved it. You were totally your own boss, responsible for everything. When you sent messages back to headquarters, they listened. And you had unlimited money,'' said <PERSON> Bazata </PERSON>. The Jeds sabotaged German troops, blew up bridges and helped organize and arm resistance forces. Most spoke French and blended into cities and villages taken over by the Germans. Some of the Americans went on to similar missions in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, organizing popular resistance against Japanese forces. Because they could pick their targets, few were killed during the mission, said retired Col. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Mills </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Fairfax </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, who is writing a book about Allied efforts behind enemy lines. <PERSON> Mills </PERSON> worked in the Jedburgh operation and supervised some of the forces in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> but was not a <PERSON> Jed </PERSON> himself. `` They were guerrillas. They had to design operations that would keep them alive,'' he said. <PERSON> Daphne </PERSON> <PERSON> Friele </PERSON>, who has helped organize the reunion, was so taken by the American <PERSON> Jeds </PERSON> when she was an 18-year-old secretary to their <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> commander that she later married two of them. Her first husband, Col. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mundinger </PERSON>, died in the Korean War. Two years ago, she married <PERSON> Berent </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Friele </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Redding </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, after they met again at a Jed reunion in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. `` It took some of them this long to find each other, and they wo n't let go,'' said Mrs. <PERSON> Friele </PERSON>, 62, who is still trying to find out what happened to the only two Americans in the unit she has n't accounted for: <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Gruen </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ian </PERSON> <PERSON> Forbes </PERSON> American members include former <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> Director <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Colby </PERSON>; retired Army Maj. Gen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Singlaub </PERSON>, who has organized a controversial worldwide effort to support resistance groups against communism, and internationally known yachtsman <PERSON> Hod </PERSON> <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON>, a retired Marine general. The late columnist <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> <PERSON> Alsop </PERSON> also was a Jed.
</TEXT>
