<HEAD>Researchers Says Science On Brink Of Correcting Flawed Immunity</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A hormone that causes the body to produce immune cells is in the final stages of clinical testing and may provide a breakthrough in protecting the elderly against death from influenza and pneumonia, two researchers say. `` This may well be a research breakthrough for the treatment of disease among elderly people,'' Dr. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ershler </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wisconsin </ORGANIZATION> told the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Aging. The committee is conducting a hearing on research into the health problems of the elderly. Thymosin Alpha One, a form of the hormone thymosin, has now been given to elderly patients in two early clinical trials, and in both cases the level of immune action was increased, <PERSON> Ershler </PERSON> said Wednesday. Flu vaccine generally is effective in only about 25 percent of the elderly who receive it, he said. But in studies using Thymosin Alpha One, the effectiveness was increased to 70 percent. Researchers have long known that the immune system becomes increasingly weaker as people age, he said. As a result, `` infections remain a major cause of morbidity and mortality in elderly people,'' he said. <PERSON> Ershler </PERSON> said a deficiency of one of the immune cells, called T-cell lymphocyte, is caused by a decline in the function of the thymus gland. This, in turn, has been traced to a shortage of thymosin. An expanded study, using 400 patients at the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Soldiers and Airmen's Home here, was conducted last fall and winter. Results have not been analyzed, said <PERSON> Ershler </PERSON>, but `` it may be a research breakthrough.'' <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldstein </PERSON>, a professor at <ORGANIZATION> George </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and a co-discoverer of thymosin, said the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> study has `` great promise.'' `` It is hoped that within two years we'll be able to apply this new approach to lower the incidence of flu and pneumonia among the elderly,'' <PERSON> Goldstein </PERSON> told the committee. He said influenza affects millions of elderly Americans annually, costs hundreds of millions of dollars in medical care and causes about 25,000 deaths among people over age 65.
