</LOCATION> _ were at the jungle meeting, the sources said. Also present were eight dissident Contra military leaders who on Sunday publicly accused <PERSON> Bermudez </PERSON> of opposing negotiations for a more permanent truce with the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION>, the sources said. <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s vice president, <PERSON> Sergio </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramirez </PERSON> <PERSON> Mercado </PERSON>, said on Wednesday at the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> that his government was not sure if rebel fighters would honor any agreement reached by their political leaders. <PERSON> Ramirez </PERSON> said the `` open rebellion'' against <PERSON> Bermudez </PERSON> `` represents a serious limitation'' to the talks. `` We do n't know now if what the political leadership of the Contras is going to discuss with us in the next round of negotiations is going to be accepted by this military leadership under the command of Col. <PERSON> Bermudez </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Ramirez </PERSON> said. He spoke at a news conference before the opening of a special <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> session on economic aid to <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bermudez </PERSON> hinted he might use force to bring the dissidents back into line but expressed hope that he and <PERSON> Adolfo </PERSON> <PERSON> Calero </PERSON>, the top Contra civilian leader, will find a solution to the problem. `` I am sure that once the fighters understand the reality of the situation, they will change their attitude,'' he said in the telephone interview. On March 23, Sandinista and Contra leaders signed a preliminary accord aimed at ending the 6 -LCB- - year-old civil war A 60-day truce went into effect April 1, during which the two sides were supposed to negotiate conditions for a lasting peace. Two rounds of high-level negotiations in <LOCATIO