<FIRST>r a PM-AleutsCompensation Bjt   05-12 0747</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Aleuts Compensation, Bjt,0775</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aleut Compensation Bill May Be `Too Little, Too Late'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AG1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL JENKINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNALASKA, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 For <PERSON> Harriet </PERSON> <PERSON> Hope </PERSON>, years of congressional wrangling over whether to compensate natives of the <LOCATION> Aleutian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> who were forced into camps during World War II have taken their toll. `` It's just too little, too late,'' she said. `` The old ones who deserve it the most are gone.'' Hope and her family were among 110 Aleuts from <LOCATION> Unalaska </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> villages ordered from their homes in July 1942 after the Japanese bombed and strafed the island's Dutch Harbor. They were herded aboard a steamship that took them to a camp in southeast <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, purportedly to protect them from harm. They were not alone. An estimated 880 Aleuts were evacuated from the Aleutians. Many houses later were ransacked or destroyed by soldiers and sailors. Photographs, diaries, icons and other possessions left behind were damaged or stolen, residents say. About 10 percent of the Aleuts died in the camps. Some never went home. It has been estimated that half the camps' survivors have since died. The Japanese seized three of the western Aleutians _ <LOCATION> Attu </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Agattu </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kiska </LOCATION> _ and occupied them between 1942 and 1943. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, conference committee staff members were scheduled to meet today to work out differences in <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> versions of a measure authorizing reparations to Japanese-Americans and Aleuts forced from their homes in the opening months of the war. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> bill, considered likely to be adopted, would pay the Aleut camp survivors $ 12,000 each, set up a $ 5 million trust fund for the six villages where people were forced from their homes, authorize $ 1.4 million to restore and rehabilitate churches damaged or destroyed in the war and pay the Aleuts between $ 12 million and $ 15 million for the loss of <LOCATION> Attu </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, which has remained under military control. Japanese-Americans forced into camps would receive $ 20,000 each, and virtually nothing else. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirtland </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> lawyer hired in 1978 to represent the Aleuts before <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, thinks the legislation, re-introduced each year since 1983, will make it to the president this year. Hope was 5 years old when the Japanese planes arrived. Her father was English, her mother, Aleut. Her father, the village postmaster, was allowed to remain behind because of his nationality. `` We had 48 hours to get ready. We were told to take nothing but a very, very few belongings,'' she recalled. Hope, her mother, two brothers and a sister joined other Aleuts from the island's three villages for the voyage. Eventually they were deposited at a burned-out cannery at <LOCATION> Burnett </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Inlet </LOCATION> on the <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Panhandle </LOCATION>. `` It was nothing but a ghost gown. There was no plumbing, no heat, just an abandoned old cannery. There was no running water. You could see through the ceiling.'' Medical facilities were virtually non-existent. Tuberculosis was a threat. Village hunters and fishermen used to the treeless mountains of <LOCATION> Unalaska </LOCATION> were thrown into a strange environment. `` It was like trying to live a subsistence lifestyle in a foreign country,'' <PERSON> Hope </PERSON> said. For the three years the family was held at the camp, <PERSON> Hope </PERSON>'s father was allowed only one 10-day visit, <PERSON> Hope </PERSON> said Her mother worked at canneries to earn money, and provided medical care to camp residents. Her brother left to work on a fishing boat. `` I just do n't understand why they did what they did,'' <PERSON> Hope </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> Aleut </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a regional native corporation, and the <ORGANIZATION> Aleutian-Pribilof </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Islands </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> led the drive for Aleut reparations. <LOCATION> Kirtland </LOCATION>'s firm searched archives and put together reams of evidence about camp conditions and the wrongs committed during and after the evacuation. At about the same time, a nine-member federal Commission On Wartime Relocation and Internment of Civilians was appointed by the president and congressional leaders. `` Nine volumes of documentary evidence were given to commission,'' <LOCATION> Kirtland </LOCATION> said. The panel held hearings around <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, and recommended compensation for the Aleuts in June 1983. Just as the compensation is pending, the scars of war remain on <LOCATION> Unalaska </LOCATION>. Trench lines cut the mountains. Bunkers, pillboxes and machine-gun nests dot the landscape. The past is never far away. Hope works as a receptionist at <LOCATION> Unalaska </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hall </LOCATION>, near the house where she was born. `` I do n't feel like I deserve anything; it's my mother and father _ they went through the anguish. They're the ones who really deserve it.'' Her father died in 1956; her mother, 10 years later.
