<FIRST>r a PM-Diarrhea     05-12 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Diarrhea,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Milk Antibodies Effective Against Traveler's Diarrhea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Researchers say they are encouraged by experimental use of a derivative of cow's milk to prevent traveler's diarrhea and hope to test their discovery on people going to developing countries. In a report today, they said that powdered concentrations of milk antibodies appeared to protect people from the effects of E. coli bacteria, a common cause of diarrhea. `` These preliminary results are highly encouraging,'' they wrote in the New England Journal of Medicine. The researchers, led by Dr. <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tacket </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maryland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION>, found that the treatment may provide an alternative to prescription antibiotics and over-the-counter bismuth subsalicylate, which can keep people from getting diarrhea. The researchers said that about half of all travelers to developing countries get diarrhea. `` We want to do a field study to see if it works among travelers,'' said <PERSON> Tacket </PERSON>. `` Our study was a very artificial situation.'' To make the concentrate, cows were first vaccinated with varieties of E. coli that cause diarrhea. The cows then produced antibodies in their milk that protected them from these microbes. The researchers removed these antibodies and prepared them in powder form. Ten volunteers drank the powdered E. coli antibodies dissolved in water three times a day for three days. Ten others got other forms of antibodies. Then all were given diarrhea-causing E. coli. None of the 10 who got the E. coli antibodies developed diarrhea. However, nine of the 10 in the comparison group got the illness.
</TEXT>
