<HEAD>Report: Suspects May Have Been Involved In Past ANC Attacks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Four whites charged with possession of an impressive arms cache may have been involved in previous attacks carried out by the <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, a newspaper reported today. Police announced on Wednesday they had made their biggest arms seizure ever in connection with the arrests of three men and one woman who allegedly were acting on behalf of the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION>'s military wing. The four suspects also had a `` hit-list'' of top police officials, according to police. Arms seized included a Soviet-made SAM-7 ground-to-air missile, limpet mines, hand grenades, assault rifles, pistols, machine guns, mortars and explosives, police said. They said the four had planned to use the missile to shoot down a police helicopter at a recent fair. Police have not released the suspects' names, but have said the three men are South African citizens and the woman is a foreigner. The four are college educated and in their 20s and 30s, police said, adding that two are military draft dodgers and one is a former journalist. The Citizen, a pro-government daily, said without citing sources that at least one of the four was believed involved in <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> attacks carried out in the early 1980s. The mostly black <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> was outlawed in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> in 1960 and began a sabotage-and-bombing campaign the following year aimed at toppling white-minority rule. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Lodge </PERSON>, a leading authority on the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> and a lecturer at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witwatersrand </ORGANIZATION>, said the arrests illustrate `` the continuing trend of young, well-educated liberal and left-wing whites -LRB- to -RRB- identify themselves with the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION>.'' Lodge said white participation in the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION>'s military wing `` obviously has a greater impact on the attitudes of white <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> than the involvement of blacks.'' Few whites have been involved in the <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION>'s military operations, although there have been several highly publicized cases in recent years. Following a March 17 car bombing that killed three people, police said the leading suspect was <PERSON> Heinrich </PERSON> <PERSON> Grosskopf </PERSON>, a white South African and an alleged <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> member who remains at large. Law and Order Minister <PERSON> Adriaan </PERSON> <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON> described the four suspects as `` a highly specialized terror unit.'' He alleged that the suspects had been trained in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, and had radio transmitters which they used to communicate with <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> headquarters in <LOCATION> Lusaka </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Zambia </LOCATION>. He said they were captured Sunday at a farmhouse near <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION>, where they had been staying since early this year. The South African Press Association, citing unidentified police sources, said a disenchanted <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> member apparently gave authorities the tip that led them to the four suspects. <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON> said police still were investigating how the weapons were brought into <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, but he said the arms came overland through <LOCATION> Zambia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Botswana </LOCATION>. Police have announced numerous arrests of alleged <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> members in recent months and say they have substantially weakened the group's ability to operate inside <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> There have been more than 70 bombings in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> since a nationwide state of emergency was imposed in June 1986, but the frequency has fallen sharply in recent months.
