<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The military charged today that foreign sponsors have stepped up weapons shipments to Afghan guerrillas and sent in more military advisors, endangering Soviet troops who are about to march out of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> reported in a front-page dispatch from its military correspondents at <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> headquarters in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> that there is great anxiety about the withdrawal that begins Sunday. `` They are facing 1,500 kilometers -LRB- 940 miles -RRB- of mountainous, war-torn roads,'' the newspaper said of Soviet soldiers who will be among the first to pull out of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s southern neighbor. `` And we know very well that roads in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> are on the forward edge of the undeclared war. It is necessary to be prepared for the possibility of armed provocations.'' The newspaper said rebel activity had been stepped up in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kandahar </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ghazni </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Paktia </LOCATION> and other provinces. `` Taking advantage of the pullback of Soviet and Afghan troops from border areas of those regions in the depth of the country, the opposition and its foreign patrons have sharply increased the number of caravans with weapons, delivering them _ not only at night now but also in the daytime,'' the paper claimed. `` In the military formations there has been a noticeable growth in the number of foreign military advisers, who organize joint actions by groups from different Moslem parties,'' the newspaper said. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has been the insurgents' chief arms supplier. <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> said the preparations for withdrawal were nearly complete at the <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> headquarters of the `` limited military contingent,'' as the 115,000 Soviet soldiers in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> are referred to in the state-run press. The dispatch did not make clear, however, how many would leave in the first march north or when headquarters would be evacuated. It said the first troops to leave would be motorized rifle regiments, paratroopers, scouts and pilots, but gave no other details. <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> has been in the throes of civil war since April 1978, when a Soviet-inspired revolution brought a Marxist government to power. Soviet soldiers intervened in December 1979 to install <PERSON> Babrak </PERSON> <PERSON> Karmal </PERSON> as the Afghan leader and to help troops loyal to him put down a widespread insurrection. <PERSON> Karmal </PERSON> was replaced by <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> in May 1986 and has since taken refuge in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>.
