<HEAD>Baseball Players Live Longer Than Ordinary Folks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to CLARIFY that doctors were from University of
Alabama at Birmingham; A version moved on sports wires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A survey of former major leaguers concludes that baseball is a healthy way of life, and the infield is the best place to be. Doctors from the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alabama </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Birmingham </LOCATION> poured over baseball encyclopedias and death certificates to learn when and how players died. `` The main thing we found was the overall protective effect of being an athlete,'' said Dr. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Waterbor </PERSON>. `` The death rate we found was 94 percent of that expected.'' The researchers said the findings support the idea that getting plenty of exercise and being in good physical shape early in life help keep folks healthy as they age. The report found that infielders had the lowest death rate, while catchers had the highest. Pitchers and outfielders were in between. <PERSON> Waterbor </PERSON> said the men's body builds may help explain these differences. `` The infielders tend to be average-looking to thin people who can move quickly, compared to catchers, who are built more like bricks,'' <PERSON> Waterbor </PERSON> said in an interview. The study also found that those who had lengthy playing careers or good records lived the longest, although these differences were small. The study, published in today's <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> England </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION>, was based on 985 men who played major-league ball between 1911 and 1915. Their longevity and causes of death were compared to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> white male population of the same age. Among other findings: _ By far the most common cause of death was heart disease The researchers were surprised to find that the death rate from the disease was 10 percent higher for ball players than for average American men. _ Baseball players were also somewhat more likely than other people to die from cancer But they were substantially less apt to die from infections, lung disease, diabetes and accidents, among other things. _ Catchers were more likely than usual to die from pancreatic cancer, pitchers from <PERSON> Hodgkin </PERSON>'s disease and outfielders from digestive ulcers _ The researchers successfully followed up on 958 players, of whom 16 were still alive in 1984 The average age of death was just under 71.
</TEXT>
