<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Four of the <ORGANIZATION> Golden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION>'s five top priests and about 30 followers were arrested today when police blocked their attempted march on the Sikh shrine which was ringed by government security forces. Among those arrested was head Sikh priest <PERSON> Jasbir </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> <PERSON> Rode </PERSON>. His talks Wednesday with government officials to try to end the four-day confrontation at the 400-year-old temple were inconclusive. Two Sikh militants were killed this afternoon in a heavy exchange of fire with security forces on the temple's perimeter, police said. A third was seriously injured. The deaths raised to at least 14 the number of people killed since shooting broke out Monday at the temple, <LOCATION> Sikhism </LOCATION>'s holiest shrine. Eleven others have been injured. Rode has called for the estimated 100 Sikh extremists inside the temple complex to dismantle their bunkers and for the 2,500 police and paramilitary forces ringing the shrine to withdraw. The priest and his followers were arrested at another Sikh shrine about a third of a mile north of the <LOCATION> Golden </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Temple </LOCATION> as they were about to start marching in defiance of a police ban. Deputy Police Commissioner <PERSON> Sarbjeet </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> asked the group to call off the march because two bursts of gunfire inside the temple were reported this morning after an overnight lull. <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> Police Chief K.P.S. <PERSON> Gill </PERSON> told a news conference that there were no plans to end the siege. Asked where it was leading, <PERSON> Gill </PERSON> said: `` We are waiting to see how the situation develops.'' `` We want the militants to stop firing so that normalcy can be restored,'' he added. `` We take responsibility for any firing from inside the temple,'' Rode responded. `` You take responsibility for firing from outside.'' Sikh militants placed a medium-sized machine gun atop a tower inside the complex and were in a position to fire down on anyone in the area. The Sikhs have also built fortifications on the northern edge of the complex, from which police Tuesday evacuated 800 pilgrims to keep them out of the crossfire. All shops and businesses in the old, walled sector of <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION> which surrounds the temple remained shuttered today and people stayed off the streets as a police-imposed curfew entered its fourth day. State-run <ORGANIZATION> All </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> said the government was trying to ensure that milk and other supplies reach civilians in curfew-bound areas. Police had hoped to lift the curfew Wednesday, but the effort failed. The temple complex covers an area equivalent to more than five city blocks, and includes offices, hostels and dining halls. The Sikhs, whose religion was founded about 500 years ago as an alternative to <LOCATION> Hinduism </LOCATION> and Islam, claim they are discriminated against by <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s majority Hindus. Sikh militants have been waging a guerrilla campaign since 1983 for more autonomy for an independent homeland in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> state. Sikhs make up less than two percent of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s 800 million people and <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> is the only state where they are a majority. More than 940 people have been killed this year in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> in attacks blamed on the extremists. Most have been Hindus or moderate Sikhs opposed to the separatist campaign. The Indian army was sent into the Golden Temple complex in June 1984 to drive Sikh extremists from the shrine. More than 1,200 people were killed in the attack, including <PERSON> Jarnail </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> <PERSON> Bhindranwale </PERSON>, a militant Sikh preacher. Later that year, Prime Minister <PERSON> Indira </PERSON> <PERSON> Gand