<HEAD>Fighting Stops Between Shiite Factions In South Beirut</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with woman killed today, other
details. Pick up 6th graf pvs: `The final...' Edits thereafter to
trim.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After six days of fighting, guns fell silent in south <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s slums today as rival Shiite Moslem militias observed a cease-fire arranged by the presidents of <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. Police said the Iranian-backed <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION>, or Party of God, controlled 70 percent of the 16-square-mile slums before the cease-fire went into effect at 11 p.m. -LRB- 5 p.m. EDT -RRB- Wednesday. Tension remained high in the slums as both sides, armed in their positions, exchanged occasional sniper and machine-gun fire. One woman was killed by a sniper's bullet in the <LOCATION> Ghobeiri </LOCATION> district today. Police said 33 people were killed and 160 wounded Wednesday before the truce began. The overall toll from nearly a week of violence was 188 killed and 532 wounded. A police spokesman said the Syrian-backed Amal, Arabic for hope, had lost most of its positions in south <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s narrow alleys and redeployed its militiamen along the disputed terrain's southern, western and northern edges. `` Amal controls all the gateways to south <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> controls most of the area from inside,'' said the spokesman, who by regulation can not be identified. Reporters who toured the embattled slums saw Amal militiamen at those positions in south <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> fighters, in light green fatigues and green headbands, controlled most of the area from inside. Bullet scars appeared on nearly every building in the area. Smoke billowed from several shell-pocked apartment blocks and shops that were hit during Wednesday's battles. Several Amal jeeps were seen destroyed along the side roads of districts under <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION>'s control. Dozens of cars were damaged. Several others were burned beyond recognition. Glass shards and rubble littered the dusty streets and alleys of the embattled slums. Iranian flags rose from at least 15 Amal positions overrun by <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION>. The `` final cease-fire'' was ordered by President <PERSON> Hafez </PERSON> <PERSON> Assad </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> and his Iranian counterpart, <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Khamenei </PERSON>, after telephone consultations late Wednesday evening. The two presidents also set up a four-man committee to supervise implementation of the accord. The committee groups <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s deputy foreign minister, <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheikholeslam </PERSON>; the head of Syrian military intelligence in west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, Brig. Gen. <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Hammoud </PERSON>; <PERSON> Ayoub </PERSON> <PERSON> Homeyed </PERSON> of Amal; and <PERSON> Hassan </PERSON> <PERSON> Khalil </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION>. Four observer teams formed by the committee entered south <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> early today to supervise evacuation of the wounded from both rival factions, the police spokesman said. He said a convoy of about 10 ambulances from the <ORGANIZATION> Lebanese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> also drove across Amal lines into the bomb-scarred slums to evacuate the wounded. However, the evacuation was delayed because `` at the last minute <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> demanded guarantees that its wounded will be safe in hospitals of west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> outside its area of influence,'' the spokesman said. He said `` the Syrians agreed to guarantee safety of wounded Hezbollahis.'' At the height of the fighting, doctors said militiamen forced surgeons at a hospital to operate at gunpoint, and that there were gunbattles inside the hospital. <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> deployed 7,500 troops in west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> 14 months ago after a month of bloody clashes between Justice Minister <PERSON> Nabih </PERSON> <PERSON> Berri </PERSON>'s Amal and the militia of Druse warlord <PERSON> Walid </PERSON> <PERSON> Jumblatt </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Progressive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. The Syrians, however, did not deploy in south <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, a traditional stronghold for Iranian-backed underground factions holding most of the 18 foreign hostages. The truce was reached after <ORGANIZATION> Amal </ORGANIZATION> lost most of south <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> to the pro-Iranian radicals. The truce calls for withdrawal of all militiamen from the streets of the southern suburbs this afternoon. `` The withdrawal will be the big test,'' the police spokesman said. Four previous cease-fire accords have collapsed due to <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION>'s refusal to withdraw to positions it held before the confrontation broke out Friday. An Amal official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said his militia `` insists on returning to the districts we controlled before the clashes started.'' He refused to say whether <ORGANIZATION> Amal </ORGANIZATION> would try to regain its lost positions by force if <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> refuses to withdraw.
