<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s call to white Democratic legislators who benefited from black votes to back him for the presidential nomination has failed to attract much support from those who count at the national convention. Since the days leading up to the Super Tuesday primaries on March 8, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> ha said that white Democratic legislators, especially those in the South who were elected with a major share of the black vote, should be willing to support him based on that basis. He recently renewed that call and added a new twist _ <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> named names. `` It's reasonable to expect that Sen. -LRB- <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> -RRB- <PERSON> Sanford </PERSON> will endorse my campaign. That's a reasonable expectation,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said during an appearance in <LOCATION> Greensboro </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sanford </LOCATION>, who was elected to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> in 1986, is one of the unpledged public officeholders who will attend the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Convention </ORGANIZATION> as a `` super delegate.'' Earlier in the campaign, <PERSON> Sanford </PERSON> backed <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, who captured <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> on Super Tuesday. In the wake of <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>'s decision to suspend his campaign, <PERSON> Sanford </PERSON> moved into the uncommitted ranks. `` He wants to enjoy his uncommitted status for a little bit,'' said <PERSON> Sanford </PERSON>'s spokesman, <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawton </PERSON>. <PERSON> Sanford </PERSON> chose not to comment on <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s call for his support, <PERSON> Lawton </PERSON> said. Back in 1986, when <PERSON> Sanford </PERSON> sought the Democratic nomination for the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> seat, he did not have the backing of <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Kinney </PERSON>, a black candidate seeking the Democratic nod, picked up <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s endorsement instead. <PERSON> Kinney </PERSON> `` was not a serious candidate by any stretch of the imagination,'' said <PERSON> Merle </PERSON> <PERSON> Black </PERSON>, a political science professor at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carolina </ORGANIZATION>. In the general election, <PERSON> Sanford </PERSON> edged <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Broyhill </PERSON>, 52 percent to 48 percent, with a major share of the black vote and nearly half of the white vote _ about 45 percent. `` By the early'70s, the late'60s, the percentage of white votes began dropping precipitously,'' said <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Sabato </PERSON>, a political science professor at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION>. `` Democrats do n't need a majority -LRB- to win the election -RRB- thanks to the black vote, but they need a healthy slice of the white vote.'' <PERSON> Black </PERSON> says that in the South the white vote has become the swing vote. `` The Achilles heel for Republicans is they get little support from blacks so they have to get a landslide of whites. The Republicans need a landslide to make it close,'' he said. The ability to capture a large share of the white swing vote, combined with strong black support, made the difference for a number of Southern senators elected in 1986. Wyche <PERSON> Fowler </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> has been elected for nine years to represent the black majority fifth congressional district in his state. In the general election, <PERSON> Fowler </PERSON> won his old district by nearly a 2-to-1 margin but he also won the support of 4-out-of-10 white voters. <PERSON> Fowler </PERSON>, who also is a super delegate, remains uncommitted. <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> Senator <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Breaux </PERSON> did well in the Cajun parishes but also carried or finished even in the white Baptist parishes for his 1986 victory. <PERSON> Breaux </PERSON> also remains uncommitted. Not only did these candidates target the white swing vote, but they had to battle the staunch white voters who refuse to support a candidate who has the backing of black voters, according to pollster <PERSON> Natalie </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>. `` It's hard to document but about one-fifth of the typically Democratic voters will not back a candidate with black voters,'' Ms. <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> said. `` Democrats are caught perenially between a rock and a hard place.'' Some of these Southern senators who managed to capture both the black vote and a large enough share of the white vote have decided not to endorse a presidential candidate before the Democratic National Convention in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, July 18-21. In fact, 11 of the 12 Southern senators who will be attending the convention as super delegates have chosen the uncommitted ranks. Only <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> remains steadfast in his support of <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> has also hinted that his supporters might stay away from the polls in November if they perceived that he was being treated unfairly. `` We define our friends by their willingness to be fair and to be just,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said. `` One thing about politics, it does not go up and down. It goes round and round. Anything that goes around comes around.'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s indication of possible party problems in the general election presents a real dilemma for Democrats, who are treading carefully on the issue. `` If <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> is not treated well, there could be a low turnout for the ticket,'' <PERSON> Black </PERSON> said. `` If it's not as high, they need a larger share of the white vote.''
