<SECOND>PM-Chemical Weapons-Safety,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panel Finds Safety Lacking in Biological Weapons Research</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Pentagon has `` serious deficiencies'' in the way it manages the safety of its research programs into chemical and biological warfare, a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee's staff report maintains. The review found `` inadequate regulations, lax safety enforcement and documented safety lapses,'' said the report by the majority staff of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Governmental Affairs oversight subcommittee. The study, released Wednesday, noted that it did not examine `` the current safety practices of particular facilities conducting ... research. Nor does it reach final conclusions as to whether ... research is being conducted in a safe manner.'' <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> Maj. <PERSON> Randy </PERSON> <PERSON> Morger </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, said today that <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officials had n't seen the report. `` We need to look at it carefully, but we're greatly concerned when there are questions from any corner about possible safety issues in programs overseen by the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION>.'' The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> recently began building new chemical weapons, after halting the program in 1969. The nation produces no germ weapons and has unilaterally renounced the use of biological weapons, but does conduct research into chemical weapons that might be used against American troops. Sen. <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Levin </PERSON>, D-Mich., chairman of the subcommittee, said he plans to hold hearings later this year to discuss the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s safety practices in the two research The study noted that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> spending on the programs has increased sharply during President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s two terms, from about $ 63 million in 1980 to $ 348 million in 1986. The number of laboratories involved in research has also increased, the study found. There are about 150 labs doing Pentagon-sponsored research in chemical and germ weapons. The subcommittee staff said it was `` unable to locate a comprehensive safety program ..., that is, a readily identifiable set of safety regulations and an office with overall safety responsibilities. In the biological weapons area, the review found that `` there is no comprehensive set of safety regulations for research'' with biological warfare agents and toxins, `` no emphasis on safety in the contractor program and no office that monitors contractor safety.'' For chemical weapons, the approach is better, although it also `` appears to have major shortcomings,'' the study said. The military has a wide number of safety steps, but many are violated, the study said.
