<BYLINE>By MARY FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A fire that gutted the top floor of the building where the <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Purchase </LOCATION> was signed in 1803 was apparently touched off by workers doing repair work, a fire official said today. Wednesday's fire, which raged out of control for two hours, destroyed or damaged priceless artifacts and threatened the nation's oldest Roman Catholic cathedral next door. The blaze destroyed 18th century French furniture stored in the upper floor and consumed the cupola atop the three-story Cabildo, a Spanish-style gray stucco building with a slate roof, officials said. No injuries were reported. Fire Chief <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> McCrossen </PERSON> said today that workers repairing the roof and waterproofing the stucco walls apparently touched off the fire. `` We think it's tied up to the restoration,'' he said. There was speculation that a soldering iron, used in repairing metal flashing, touched off timbers that originally came down the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> as flatboats. The mansard roof and the top floor were added in 1847 using timbers salvaged from the river barges. `` There's all the cultural heritage of <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> in that building. It makes me want to cry,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sefcik </PERSON>, museum director of the 193-year-old landmark in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>' French Quarter. Smoke and water stained and soaked contents of the first and second floors, where paintings, tapestries, doll and fan collections, <PERSON> Mardi </PERSON> <PERSON> Gras </PERSON> memorabilia, pottery and other items were on display, officials said. `` Next to Independence Hall in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, this is the most historic building in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> architect who renovated the Cabildo's interior 20 years ago. The cause of the fire remained uncertain, but <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said the building remained structurally sound and could be repaired. An estimate of damages was not immediately available. The building alone was assessed at $ 50 million and is insured, said <PERSON> Sefcik </PERSON>. `` Every painting, every artifact suffered some water or smoke damage,'' <PERSON> Sefcik </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> signed the <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Purchase </LOCATION> inside the three-story building in 1803. It also was the repository for a death mask of <PERSON> Napoleon </PERSON> and other priceless antiques and artifacts. The bronze death mask was saved. The Marquis de Lafayette stayed at the Cabildo as a guest, and <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Lafitte </PERSON>, brother of the notorious buccaneer <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Lafitte </PERSON>, was jailed there for smuggling. Firefighters managed to keep the flames from spreading to the adjacent <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cathedral </LOCATION>, which remained undamaged except for some melted copper on the outside. Built in 1794, <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cathedral </LOCATION> is the oldest active Roman Catholic cathedral in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> celebrated Mass there when he visited <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> last September. The Cabildo was built a year later and served as the seat of <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> territorial government for <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, the Confederacy and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The building, which has been used as a 