<TEXT>
 Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> has appointed Prince <PERSON> Sadruddin </PERSON> <PERSON> Aga </PERSON> <PERSON> Khan </PERSON> to coordinate the international relief effort for the return of Afghan refugees under an accord signed in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Sadruddin </PERSON>, appointed Tuesday, is the son of the late <PERSON> Aga </PERSON> <PERSON> Kahn </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> and uncle of the current Aga Khan IV. The <PERSON> Aga </PERSON> <PERSON> Khan </PERSON> is spiritual leader of the world's 15 million Ismaili Moslems. <PERSON> Sadruddin </PERSON>, 55, was <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> High Commissioner for Refugees from 1965 to 1977. He will hold the rank of under secretary-general. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> has not divulged details of the massive program which he will oversee. His salary was not reported. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> mediated an agreement between <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> providing for the nine-month withdrawal of 115,000 Soviet troops from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> beginning Sunday. It also provides for the return of 5 million Afghan refugees, 3 million of them in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and 2 million in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Sadruddin </PERSON> was born in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> to a family known for formidable wealth and philanthropy. He is of Iranian origin and lives in <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Sadruddin </PERSON> <PERSON> Khan </PERSON> was graduated from <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in 1954 and did postgraduate work at the <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Middle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> until 1957. In 1958 he was a special consultant to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Educational </ORGANIZATION>, Social and Cultural Organization -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> UNESCO </ORGANIZATION> -RRB-. He was active in the preservation of Nubian monuments. As commissioner for refugees, <PERSON> Sadruddin </PERSON> oversaw operations to help displaced persons in <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Uganda </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>. Since 1983 he has been co-chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Humanitarian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Issues </ORGANIZATION>.
