<HEAD>Communist Leadership Offers Resignation Over Poor Investments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HELSINKI, Finland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The entire 11-member politburo of <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> offered to resign after the party treasury lost an estimated $ 2.25 million last year in poor investments, the media reported Thursday. The politburo, led by party chairman <PERSON> Arvo </PERSON> <PERSON> Aalto </PERSON>, offered its resignation at its meeting Wednesday. It will be considered at the party's <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> meetng later this month. The <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> was not expected to accept all of the resignations. The Independent <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION> daily <ORGANIZATION> Helsingin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sanomat </ORGANIZATION> said in an editorial that there was `` no reason to feel malicious pleasure outside the party.'' <PERSON> Aalto </PERSON> was not available for comment Wednesday or Thursday. The failed foray into the investment market meant a further loss of face for the party after a steady loss of voter support over the past 10 years. Internal quarrels led to a party split before last year's parliamentary elections. In 1958, the party had 50 seats in the 200-seat parliament. In the 1987 election, the two Communist factions won a total of 20 seats.
