<FIRST>r i AM-WHO-Polio     05-12 0337</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-WHO-Polio,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Agency Launches Effort To Root Out Polio By Year 2000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday endorsed a massive immunization campaign to protect all children against polio and eradicate the crippling disease by the year 2000. Only half the world's children are immunized, and 275,000 new cases of polio occur each year, mainly in developing countries, according to WHO. A committee of the 166-nation <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> agency passed by consensus a resolution calling for the eradication program. Approval by <ORGANIZATION> WHO </ORGANIZATION>'s full assembly is expected Friday at the final session of the agency's annual meeting Polio is the major disease with the best chance of being stamped out, the resolution said. It asked <ORGANIZATION> WHO </ORGANIZATION>'s director general to seek funds needed for the campaign and urged all countries to step up surveillance to permit quick identification of outbreaks. Eradication is expected to require doubling the $ 500 million the organization spends each year on immunization programs against six major childhood diseases in the Third World, including polio. The others are measles, diphtheria, whooping cough, tetanus and tuberculosis. About 10 million people worldwide have been crippled by polio, and one patient in 10 dies of the disease, <ORGANIZATION> WHO </ORGANIZATION> said. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> has reported the most cases of polio in recent years _ 14,629 in 1986. <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> reported 1,843 cases, <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> 1,600, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> 1,537, <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION> 810 and <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> 665. WHO estimates that only one case in 10 is reported to its headquarters in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> Eliminating polio will be `` an appropriate gift, together with the eradication of smallpox'' to the next century, the resolution said. <ORGANIZATION> WHO </ORGANIZATION> led a global drive that eradicated smallpox by the late 1970s. Polio became rare in developed countries after <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> scientists developed two vaccines in the 1950s. WHO expects to eliminate the polio virus from the <LOCATION> Americas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> by 1990. The organization says it costs $ 10 to immunize a child against polio and other major diseases, although the cost can be higher to reach children in remote areas.
</TEXT>
