<HEAD>NIH To Shift Gears In Funding On Artificial Heart Research</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 13th graf, ``So far xxx, to CORRECT that devices have
been used for only a few weeks, not that patients have lived for
only a few weeks</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> will stop funding artificial heart research and will focus instead on smaller devices intended to assist rather than replace hearts, according to a report published today. `` While the -LRB- artificial heart -RRB- device seemed to work well, the biology did n't work,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Lenfant </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Heart </ORGANIZATION>, Lung and <ORGANIZATION> Blood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>. `` The human body just could n't seem to tolerate it. We were left wondering whether the idea of a permanent replacement will ever work,'' <PERSON> Lenfant </PERSON> said in an interview published in The Atlanta Constitution and The <ORGANIZATION> Atlanta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION>. The decision means four institutions awarded contracts last year for artificial heart research will receive only about $ 1 million of the $ 5 million each was expecting over the next five years. `` This is a tremendous setback for scientific advancement in the field,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Olsen </PERSON>, head of artificial heart research at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utah </ORGANIZATION>, which had received one of the contracts. He said the decision will set back development of a permanent artificial heart for more than 10 years. `` This does not mean the end of the artificial heart program. It means we are taking a different approach. It may take somewhat longer, but it may also help us develop a device that works better,'' <PERSON> Lenfant </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Barney </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> became the first recipient of an artificial heart Dec. 2, 1982, in surgery performed at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utah </ORGANIZATION> by Dr. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> DeVries </PERSON>. He died the following March. Four other patients have received permanent artificial hearts, three at <ORGANIZATION> Humana-Audubon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Louisville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>, where <PERSON> DeVries </PERSON> now works, and one in <LOCATION> Stockholm </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Schroeder </PERSON> was the longest survivor, living almost two years with the Jarvik-7 artificial heart. All of the patients, however, suffered severe complications, including strokes and major infections. <PERSON> Lenfant </PERSON> said reports about those problems were one reason the government decided to withdraw support for continued development. Instead, the agency will focus its funding on smaller ventricular assist devices as stopgap measures for patients awaiting a transplanted human heart, he said. `` We believe it is time to try them in patients who need long-term support,'' <PERSON> Lenfant </PERSON> said. So far such `` bridge'' devices have been been used only for a few weeks. <PERSON> Lenfant </PERSON> said the government wants to see if they will work for three or four years at a time. The newspapers said the <ORGANIZATION> NIH </ORGANIZATION> decision would be officially announced next week.
