<HEAD>Forest Service Asks Power to Pursue Growers Off Its Land</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> officials asked <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> today for `` hot pursuit'' authority against heavily armed marijuana growers who forced the closure of 886,000 acres of national forest land last year as unsafe for tourists and timber interests. Deputy <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> told a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> hearing that his 150 law enforcement agents need statutory authority to pursue fleeing marijuana farmers beyond the boundaries of national forests and grasslands, especially in the <LOCATION> Far </LOCATION> <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>, where the problem is most acute. His request was endorsed by <PERSON> Sens </PERSON>. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Harkin </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Iowa </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Wyche </PERSON> <PERSON> Fowler </PERSON>, D-Ga., who said `` these marijuana gardens are protected by a Marquis de Sade torture chamber of devices intended to maim, cripple or kill intruders. Rep. <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyden </PERSON>, D-Ore., testifying at a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> agriculture subcommittee hearing, said illicit marijuana cultivation `` is a problem of staggering proportions'' in the West <PERSON> Wyden </PERSON> is chief sponsor of a bill that would grant <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> agents authority to conduct investigations, searches, seizures and arrests outside the boundaries of national forests if drug crimes originate there. He said the agents are `` hamstrung'' under current law because `` they are authorized to go after these criminals, but only as long as they remain within the boundaries of the federal forests.'' <PERSON> Wyden </PERSON> also proposed to stiffen federal penalties for unauthorized use of chemical herbicides and fertilizers in national forests, and to increase the maximum penalties for marijuana cultivation on those lands, which total 191 million acres in 44 states, <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Virgin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Packwood </PERSON>, a special agent in the <ORGANIZATION> Trinity-Shasta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, blamed the lack of `` hot pursuit'' authority on the poor success rate in prosecuting marijuana growers, who have an estimated $ 14 billion in annual profits. In 1986, <PERSON> Packwood </PERSON> said, 70 percent of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s 872 arrests for illegal marijuana farming went unprosecuted because of hampered investigations. `` Law enforcement has failed to establish a deterrent to cultivation activity and has become in the eyes of the grower just another business expense,'' <PERSON> Packwood </PERSON> said. The subcommittee, chaired by <PERSON> Harkins </PERSON>, heard testimony that marijuana growers are using a wide variety of sophisticated weapons to guard their farming plots in national forests, including attack dogs who get their commands from radios mounted on their collars. <PERSON> Wyden </PERSON> said that during a raid on a drug lab near a national forest in southern <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Josephine </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> sheriff `` seized a cache of weapons that could outfit a small army,'' including 51 machine guns, semi-automatic rifles and other automatic weapons, 100,000 rounds of ammunition and 150 pounds of gunpower.
