<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Some of the time-consuming paperwork will be shaved from appeals resulting from <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> decisions involving wildfires and other natural disasters, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said today. <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> Chief F. <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> said a newly adopted interim rule primarily concerns future natural disasters in the national forests. However, he said the agency also `` needs to speed up appeal procedures for recovery and rehabilitation activities that resulted from 1987's severe fire season in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>. It was this natural disaster that brought to our attention the need for special appeal procedures.'' Under the interim rule adopted today, anyone may appeal decisions on recovery and rehabilitation activities that result from natural disasters, such as wildfires, flooding, earthquakes and high winds, he said. Those who appeal will be entitled to a `` one-level appeal process'' which must be completed within 90 days, <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> said. Previously, appeal processes could be reviewed at two administrative levels. An estimated 2.2 billion board feet of national forest timber were destroyed or damaged in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> in the 1987 fire season, with about 40 percent of that volume offered for sale, he said. `` A delay in fire-caused salvage sales and related rehabilitation activities in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> could result in unnecessary losses of valuable natural resources,'' <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> said. The fires disrupted the timber sale programs of several national forests, he said. As a result, the economies of timber-dependent communities in the burned areas could suffer from delays in salvage and rehabilitation work.
