<HEAD>Dukakis Strong in California, But Demographics Good for Jackson</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Democrats are likely to go for the favorite next month, abandoning their longtime penchant for backing underdogs in presidential primaries, pollsters say. But the tradition may not succumb without a fight. <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is substantially ahead of <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> in opinion polls, most recently in a Gallup survey this week giving <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> 67 percent to 26 percent for <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and 7 percent undecided. But if <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is the heavy favorite to win, pollsters said in recent interviews, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> still may do better than his recent finishes, perhaps well enough to boost his influence at the party's convention in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> `` I would be extremely surprised if <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> got over 40 percent,'' said I.A. <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>, chief of polling for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>. While that strong a showing is by no means assured, pollsters say there are several reasons <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> could do well in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> on June 7. One is demographics: Many of the voters fit the profile of <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> supporters. Another is history: <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, who has found support from whites elusive, did his best on that score in his 1984 campaign with <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> whites. Yet another factor is a decreased expectation that <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> can win the nomination. Several analysts said dissatisfied Democrats may be more likely to cast a protest vote for <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> when it appears he can not actually win. `` When you do n't think <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> is a viable nominee he gets a better vote than when you do,'' said <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>. He noted that <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s support from whites fell off after the <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> primary, when he looked strong But after losing a series of landslides, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> got 24 percent of the white vote in <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> this week, his second-best showing among whites all year. Given the liberalism of many <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Democrats, `` there's a number of people that would like to give him bargaining chips in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> by his showing well here _ people who may not want him to be president but want to give him some clout,'' <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> said. Any added clout from second place would stem from vote totals rather than the delegate count; the primary is a winner-take-all contest, with delegates awarded only to the first-place finisher in each congressional district. Pollsters stressed that a victory by <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> would be exceedingly difficult, even with his plans to campaign heavily in the state. Blacks, who have been giving him support in the 90-percent range, made up only about 15 percent of the primary electorate in 1984, and <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> has not increased blacks' share of the vote in most other states. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> in 1984 won four of the state's 45 congressional districts and received 21 percent of the vote statewide. `` Conventional wisdom is that <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> should do better than four years ago, but not dramatically,'' said California-based pollster <PERSON> Mervin </PERSON> <PERSON> Field </PERSON>. He said <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> may be hurt by his recent losses while <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is fueled by his run of wins. Still, <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> noted that <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> have a history of backing the anti-establishment candidate. <LOCATION> Califor