<HEAD>Pothole Settlement Costs Dallas Nearly $1 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A potholed street has cost <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> almost $ 1 million in a settlement that nearly wiped out its litigation reserve fund, officials said. City Council approved, by a 5-2 vote Wednesday, a $ 969,000 settlement with a man whose wife was killed three years ago by a motorist who swerved after hitting a pothole. In a suit in state district court, the family of <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Glennie </PERSON> <PERSON> Mayer </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Rowlett </LOCATION> had sought $ 2.4 million from the city for failing to fill the pothole, which was about 8 inches deep and 3 feet across. The suit contended the city had been negligent because it failed to properly maintain the street despite a complaint filed with the Streets and <ORGANIZATION> Sanitation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. City Attorney <PERSON> Analeslie </PERSON> <PERSON> Muncy </PERSON> said the city's litigation fund has `` just a little'' more than $ 1 million, which must last until Sept. 30, the end of the fiscal year. In 1985, there was no state limit on death claims resulting from faulty street maintenance. The state's 1987 tort reform law set a $ 250,000 limit. The lawsuit, filed by <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mayer </PERSON>, stems from a Nov. 18, 1985, accident that killed Mrs. <PERSON> Mayer </PERSON>, 48. Under <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> law, a city may be held liable for an accident caused by a pothole only if a complaint has been filed and there was time for crews to fill it.
