<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The defense ended its closing arguments today in the cocaine-smuggling trial of <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON> <PERSON> Rivas </PERSON>, ridiculing prosecutors for trying to make the Colombian appear responsible for the nation's drug problem. `` If that is true, you could lock up the doors to this courthouse and tear down all the ` Just Say No,' signs,'' defense attorney <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Shohat </PERSON> said, referring to a national anti-drug week campaign. <PERSON> Shohat </PERSON> urged the jury to make an independent judgment about the charges against <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON>, saying `` The government does not own the jury _ noboby owns the jury.'' Counsel for Lender's co-defendant, <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlton </PERSON> <PERSON> Reed </PERSON>, also was expected to finish his closing arguments today, followed by a rebuttal from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Merkle </PERSON>. The case was scheduled to go to the jury Friday. <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON>, 38, and <PERSON> Reed </PERSON>, 57, of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pedro </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, are charged with conspiring to smuggle about 3.3 tons of cocaine into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> via <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON>'s private Bahamian island, <PERSON> Norman </PERSON>'s Cay, from 1978 to 1980 A separate <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> indictment accuses <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON> of being one of the leaders of the so-called <LOCATION> Medellin </LOCATION> cartel, a violent Colombian smuggling ring believed to be responsible for a major portion of the cocaine entering the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Shohat </PERSON> spent this morning hammering again at what he said were inconsistencies in the testimony of government witnesses, many of whom were admitted smugglers given immun