<HEAD>The Archtraitor is Dead, but Questions Linger</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY18</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: INSERTS 2 grafs after 8th `His network' to include Anthony
Blunt, the ``fourth man''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> `` Kim'' <PERSON> Philby </PERSON> is dead, but the bitter aftertaste of his colossal betrayal still lingers in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. Even 25 years after the privileged English gentleman was unmasked as <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s highest-placed mole in Western intelligence, central questions remain unanswered: Were there others of higher rank? Were the operations of Western intelligence agencies compromised more seriously than they realize? When <PERSON> Philby </PERSON> gave his only interview to a Western journalist four months before he died, was it part of a new plot by his <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> masters to discredit the British and undermine their relationship with <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>? A tribute to <PERSON> Philby </PERSON> came Thursday, the day after he died at age 76, from <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, a former British intelligence officer. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> has done much to keep the scandal alive with his allegation that an even higher mole existed: the late Sir <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Hollis </PERSON>, who directed the MI5 security service from 1956 to 1965. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s claim is in his volume of memoirs, called `` Spycatcher,'' which is banned in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. In a statement from <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, where he now lives, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> called <PERSON> Philby </PERSON> `` an outstanding man in the intelligence world.'' <PERSON> Philby </PERSON> became a Soviet agent while at <ORGANIZATION> Cambridge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in the 1930s, joined the secret service and rose to high rank. He was believed to be in line to head MI6, the sister service of MI5. His network unraveled in 1951 with the defection of <PERSON> Guy </PERSON> <PERSON> Burgess </PERSON> and <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Maclean </PERSON> to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, but <PERSON> Philby </PERSON> escaped exposure for 12 more years. In 1963 he, too, defected. In 1964 the `` fourth man,'' <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Blunt </PERSON>, confessed he had worked for the Soviets while in MI5 and received immunity in exchange for information about the other three. His treason was kept secret and he eventually became art adviser to Queen <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>, receiving a knighthood. Blunt's past was made public in 1979 and he was stripped of his honors. He died in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> in 1983. The damage to <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> security, which shared secrets with <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, is incalculable. Now that all four of `` Stalin's Englishmen'' finally are dead, the suspicion persists that there were five <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s claim about <PERSON> Hollis </PERSON>, whether true or not, illustrates the doubt that still eats at the British security services because of <PERSON> Philby </PERSON>'s treachery. `` It's bad for morale, and it's actually bad for operations,'' said <PERSON> Rupert </PERSON> <PERSON> Allason </PERSON>, a Conservative member of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> and who writes histories and analyses of espionage under the name <PERSON> Nigel </PERSON> <PERSON> West </PERSON>. He said the suspicions mean intelligence analysts must ask themselves constantly whether the files they use contain `` tainted information'' left by the traitors. <PERSON> Philby </PERSON> still was a <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> officer when he died, and intelligence experts here believe the lengthy interview he gave in January to <PERSON> Phillip </PERSON> <PERSON> Knightley </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sunday </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> was a <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> operation. `` The Soviets had things in mind that they wanted to accomplish,'' said <PERSON> Miles </PERSON> <PERSON> Copeland </PERSON>, a retired <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> officer living in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Copeland </PERSON> and <PERSON> Allason </PERSON>, in separate interviews, said the purpose was to revive <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> suspicions of British intelligence generated by the <PERSON> Philby </PERSON> affair. They pointed to remarks by <PERSON> Philby </PERSON> to <PERSON> Knightley </PERSON> in which he hinted that other traitors remained in British intelligence and that the British could not be trusted to keep secrets. <PERSON> Allason </PERSON> said <PERSON> Philby </PERSON> had clearly hinted to <PERSON> Knightley </PERSON> that there were other moles, still undiscovered. He also saw hidden purpose in letting <PERSON> Knightley </PERSON> see how comfortable and privileged <PERSON> Philby </PERSON> was in his adopted homeland. `` It was a carrot to other people'' who might want to defect, <PERSON> Allason </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Copeland </PERSON> noted <PERSON> Philby </PERSON>'s recollection of a British intelligence official taking classified files with him when he retired. The traitor's aim, <PERSON> Copeland </PERSON> thinks, was to show once again that secret British files are not leakproof. Apart from all this is the question of what possessed this epitome of the English gentry to devote himself to communism and treachery. Author <PERSON> Malcolm </PERSON> <PERSON> Muggeridge </PERSON>, once a close friend, blamed the double agent's father <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Philby </PERSON>, the celebrated explorer and expert in Arabic. `` <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> could never be the towering figure his father was, so he compensated for it by defying him and all he stood for in the most appalling manner,'' <PERSON> Muggeridge </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION>. He called <PERSON> Philby </PERSON> `` a cad's cad.'' <PERSON> Allason </PERSON> called him `` a grotesquely unpleasant man who betrayed everyone he came in contact with, including his close friends and family.'' <PERSON> Philby </PERSON>, born in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and raised in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, wrote that he felt little conventional English patriotism. He said he embraced communism at <LOCATION> Cambridge </LOCATION> because <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> was not challenging German militarism, and communism alone seemed to offer resistance. An editorial in the conservative <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> said he deserved only contempt. `` The convention whereby the dead should be judged charitably demands suspension in the case of <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Philby </PERSON>,'' it said. `` He has died impenitent, glorying in his own treason.''
