<HEAD>Palestinian Children Attend Underground Schools</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TLV9</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BIR ZEIT, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soldiers closed Arab schools months ago, but children are back in class, reciting lessons in unfinished buildings, mosques and churches with the added spice of defying the Israeli occupiers. About 60 youngsters aged 6 to 12 study math, English, Arabic, history and geography in bedrooms of an incomplete villa on a rocky hillside _ peering out during the multiplication tables, as children do, at yellow flowers in the valley. Secret schools are different, and to many students an adventure. The children do not have to wear uniforms, classes are coeducational, and some children from private Moslem and Christian schools are studying together. The army closed all 820 <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> schools Feb. 2, sending home 300,000 elementary and secondary students. Schools in the <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> have been closed for days at a time, but the army has not shut down the entire system. Israeli officials said schools had become assembly points for the anti-Israeli rebellion that began Dec. 8 among the 1.5 million Palestinians of the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. Leaflets issued this week by the uprising's clandestine leadership urge more secret schools to get started. Those already operating include half a dozen in <LOCATION> Bir </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zeit </LOCATION>, 12 miles north of <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>. The underground schools symbolize the transformation of the 5-month-old revolt, which has claimed the lives of 186 Arabs and two Israelis. There is far less street violence now, but the air of defiance is little diminished. Teachers and students interviewed at the `` people's schools'' agreed that challenging <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s authority was a significant reason for organizing the classes. `` Because the Israelis closed the schools, we come here to show that we can break their rules,'' said <PERSON> Amjad </PERSON> <PERSON> Shibli </PERSON>, 16. His school `` uniform'' was brown jeans and yellow and black running shoes. <PERSON> Amjad </PERSON> was among about 75 teen-agers attending high school classes in an unfinished building behind the city hall. He said he had spent the past three months working in his father's cafe and sometimes joined other youths in throwing stones at <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> soldiers. Rocks intended to slow Israeli vehicles are scattered in streets leading to the makeshift high school. The pavement near another school had been blackened by bonfires of tires burned as protest barricades. The military government, known as the <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, closed four universities as well as the lower schools because many protests began on the campuses. `` Schools were closed because the children did n't want to study. They had become a place for disturbances and violence,'' said <PERSON> Olivier </PERSON> <PERSON> Rabovitch </PERSON>, a spokesman for army administration. He said protests had decreased dramatically in recent weeks and the schools might be allowed to reopen if the situation remained calm. An <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> teacher who identified himself only as Professor <PERSON> M. </PERSON> said: `` The Israelis have kept the schools closed as a general punishment of the population.'' He is a lecturer at the shuttered <ORGANIZATION> Bir </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Zeit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and organized most of the underground schools that opened here two weeks ago. Thirty-seven parents, university graduates and laid-off university teachers were recruited to conduct classes for several hundred volunteer students in <LOCATION> Bir </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zeit </LOCATION>, Professor <PERSON> M. </PERSON> said. He said regular teachers, who are <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> employees, refused to help because <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> authorities threatened to dismiss them. Professor M. acknowledged `` an element of challenge'' to the army in organizing the schools, but he and other teachers said their main concern was seeing that the children did not fall too far behind in their studies. Although many classes are coeducational, some Moslem families send their children to study in mosques, where boys attend in the morning and girls in the afternoon. At the unfinished villa on the hill, <PERSON> Assad </PERSON> <PERSON> Sayegh </PERSON>, a 26-year-old economics graduate of <ORGANIZATION> Bir </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Zeit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, was teaching math to 14 pupils aged aged 8 and 9 who sat in small chairs against the unpainted concrete walls. His blackboard and textbooks were spirited from the government school. <PERSON> Sayegh </PERSON> said the youngsters were taught the politics of the `` intefadeh,'' or uprising, but a reporter saw no evidence of indoctrination in the classes visited. `` The government wants to keep the Palestinian people empty-headed,'' <PERSON> Sayegh </PERSON> said. `` That way Palestinians ca n't make bombs or fly airplanes. They want all the knowledge for themselves so Palestinians ca n't destroy the Jewish government.''
