<FIRST>u w AM-PreventionIndex Bjt   05-12 0711</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Prevention Index, Bjt,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dip in Clean-Living Index Shows Need to Push Health Habits:
Experts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The first decline in an annual index of American health practices illustrates there is a big difference between people knowing they should eat right and exercise and actually doing it, authorities said Thursday. Dr. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> McGinnis </PERSON>, a federal health official, said the drop underscores the need for leaders `` to redouble our efforts to convince Americans that health promotion ideas are not a fad.'' Despite extensive publicity in recent years about the value of proper diet and exercise, the 1988 survey by Prevention magazine showed few gains in those areas, <PERSON> McGinnis </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prevention </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Promotion </ORGANIZATION>, noted. In particular, he told reporters it is `` an issue of some concern that we have n't seen improvement'' in the number of people who told pollsters they `` try a lot to avoid eating too much fat.'' Only 54 percent answered `` yes'' to that question, down from 56 percent in the 1987 report. The latest result also is down from the 55 percent who gave a `` yes'' response in polling done for the initial index in 1984. The overall 1988 Prevention Index stood at 64.8 out of a possible 100 _ down from 65.2 last year but 3.3 points above the first index in 1984. However, the overall gain from 1984 is due largely to sharp jumps in the number of people who have smoke detectors in their homes, a 15 percent jump; and the number who report wearing auto seatbelts, a 38 percent climb. <PERSON> McGinnis </PERSON> complimented the commercial magazine for compiling the index, noting that is the only survey that has tracked trends in 21 specific areas over a five-year period. `` One clear message from this year's survey is that the spread of good health habits is not automatic,'' said <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Dybdahl </PERSON>, director of the Prevention Index. `` People may know more than ever about good health, but they may not be acting on what they know. In key areas such as diet, exercise and weight control, there is still much room for improvement.'' For example, the number saying they are making efforts to limit high-cholesterol foods fell from 46 percent in the 1987 report to 42 percent this year, the same as it was in 1984. Compared with 1984, there was a two-percentage-point drop in the number who said they try to avoid too many sweets and three-point decline in the number who said they get seven or eight hours sleep most nights. Although up two points from the 1984 report, only 35 percent of Americans say they exercise strenuously three or more days a week and only 24 percent say they are at their proper weight, up one point from 1984. Seventy-two percent say they do not smoke, the same as last year and up two points from 1984. <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Louis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Harris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION>, which conducts the poll that forms the basis for the index, described the figures on diet and nutrition as `` amazingly flat'' from a statistical viewpoint. <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> said the lack of significant improvement in the diet and exercise portions of the five-year survey show a gap between `` lip service and good intentions'' and actual practice. Weight control is `` a truly dismal story,'' he said, noting that 76 percent of <LOCATION> Americans </LOCATION> think they are overweight. `` We remain the most obese country in the world,'' he said. <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> pollsters ask the same questions each year to give an accurate year-to-year comparison. The current year's report was based on telephone interviews conducted with 1,250 randomly selected adults Nov. 11-25 and has a 3 percent margin of error. <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> acknowledged that the typically small year-to-year changes registered in the survey often fall within the margin of error. However, he said the theoretical chance for error is largely overriden because consistent trends tracked over the five-year sampling period give added credence to the figures reported in any one year. The single-number Prevention Index itself is derived by assigning weights to each of the 21 survey questions and applying poll results to that relative value scale. For example, not smoking is assigned the highest ranking _ 9.78 on a scale of one to 10.
</TEXT>
