<HEAD>Transplant Tot Touched Many</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE DRESSLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Tabatha </PERSON> <PERSON> Foster </PERSON>, the chubby-cheeked tot who smiled despite adversity, won the hearts of many, and her supporters say her fight following a historic five-organ transplant reveals more about life and courage than about medicine. `` Through her, God touched the world,'' her uncle, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Foster </PERSON>, said Thursday. `` He said: ` Look, y' all think you got problems, well look at this girl Look what she has done.' It brought the highest and the lowest people together for just a minute.'' <PERSON> Tabatha </PERSON>, 3 -LCB-, of <LOCATION> Madisonville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>, died Wednesday afternoon in the intensive care unit of <ORGANIZATION> Children </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> after an infection in her bloodstream caused her heart, kidneys and liver to fail. The 36-pound, pigtailed child was the world's longest survivor of a five-organ transplant. She received a new liver, small intestines, pancreas and parts of a stomach and colon during a 15-hour experimental operation that ended Nov. 1. Similar procedures had been performed only twice before, and both patients died within a few days. `` You could n't help but love that little girl. So many of us learned so much from her and not just medically,'' said hospital spokeswoman <PERSON> Sue </PERSON> <PERSON> Cardillo </PERSON>. `` <PERSON> Tabatha </PERSON> was never down,'' she said. `` When people ask if the operation was a success, it's hard to measure success. It was a success because <PERSON> Tabatha </PERSON> lived six additional months and there were good times.'' Because of an intestinal deformity, doctors had been forced to remove 95 percent of <PERSON> Tabatha </PERSON>'s small bowel three days after she was born. She was placed on a highly concentrated liquid diet, which damaged her own liver. Doctors had said <PERSON> Tabatha </PERSON> would soon die without the transplant. She was hospitalized for all but seven weeks of her life and though she said she craved pizza, the only solid food she ever ate was rice cereal, Ms. <PERSON> Cardillo </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Tabatha </PERSON> won the affection of hospital staff with good-natured teasing, playing peek-a-boo and singing `` The Itsy-Bitsy Spider.'' She walked through hospital halls with an intravenous pole in tow, wearing her cherished tennis shoes and chatting with anyone. <PERSON> Tabatha </PERSON>'s hospital room was empty Thursday. The countless stuffed animals, `` tons and tons'' of cards and a photo of a puppy recently given to <PERSON> Tabatha </PERSON> have been packed in boxes, Ms. <PERSON> Cardillo </PERSON> said. `` I think it's affected everybody in the hospital from housekeeping on up. At every level heartstrings are being pulled,'' Ms. <PERSON> Cardillo </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Tabatha </PERSON>'s parents, <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Foster </PERSON>, quickly checked out of <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Ronald </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> McDonald </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, where they had stayed for months. Ms. <PERSON> Cardillo </PERSON> said they did not want their whereabouts known Thursday as they prepared to leave for home. Other family members gathered in <LOCATION> Madisonville </LOCATION>, waiting for the parents to join them and remembering <PERSON> Tabatha </PERSON>. `` She had those fat jaws and was always smiling,'' <PERSON> Foster </PERSON>, 33, said in a telephone interview. `` She was a survivor. She was a fighter.'' <PERSON> Tabatha </PERSON>'s aunt, <PERSON> Doris </PERSON> <PERSON> East </PERSON>, 41, of <LOCATION> Huntsville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>, said the child taught her to have faith. `` She taught me to endure because she did,'' she said. Ms. <PERSON> East </PERSON> said the family was grateful the tr