<HEAD>Plant Explosion Kills One, Injures Eight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHANIE NANO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An explosion spewed flaming metal chips throughout an industrial plant Thursday, killing one worker and injuring eight others, officials said. Businesses near the plant on the city's east side were evacuated while firefighters worked to keep flames from spreading to a warehouse containing powdered metals, including magnesium, titanium and aluminum. `` The dust collector blew up and spread these flaming metal chips and debris all over and started the fire,'' said Fire Chief <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> McNamee </PERSON>. Firefighters found one worker's body in the <ORGANIZATION> Mineral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Metals </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> plant after the fire was brought under control about noon, three hours after it was reported. The victim's identity was not immediately available. Plant secretary <PERSON> Denise </PERSON> <PERSON> Sobola </PERSON> said there were 29 people in the plant when the explosion occurred. The plant processes powdered metal into a substance for welding rod coatings, workers said. Ms. <PERSON> Sobola </PERSON> said her office filled with dust and she ran out a side door. She said workers were `` just running out and collapsing outside the doors.'' Ms. <PERSON> Sobola </PERSON> said there have been minor explosions at the plant in the past that have spread dust throughout the plant. `` I knew this time -LRB- it was worse -RRB-. I heard glass busting and everything,'' she said. <ORGANIZATION> Chemalloy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Bryn </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mawr </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, is the parent company of Mineral Metals. Chemalloy President <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Demos </PERSON> was en route to <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION> on Thursday and not available for comment, his office said. Six workers were treated at <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION> Metropolitan General Hospital for burns and smoke inhalation, said hospital spokeswoma