<FIRST>r a AM-YouthSuicide     05-12 0516</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Youth Suicide,0528</SECOND>
<HEAD>Depressed Youths Predisposed To Suicide, Study Shows</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For release 4 p.m. EDT.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCIA DUNN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Depressed teen-agers intent on killing themselves show chemical abnormalities in their brains that appear to predispose them to suicide, according to a study released Thursday. `` It clearly demonstrates some brain differences in suicidal adolescents. It's not purely a mind phenomenon,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Neal </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON>, assistant professor of psychiatry at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pittsburgh </ORGANIZATION>. Earlier studies have found similar abnormalities in the brains of suicidal adults, although experts are divided as to what conclusions can be drawn. <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON>'s research is believed to be the first that demonstrates neurochemical abnormalities in suicidal adolescents. `` What this suggests is that there is a biochemical basis to at least depressive people with chronic suicidal plans,'' <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> said. `` There's something that goes on with the brain and there are environmental phenomena that impinge on that.'' <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> said his findings, reported at the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Psychiatric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>'s annual conference in <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION>, could help doctors identify and treat certain patients before they try to commit suicide. <PERSON> Irma </PERSON> <PERSON> Lann </PERSON>, a science administrator in child and adolescent disorders research for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON>'s work is preliminary, and further study is needed. `` It's premature to even think that we could be able to identify groups of suicidal adolescents,'' she said. Of the 29,453 suicides in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 1985, the last year for which figures are available, 2,127 were committed by youngsters 19 and under, according to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statistics </ORGANIZATION>. About 80 percent of them were boys. Boys and girls are afflicted about equally by depression. But while more girls attempt suicide, more boys succeed at it, according to <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON>. <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> and Dr. <PERSON> Joaquim </PERSON> <PERSON> Puig-Antich </PERSON>, professor of psychiatry at <LOCATION> Pitt </LOCATION>, began their study in 1980 at the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Psychiatric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. They continued their work, funded by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION>, after moving in 1984 to <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Psychiatric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Clinic </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>. From 1980 to 1987, the psychiatrists monitored the growth hormone secretion of 140 boys and girls ranging in age from 12 to just under 18. The tests were conducted while the subjects slept. Most growth hormone secretion occurs during sleep, especially during the first several hours, according to <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON>. At least three neurotransmitter systems in the brain are involved in controlling sleep growth hormone secretion, which also affects moods. The 34 youngsters who suffered from major depression and had attempted suicide or devised a suicide plan secreted less growth hormone than the 40 depressed but non-suicidal students and 66 healthy children, whose levels were about the same, <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> said. The subjects' sex was not a factor, and their ages were taken into account. Later, 43 of the students received a one-time shot of Desipramine, an antidepressant known to stimulate the release of growth hormone. Among the eight depressed, suicidal youths who received the shot, less growth hormone was released than among the 12 depressed but non-suicidal and 23 healthy adolescents, <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> said.
