<TEXT>
 The federal government should direct its efforts to providing health care for the chronically ill, says the new president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Retired </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Persons </ORGANIZATION>. `` We contend that national legislation based on a social insurance approach is required so that the risk can be spread over millions of working and retired persons,'' said <PERSON> Louise </PERSON> <PERSON> Crooks </PERSON>, 76, who ascended to the presidency Wednesday during the biannual meeting of the 28 million-member association. `` We must find a way to assure adequate health care for the estimated 37 million Americans, who have no health care insurer whatsoever, and expand and improve private pension plans so that future generations of older Americans will have more adequate retirement income,'' the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lafayette </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ind. </LOCATION>, woman said. Among the health issues discussed at the convention was Alzheimer's disease, a form of dementia that afflicts about 2 million elderly Americans. The disease's cure and cause remains unknown. Dr. <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON>, director of the Program on Aging at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Bethesda </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, said the federal government is spending $ 90 million a year to research the disease, up from $ 4 million in 1974. `` Alzheimer's has emerged as one of the great mysteries of medical science,'' <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> said. The conference also looked at the needs of those who care for the elderly. Those people, mostly women, often are burdened by unrelenting demands and develop health problems of their own, said <