<FIRST>r a AM-SentencingCommission     05-12 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sentencing Commission,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Judge Declares U.S. Sentencing Commission Unconstitutional</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOBILE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge has declared unconstitutional a commission that sets federal sentencing guidelines, saying the president's authority to remove commission members violates the separation of powers between the executive and judiciary branches of government. Chief <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> W. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brevard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hand </ORGANIZATION> also threw out the sentencing guidelines themselves. Hand's ruling Wednesday on a motion in a cocaine case was similar to one issued by U.S. District Judge <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Shoob </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>; challenges to the guidelines also have been filed in other jurisdictions and many federal judges have criticized them. Under the commission's guidelines, federal judges must impose sentences within prescribed ranges unless special circumstances exist that are not adequately considered by the commission's rules. The guidelines, <ORGANIZATION> Hand </ORGANIZATION> said, substantially restrict the traditional discretion allowed judges in sentencing. Hand said the commission, created by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in 1984, improperly includes three federal judges. Members of the commission are appointed by the president and may be removed by him for neglect of duty, malfeasance in office or for other causes. `` Federal courts must carefully abstain from exercising any power that is not strictly judicial in its character, and which is not clearly confided by the Constitution,'' Hand ruled. He said the job of setting guidelines is essentially an administrative rule-making task, legislative in nature, and `` not a proper function of the judiciary.''
</TEXT>
