<HEAD>House Votes To Make Itself More Immune To Civil Suits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The House unanimously approved a resolution Thursday that asserts the right of its members to be immune from civil lawsuits when they issue news releases, hold news conferences or communicate with government officials. The 413-0 vote was triggered by a federal appeals court decision that limited lawmakers' immunity to activities such as speaking and voting on the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> or <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> floor. The resolution requested that the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> hear an appeal of the case, in which the need for a broader interpretation of immunity would be argued. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> expressed `` deep concern'' with the ruling `` because of its impact on the necessary and proper functioning of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Representatives </ORGANIZATION>.'' The dispute began in 1985 when Rep. <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Sundquist </PERSON>, R-Tenn., wrote to the attorney general and the president of the <ORGANIZATION> Legal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> about a controversy over expenditure of federal money by <ORGANIZATION> Memphis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Area </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> Sundquist </PERSON>, who released the letters to the news media, made a reference to a staff attorney for the <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION> group, who sued the lawmaker for defamation of character. In April 1986, a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> district judge in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> dismissed the suit on grounds that members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> are entitled to immunity while acting in good faith within the scope of their official duties. Last November, a panel of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGAN