<HEAD>Expert Testifies Train Crew Lacked Sleep Before Fatal Accident</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNE McGRAW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YORK, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Conrail </ORGANIZATION> crew members in a fatal train accident suffered from a lack of sleep and could have dozed off while still instinctively performing basic duties, an industrial psychologist testified Thursday. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tepas </PERSON>, professor of psychology and director of the industrial and organizational psychology program at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Connecticut </ORGANIZATION>, said the three crew members on each of the two trains suffered from `` chronic sleep deprivation.'' <PERSON> Tepas </PERSON> testified during the second day of a <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> hearing on the Jan. 14 train accident in <LOCATION> Thompsontown </LOCATION>, which killed four people. The two <ORGANIZATION> Conrail </ORGANIZATION> trains, one hauling coal and the other carrying trailer-vans, smashed head-on at about 8 a.m., killing the engineer and the brakeman on both trains and derailing all five locomotives. Damage was estimated at $ 5 million. <PERSON> Tepas </PERSON> said the rail employee's erratic work schedules; harsh, monotonous work environment; and a lack of programs to help employees deal with job stress promote sleeping on the job. `` Work systems which result in night work, shifts of unusual length and unpredictable work hours result in conditions which place workers and the general public at risk,'' he said in prepared testmony. Spokesmen for <ORGANIZATION> Conrail </ORGANIZATION>, a private freight rail organization set up by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to operate six bankrupt railroads, have said they would n't comment on any of the testimony. During his testimony, <PERSON> Tepas </PERSON> said workers on erratic schedules do not make up for lost sleep, nor do they adapt to those schedules. The same workers are not usually able to judge how their work has been affected while suffering from chronic sleep deprivation, he added. Though asleep, people can still react automatically in different situations, he said, adding that dozing rail workers could respond to danger signals as part of a natural reflex. `` In all stages of sleep, it is possible for people to perform simple responses to simple stimuli,'' <PERSON> Tepas </PERSON> said. `` People can sleep for a few seconds or minutes and can perform quite well when they wake up,'' he added. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> railroad companies must pay more attention to the consequences of sleep deprivation, <PERSON> Tepas </PERSON> said. Training employees who work unpredictable work schedules how to handle odd sleeping hours would help, as well as adding some kind of change to routine duties, he said. The accident apparently occurred when the westbound trailer train had been shifted to an eastbound track on the <ORGANIZATION> Conrail </ORGANIZATION> main line between <LOCATION> Harrisburg </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>. The eastbound coal train apparently ran a stop signal and smashed head-on into the trailer train. The two survivors of the accident both said Wednesday they had had only a few hours of sleep before they reported to duty the day of the wreck. <ORGANIZATION> Inquiry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kolstad </PERSON> said the inquiry board would not issue its report for several months. The hearings are scheduled to last through Friday.
