> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Welfare </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> said `` many positive changes'' had occurred as a result of the law. The Children's Defense Fund said that without the changes, `` the crises facing the child welfare system today would be even more overwhelming. Those and other groups said there remain serious problems ranging from patchwork services and inadequate federal funds to the increasingly disturbed children entering the foster care system as a result of unemployment, poverty, drug abuse, homelessness and family violence. <PERSON> Downey </PERSON> and <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> aimed their fire at the administration, contending officials are failing to penalize states no matter how bad their records are. `` As one of our witnesses told us, you'd have to work overtime to flunk your audit,'' <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said. He said the department is relying on a checklist filled out by states themselves, plus sample cases that do n't reflect the serious problems pinpointed by lawsuits and studies across the country. Those problems have included child abuse by foster parents, slipshod monitoring by authorities responsible for the child's future, and failure to refer children for adoption or return them to their families where that is appropriate <PERSON> Downey </PERSON> said a lawsuit in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> revealed that child welfare offices were being used as shelters and 1,000 children had been subjected to multiple one-night placements. He said a suicidal 12-year-old was sent to 17 placements in 28 working days. Despite this information, he said, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> is one of seven states that has not been audited since the law was enacted. <PERSON> Olson </PERSON> said she was not aware of the lawsuit, probably because the federal government is not a party to it. `` You are a party to it,'' <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> rejoined. `` You're paying the bill for the care of these children ... When states are out of compliance, they're not supposed to get the money. Somehow, that does n't happen.'' <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> and <PERSON> Downey </PERSON> also scored the administrators for failing to help states cope with soaring rates of homelessness, drug abuse and child abuse. They said thousands of children are in foster care because their parents are homeless or the social services their families need are unavailable.
