udience laughed. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> aides were hesitant to comment on the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> endorsement. All <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign manager <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Atwater </PERSON> would say was, `` That's behind us now. At the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> was mystified that his endorsement was viewed as anything less than whole-hearted. `` He is mortified,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. `` He thought the speech was terrific. He wrote it himself. He thought it was strong, a full endorsement of his vice president who he thinks incredibly highly of.''
