<HEAD>Fed Chairman Urges House To Pass Securities Underwriting Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> on Thursday urged the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> to follow the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s lead and pass major legislation to give banks new securities underwriting powers. <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> favored the approach taken by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, which in late March approved legislation that would repeal most restrictions of the Depression-era Glass-Steagall Act. That statute barred a mingling of the banking and securities industries. The 1933 law was one of the reforms passed following the 1929 stock market crash. It was aimed at curbing the types of speculation which were blamed for the crash. <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> said that one of the attractive features of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> legislation is `` that its near-complete repeal of the Glass-Steagall Act allows for a market driven evolution of financial services and products.'' `` I would urge the House in its deliberations in the months ahead to adopt an approach similar to that of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> said. However, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> proposal, sponsored by Sen. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Proxmire </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Wis </LOCATION>., faces an uncertain future Opponents of the measure in the securities industry have an ally in Rep. <PERSON> Fernand </PERSON> <PERSON> St </PERSON> <PERSON> Germain </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-R.I. </LOCATION>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. Once before, in 1984, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> passed a bill to give banks broader powers but the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> has never done so. <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> made his comments in a speech to banking officials in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. His remarks were also released in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> said the legislation did not represent a bailout for banks but was instead a reorganization of the financial services industry which would better serve the public. `` The public benefits of expanded powers include not only a stronger and safer banking system, but also the more efficient and convenient delivery of a wider array of lower-cost financial services,'' he said. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> bill would permit a company that owns a bank to also own a securities company as long as the two subsidiaries were operated separately. The securities affiliate would be allowed to underwrite municipal-revenue bonds, mortgage-backed securities and commercial paper. Within six months of the bill becoming law, the legislation would allow the securities affiliates to begin underwriting mutual funds and corporate bonds. In 1991, the legislation requires that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> vote on whether to allow the securities affiliates to take the next step of being able to underwrite corporate stock.
