<HEAD>USSR Turning Increasingly To Barter Arrangements</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is turning increasingly to barter arrangements with other countries in an effort to stretch its declining reserves of foreign currency, an <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> analyst said Thursday. `` Foreign currency is tight for the Soviet government, which in turn has decreased the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s buying power significantly,'' said <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamby </PERSON> of the department's <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Hamby </PERSON>, now the agency's deputy director of marketing for dairy, livestock and poultry, recently returned from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> after 2 -LCB- years as <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> agricultural attache. His remarks were in a new issue of the agency's Foreign Agriculture magazine. The Soviets make it plain they are in a better position to exchange products for foreign goods than to pay in foreign currency. `` This is a difficult constraint on trade from the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> standpoint,'' <PERSON> Hamby </PERSON> said. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> simply does not have the ability to supply the quantity or quality of either agricultural or non-agricultural products which would make a barter arrangement feasible.'' <PERSON> Hamby </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> imports only about $ 25 million worth of Soviet agricultural products each year, while the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s imports of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> farm products averages around $ 2 billion annually. `` This situation has led to continuing Soviet pressure to lift <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> import restrictions on Soviet furskins and other commodities, and pressure for most-favored-nation -LRB- MFN -RRB- trade status, which would give the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> preferential access to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market,'' he said. Under <ORGANIZATION> MFN </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would grant the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> the same trading privileges that it offers most other foreign trading partners. The <ORGANIZATION> MFN </ORGANIZATION> designation for the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has been held up for years because of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s restrictive emigration policies. These issues are likely to persist in any trade negotiation between the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Hamby </PERSON> said. Currently, negotiators are working on a successor to the five-year grain agreement between the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.
