student's comment. Deletes now-outdated last graf.
^LaserPhotos CX3,10</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON> `` would not have been amused'' by a painting showing him in women's lingerie, but the late mayor would n't have gone along with aldermen who stormed the exhibit and had the work removed, a longtime friend said Thursday. `` He would have been the first one to say the artist has a right to do whatever the artist does,'' former mayoral press secretary <PERSON> Alton </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said a day after the outraged aldermen had police confiscate the painting from the School of the <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>. Officer <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Camden </PERSON> said police removed the painting `` for safekeeping because of the possibility of inciting civil unrest.'' He said it would be returned Thursday. The painting by student <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> depicts <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> wearing a frilly white bra, panties and stockings, holding a pencil and frowning out at viewers. It had been displayed in a school hall with dozens of others in a student competition. The school offers a four-year bachelor of arts program and a two-year master's degree, said <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Frech </PERSON>, a spokesman for the private school whose sister institution is the adjacent art musuem. The exhibit is closed to the public, but the aldermen say they got involved after receiving numerous complaints from angry constituents who had seen the painting. They contend the work titled `` Mirth and Girth'' is an insult to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. But a group of students argue the painting is artistic self-expression and protected by the First Amendment. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> would have agreed with both assessments, <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said. `` He would not have been amused,'' and would have seen the painting as `` aiding and abetting'' a campaign waged by his detractors to raise questions about his character, <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. But <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> added, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> would have strongly felt that `` in terms of either ordinance statute or constitutional law ... there's absolutely no way that it can be suppressed. `` I do n't think it's the most tasteful portrait, but I do n't think that matters,'' <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> told radio station WLUP `` Nobody said when I went to the Art Institute that I had to produce tasteful artwork. In fact ... that goes against everything the institution is about,'' he said. `` It's like saying you have to produce artwork in a certain way.'' At the school, a group of about 15 people marched peacefully outside Thursday to protest the painting as the board of directors met inside to discuss the matter. <PERSON> Frech </PERSON> said he did not know what options the board was considering. Civil liberties experts and legal scholars took the students' side `` We're against censorship and this seems to be a form of censorship,'' said <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Polsby </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Northwestern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> law professor, called the aldermen's behavior `` constitutionally indefensible. `` They behaved like a lynch mob and very seriously violated the civil rights of -LRB- the artist -RRB- as well as the <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>.'' <PERSON> Alderman </PERSON> <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> Streeter </PERSON>, who was among those who stormed the school and helped draft a resolution demanding that the painting be removed, said he's aware of the constitutional issues involved. `` There's a moral question that outweighs the constitutional question,'' he said Thursday. The city of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> gives the <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, which oversees the school, subsidies of $ 5 million a year `` as well as other public and private funds, and we do n't feel that any institution, private or public, has a right to portray a leader of any community ... in such a derogatory fashion,'' he said. <PERSON> Alderman </PERSON> <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaw </PERSON>, who sponsored the resolution, said police removed the painting because `` it posed a threat to the safety to the school and the general community.'' `` People, particularly from the black community, are highly perturbed _ using it mildly _ about this particular portrait,'' <PERSON> Shaw </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, who died in November, was the city's first black mayor. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION> was looking for the student and would represent him if he chose to protest the case in court.
