ector, in addition to mine, whom he had already prostituted since the age of 13,'' said a sworn statement from <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Vazquez </PERSON> <PERSON> Padilla </PERSON> distributed to reporters by police. The statement said the youth, the youth's uncle and another man he paid $ 200 agreed to take <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> to an isolated location and kill him. On May 4, when <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> was driving his car to the city of <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION> with his adopted son, the three other men waited by the side of the road near the north coast town of <LOCATION> Sosua </LOCATION> and forced the car to stop. They got in, leaving the adopted son behind, and drove to a nearby farm, where they held Rose for eight hours before killing him, it said. `` Around 8 p.m. we clubbed him to death beating him on the head,'' the statement said. The father's statement said the men took the money from <PERSON> Rose </PERSON>'s pockets and divided it, but left his documents intact They then put <PERSON> Rose </PERSON>'s body in the car and drove to a small ditch, where `` we flipped the car over to make it look like a traffic accident.'' Results of an autopsy released Monday described the death as accidental, but pathologist <PERSON> Sergio </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarita </PERSON> told reporters Thursday the final report indicated `` the death was not an accident but a homicide.'' He said `` investigations ... indicated the car was impacted at a very slow speed that would not have exceeded 15 kilometers per hour -LRB- just over 9 mph -RRB- so -LRB- Rose's -RRB- injuries could not have been from that impact.'' <PERSON> Sarita </PERSON> said tests in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> showed traces of a cocaine derivative in <PERSON> Rose </PERSON>'s urine but none in his brain. `` While examining <PERSON> Rose </PERSON>'s documents at the site where the body was found police ... found he was carrying an amount of cocaine in his purse,'' sa