<HEAD>Watchdog Group Blasts AIDS Policies In New York Prisons</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 State prison inmates with AIDS sometimes get improper medical care and are being unnecessarily denied freedom for the final days of their lives, a prison watchdog group charged Thursday. The <ORGANIZATION> Correctional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> said an 18-month investigation demonstrated that the prison system and state government have not responded adequately'' to AIDS in the prisons. `` AIDS and prison is proving to be a devastating combination,'' said <PERSON> Cathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Potler </PERSON>, author of the report. Among other things, the association urged mandatory education about AIDS for prisoners and staff, expanded and better-supervised medical care, and new provisions to allow the release of terminally ill prisoners. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, which has more AIDS cases than any other state, also has more prisoners with AIDS. As of the end of last year 597 AIDS cases had been confirmed among <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s prison inmates, said state prison system spokesman <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Flateau </PERSON>. Of those, 346 inmates died while in prison, 152 had been released and 99 remained in custody. He said about 100 AIDS cases and 120 cases of AIDS-Related Complex, are in the 42,000-inmate system. There is no known cure for acquired immune deficiency syndrome, which is fatal. The association had medical consultants and non-medical investigators visit several prisons to prepare its report. The group said it also found that inmates suffering from AIDS are often shunned by other inmates who are afraid of even casual contact. Inmate barbers at one prison refused to give haircuts to men with AIDS, said the report. And while prison officials told the association that `` the hysteria initially expressed by the security staff has subsided considerably'' over the last three years, the watchdog group still found evidence of fear. State Corrections Commissioner <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Coughlin </PERSON> said the association's medical team should have spent more time in the prisons. `` Much of the report consists of the opinions of non-medical researchers, supported by unattributed comments by staff and inmates, the content of which may or may not be accurate,'' <PERSON> Coughlin </PERSON> said.
