<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge questioned Thursday whether the government alone can drop the drug indictment against <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, and local prosecutors inisted they want to try the case. `` My understanding and knowledge of the law is that the presiding judge is not required to dismiss an indictment on the motion of the government,'' said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoeveler </PERSON>, who is handling the case. `` However, I am having the law researched further.'' Presidential spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said Thursday that the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration is discussing a deal that could result in the dropping of drug trafficking charges against <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> in exchange for his agreement to relinquish power. The lead prosecutor in the case, Chief Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Gregorie </PERSON>, said Thursday he strongly opposes any deal. `` I am against the dismissal, and right now I am ready to try this case,'' said <PERSON> Gregorie </PERSON>. <PERSON> Gregorie </PERSON>'s boss, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Kellner </PERSON>, released a statement through his executive assistant <PERSON> Ana </PERSON> <PERSON> Barnett </PERSON> following his meeting with Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` He would not discuss the details of his talk with Mr. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>, but he said, ` I presented my views,''' Ms. <PERSON> Barnett </PERSON> said. `` I am authorized to say his views have n't changed, and he wants to proceed with the case and he's ready to proceed with the trial.''' <PERSON> Kellner </PERSON> has previously vowed not to dismiss the indictment, but <PERSON> Noriega </