<HEAD>New Procedures Set For Inspecting Imported Meat And Poultry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 New procedures have been designed to regulate the inspection of imported meat and poultry, including the permanent marking of shipments that fail to meet <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> standards, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> announced Thursday. Each consignment that fails to pass <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> inspection would be stamped `` <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Refused Entry'' on each carcass or packing container, said <PERSON> Lester </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON>, administrator of the department's <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inspection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. `` This will help ensure that rejected meat and poultry does not get into the human food supply in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` It will also warn other countries where the products might be subsequently shipped that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> has rejected the items.'' Products that are refused entry must be removed from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, converted to animal food or destroyed. Previously, such products were identified with temporary placards and had to be closely monitored by <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> employees. The new regulation, which takes effect June 12, also will eliminate a requirement that products refused entry be sealed before being transported in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, since the permanent markings will serve to identify it. <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON> said the new rule also reinstates the practice of `` controlled pre-stamping'' in which import inspectors can put their `` passed'' mark on containers of imported products before the inspection has been fully carried out. This procedure is especially useful at cold storage facilities, so that meat and poultry can be stamped and samples taken for testing and inspection. If there are no problems, the products do n't have to be handled again, he said. If the products fail inspection, inspectors can remove the marks and stamp the products indelibly as refused. In a related action, the agency announced a proposal to allow imported meat and poultry to be inspected only at the port where the products are unloaded. Currently, the products can be shipped across the country to another port for checking by <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> inspectors. <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON> said the proposal, which will be open for public comment until July 12, would give federal inspectors `` much better control of imported products entering food channels'' in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.
