<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Children's advocates on Thursday announced a `` Safe Kids'' campaign designed to combat the leading killer of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s children _ injuries that can be prevented. `` Preventable injuries are epidemic in this country ... -LRB- these -RRB- things are preventable and that's what people have to be made aware of,'' actress <ORGANIZATION> Markie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> NBC-TV </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Night Court'' said at a press conference. `` We've got to change our vocabulary and priorities with children now,'' she said `` We need to become more child-oriented.'' Sen. <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON>, D-Conn., who has scheduled hearings on the issue, said surveys show that most parents would identify drug abuse and kidnapping as the major concerns about their child's <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON> said 67 children in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> State </LOCATION> were abducted last year and 57 died from drug abuse, while nearly 8,000 children aged 14 and under were killed and 50,000 were permanently disabled as a result of avoidable accidents. According to the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, nearly half the deaths of children aged 14 and under are caused by unintentional injuries. The Safe Kids campaign was developed by <ORGANIZATION> Children </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, and is supported by <ORGANIZATION> Johnson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Johnson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. Surgeon General <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Everett </PERSON> <PERSON> Koop </PERSON> serves as honorary chairman of the national campaign. More than 40 health, corporate and children's organizations have joined the campaign, with President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> expected to sign a proclamation designating May 16-22 as National Safe Kids Week. Public service announcements featuring Ms. <PERSON> Post </PERSON> will begin airing nationwide on Monday, inviting listeners to call 800-365-KIDS to request a 16-page safety booklet. The publication advises parents on how to protect children from injury in five leading risk areas: traffic accidents, drownings, burns and scalds, choking and poisoning, and falls. The booklet also urges parents to take first aid and cardiopulmonary resuscitation courses to enable them to provide immediate proper care if an injury does occur. Safe Kids groups in 24 cities will host injury prevention activities next week. `` This campaign has set an ambitious goal _ to change the way <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> thinks about and deals with the epidemic of preventable injuries to children,'' said <PERSON> Herta </PERSON> <PERSON> Burbach </PERSON> <PERSON> Feely </PERSON>, executive director of the campaign. `` The fact is we have not done and we are not doing everything that we can to prevent childhood injuries either as individuals, the community or as a nation.''
