<HEAD>House Appropriations Subcommittee Cuts NASA Budget By $780 Million</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> appropriations panel cut more than $ 780 million out of the <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> budget Thursday and agency officials said the reduction could seriously affect the civil space program. In the markup of appropriations for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Appropriations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>'s subcommittee on housing and urban development and independent agencies approved a total budget for fiscal year 1989 of $ 10.706 billion. <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> had asked for $ 11.488 billion. While that subcommittee was cutting the budget, the full <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION>, Space and Technology authorized the total dollars that <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> had requested, making only minor changes in distribution of the funding. But this action will have little effect if the funds are not appropriated. The budget reduction by the Appropriations subcommittee `` is really going to hurt the program. There is no more slack left in <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>,'' said shuttle astronaut <PERSON> Jon </PERSON> <PERSON> McBride </PERSON>, on assignment in <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>'s congressional relations office `` Something will have to be cut. There's nothing left. If they do make these cuts, some serious things will happen to the civil space program.'' In one of the largest reductions, the Appropriations subcommittee cut <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>'s request for the struggling space shuttle program by more than $ 200 million. The language of the bill would let <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> decide what shuttle program activities will be eliminated. <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> had asked for $ 3.610 billion to improve and start flying the shuttle again, but the subcommittee agreed to appropriate only $ 3.4 billion. `` This will be one of the toughest cuts to accommodate,'' said <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Dawson </PERSON>, a staff member of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on space science and applications. <PERSON> Dawson </PERSON> said some of the shuttle program items that could be affected include manufacture of spare parts, an effort to enhance the performance of the rocket engines and fuel pumps on the orbiter and the scheduling of missions. It would not, however, affect the resumption of shuttle flights. `` It's going to hurt them no matter what they do,'' said <PERSON> McBride </PERSON>. The space shuttle has been grounded since January 1986 when the explosion of the Challenger shuttle killed seven crew members. The winged spacecraft fleet is scheduled to resume flights in August. Appropriations subcommittee members also cut $ 65 million from the $ 967 million <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> had requested for development of the space station. <PERSON> Dawson </PERSON> said the $ 902 million allocation would allow the space station program to continue will little effect. Other cuts, with the original <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> request in parenthesis, include: _ Advanced X-ray astrophysics facility, an astronomy satellite, $ 16 million -LRB- $ 27 million -RRB- _ Commercial Development Space Facility, a privately built orbiting factory that <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> was to lease, zero -LRB- A $ 25 million appropriation from last year was rescinded -RRB-. _ Titan 4 launch rocket, $ 23 million -LRB- $ 43 million -RRB- The subcommittee also cut <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> plans to buy a Delta II and a Titan 3 launch rocket. The marked-up bill is expected to go to the full <ORGANIZATION> Appropriations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION