<HEAD>House Intelligence Committee Approves Notification Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday it has approved and sent to the full <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> legislation that would require the president to notify <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> within 48 hours when he authorizes covert intelligence missions. The bill, which grew out of the recommendations of the congressional panels that investigated the Iran-Contra affair, was approved Wednesday on an 11-to-6 party-line vote and announced Thursday by the committee. It is similar to a covert-action measure passed March 15 by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> on a vote of 71 to 19. A central dispute in the Iran-Contra affair was the approval by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> of a secret arms-for-hostages swap which was not discovered for 10 months after it was authorized, even though the law requires notification of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> `` in a timely fashion.'' The congressional Iran-Contra committees recommended that the law be changed to eliminate all ambiguity. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> bills would require the president to make a written `` finding'' that any covert action is required on national security grounds, and to provide copies to the congressional intelligence oversight committees. The committees would have to be given prior notice of such actions, unless an emergency prevented notification. In such cases, the president would have up to 48 hours to get word to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. The president also would have to tell <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> which agencies are to be involved in the covert action and disclose whether private third parties are to be involved, as they were in the Iran-Contra affair. Under the bill, a covert action is any <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> activity, other than traditional military, diplomatic and law enforcement actions, designed `` to influence political, economic or military conditions abroad so that the role of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> government is not intended to be apparent or acknowledged publicly ...'' As it considered amendments to the measure, the Democrat-controlled panel rejected an effort by Rep. <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Cheney </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Wyo </LOCATION>., to leave an exemption from the 48-hour notice requirement The committee also rejected an effort by Rep. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Livingston </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-La </LOCATION>., to provide for fines up to $ 20,000 and up to five years in prison for unauthorized disclosure of classified information
