<BYLINE>By BILL SIMMONS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OZARK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A man accused of slaying 16 people was convicted Thursday and sentenced to death in the holiday season shooting rampage that left a man and a woman dead. He immediately asked that the sentence be carried out as soon as possible so that the `` torture and suffering within me'' would end. A <ORGANIZATION> Franklin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> jury deliberated less than 1 -LCB- hours before convicting <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> of capital murder and five counts of attempted capital murder. They then heard arguments on whether to sentence him to death or to life in prison without parole, and later returned the death penalty. This trial, which started Monday, stemmed from a 45-minute shooting spree in <LOCATION> Russellville </LOCATION> on Dec. 28. <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON>, 47, is scheduled to stand trial again in July in the deaths of his wife, seven children, four grandchildren, and two in-laws whose bodies were found in and around his house after the rampage ended. They had all been shot or strangled. After Circuit Judge <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON> ratified the death penalty verdict, <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> put on his glasses and in a calm voice read a brief statement asking that the sentence be carried out as soon as possible. `` It is my wish and my desire that absolutely no action by anybody be taken to appeal or in any way change this sentence,'' <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> said. `` It is further respectfully requested that this sentence be carried out expeditiously. I want no action that will delay, deny, defer or denounce this very correct and proper death sentence.'' `` I only ask for what I deserve,'' he said. `` Let the torture and suffering in me end. Please allow me the right to be at peace.'' Afterward, the judge said it was not clear whether <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> had the legal right to cancel the automatic appeal provided for death sentences in state law. Under <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> law, the death penalty would be carried out by lethal injection. Earlier, prosecutor <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Bynum </PERSON>, arguing for death for the retired <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> master sergeant, had said `` there is nothing in the record that says this man is entitled to a break _ nothing.'' Defense attorney <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Irwin </PERSON>, who had rested his case without calling any witnesses, asked the jury for mercy. `` One thing is certain _ <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> is going to die in prison,'' <PERSON> Irwin </PERSON> said. `` The only question is whether it is by our hand or by some act of providence or by a merciful God.'' Later, another defense attorney, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>, said they had urged <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> not to ask for the death penalty but now felt duty bound not to oppose him. `` He wanted the death sentence; he felt like he deserved it,'' <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> said. `` And he wanted us as his attorneys to do everything within our power to see that he could get the death sentence, if you can imagine that.'' <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> was found guilty of capital murder _ the deaths of two people made it a capital crime _ and of five counts of attempted capital murder for the four people who were wounded and a fifth person who was fired at but not hit. Jurors reduced a kidnapping charge to first-degree false imprisonment and also convicted <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> of that charge. In addition to the death penalty on the murder charge, the jurors sentenced <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> to 30 years for each of four attempted capital murder counts, 20 years for the fifth attempted murder count, and seven years for first-degree false imprisonment. <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON> ordered that those sentences be served consecutively. In his closing statement, <PERSON> Irwin </PERSON> argued that the state did not support its contention the murders were premeditated and that there were no tests to link <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> to the murder weapons and other evidence. But <PERSON> Bynum </PERSON> said such tests were unnecessary because of the number of witnesses and the testimony from <ORGANIZATION> Russellville </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> Chief <PERSON> Herb </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON> that <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> handed him the murder weapon. `` The evidence in this case is strong; it's stout,'' <PERSON> Bynum </PERSON> said. Among the spectators in the standing-room-only courtroom were <PERSON> Viola </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Shields </PERSON>, and her husband, <PERSON> Roger </PERSON>, relatives of some of the <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON>' family victims. Tears welling in her eyes, Mrs. <PERSON> O'Shields </PERSON> displayed a photograph of one of the victims, <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON>' 17-year-old daughter, <PERSON> Loretta </PERSON>. `` Is n't it a shame?'', she said. Killed were <PERSON> Kathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Kendrick </PERSON>, 24, who reportedly had spurned <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON>' advances a year before the shooting; and <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Chaffin </PERSON>, 33, described by police as a chance victim. She was shot at the law office where she worked, while he was shot at an oil company. A state ballistics expert, <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> McDonald </PERSON>, testified that bullets that killed <PERSON> Kendrick </PERSON> and <PERSON> Chaffin </PERSON>, and bullets found at a market where two people were wounded, had been fired by the same nine-shot revolver that <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> handed to police when he surrendered. The trial was moved to Ozark because of extensive pretrial publicity.
