 </PERSON> and members of his American organization. `` <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> was just another pilot,'' <PERSON> Merkle </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Shohat </PERSON> ended his arguments for <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON> on Thursday by telling the jury to `` do what you feel is right.'' The jury must not condemn <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON> based on the prosecution's attacks on his character, said <PERSON> Shohat </PERSON>, but must stick to the specific charges contained in the 11-count indictment <PERSON> Shohat </PERSON> spent the morning again hammering away at what he said were inconsistencies in the testimony of government witnesses, many of whom were admitted smugglers given immunity for their testimony. Later, <PERSON> Merkle </PERSON> said, `` The attack on the credibility of the witnesses is this case is so much sound and fury.'' <PERSON> Shohat </PERSON> had said the chief prosecution witness, convicted smuggler <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Ward </PERSON>, was `` given the break of a lifetime'' for his testimony against <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON>, getting a possible 215-year sentence and $ 5.9 million fine cut to less than six years in prison. <PERSON> Shohat </PERSON> went through what he termed `` the litany of lies'' testified to by several members of <PERSON> Ward </PERSON>'s group of American smugglers. `` These people planned to dump on Mr. <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON>. These people knew how to get an <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> card to freedom,'' he said. <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON>, who officials have said was a key member of <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s violent <LOCATION> Medellin </LOCATION> cartel, is charged with conspiracy, possession of cocaine with intent to distribute, importation of cocaine and operating a continuing criminal enterprise He was arrested near the Colombian town of <LOCATION> Medellin </LOCATION> in February 1987 after a shootout and was immediately flown to <LOCATION> Florida </LOCA