<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Five people were arrested Thursday on charges of running a treasure-hunting scam that fleeced 700 investors of $ 1.7 million. `` This was a treasure salvage company, but the only treasure found was the money that was taken from the pockets of investors,'' state Comptroller <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> said. The three companies accused of wrongdoing traded on the success of the treasure-hunter <PERSON> Mel </PERSON> <PERSON> Fisher </PERSON>, who found Spanish treasure ships off the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Keys </LOCATION> and retrieved gold and jewels worth millions of dollars, <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> said. `` The people bought a ship from <PERSON> Mel </PERSON> <PERSON> Fisher </PERSON> and they bought apparently a small amount of treasure so they could show this and use it and use <PERSON> Mel </PERSON> <PERSON> Fisher </PERSON>'s name,'' <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> said the operators falsely claimed they found three wrecks. No treasure-hunting was ever done and no treasure was found, he said. Instead, the defendants pocketed investors' money, and it is unlikely they will get any of it back, the comptroller said. <PERSON> Fisher </PERSON> is not involved in any of the operations and is not accused of any wrongdoing, <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> said. The five people arrested were indicted by a grand jury May 5 on charges of fraud, sale of unregistered securities and racketeering. The three agencies that announced the arrests also are investigating as many as 15 other treasure-hunting operations seeking investors with `` treasure fever,'' <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> said. Most of the bogus operations are in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, but a few are out of state. Most of those under investigation also have been trading on <PERSON> Fisher </PERSON>'s success.
