<HEAD>Chronology of Major Evens In Panamanian Crisis</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Noriega, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Here is a chronology of events in the Panamanian crisis: FEB. 25 _ <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s president, <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Arturo </PERSON> <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON>, announces dismissal of defense chief Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, who had been indicted in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> on drug charges. FEB. 26 _ Noriega-dominated <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> ousts <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON>. Education Minister <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Solis </PERSON> <PERSON> Palma </PERSON> named head of state. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> opponents call for general strike. MARCH 1 _ General strike gains support. Locally owned banks close. International banks limit withdrawals. MARCH 3 _ Organizers end general strike. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> federal courts block withdrawal of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> funds from <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> banks. MARCH 4 _ <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Panama </ORGANIZATION> says it can not meet cash demands. International banks fearing a run on deposits close their doors. MARCH 11 _ President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> imposes economic sanctions, including eliminating trade preferences for <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> and placing <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION> fees in escrow. MARCH 14 _ Public employees stage work stoppages and riot when government is unable to pay wages. Riot police use tear gas and truncheons to disperse demonstrators. MARCH 16 _ <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> survives coup attempt by dissident officers. Demonstrations and strikes at state-run utility companies, ports and government ministries. MARCH 17 _ Government declares `` state of urgency'' and soldiers patrol capital. MARCH 18 _ <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> meets with <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officials who say the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will not extradite him on the drug charges if he seeks asylum in third country. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> reportedly says he wants to remain in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> and take part in formation of transitional government. MARCH 20 _ <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> says indictments against <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> will not be dropped and <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> can not have say about government after his departure. MARCH 21 _ General strike paralyzes nation. <PERSON> Solis </PERSON> <PERSON> Palma </PERSON> announces <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> offers to resign before May 1989 elections if opponents agree to talks. Opposition leaders and <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> reject offer. MARCH 30 _ Nation's three biggest supermarket chains open, signaling rupture in general strike. Government announces banks will reopen with limited service. APRIL 8 _ <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> bans payments from <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> citizens or companies to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s government, including bills, fees or fines. APRIL 20 _ Government lifts state of emergency. APRIL 28 _ <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> backs away from insisting <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> leave <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, saying he just has to resign. Panamanian opposition protests change in stance. APRIL 30 _ <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> relaxes order prohibiting payments by Americans to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. MAY 7 _ <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> rejects <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ultimatum to resign and leave <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> and says he is considering Guatemalan offer to mediate end to crisis. MAY 9 _ Banks let customers make limited cash withdrawals. MAY 11 _ <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration sources say <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> has offered to drop drug charges against <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> if he steps down and leaves country. Panamanian government says there has been no deal.
