<HEAD>Senate Considers Plans To Use Military To Fight Drug-Runners</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS lead with 2 grafs to UPDATE with prospects for passage
slipping to Friday; INSERTS 3 grafs after 8th graf pvs bgng,
`Another proposal,' to UPDATE with later comments from Nunn,
D'Amato; ADDS new last graf with Persian Gulf vote</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday was trying to find a way to increase <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military involvement in the war against illegal drugs, but bogged down in a dispute over whether to give the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> new powers to arrest drug traffickers in international waters. The dispute centered around a <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> budget bill, which the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> is trying to finish. The argument over the anti-drug provision is the major remaining hurdle and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> leaders said they do n't expect to pass the bill before Friday. <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> attended a closed-door series of meetings at the Capitol to discuss the anti-drug plans, which have been proposed in response to what legislators say is public demand to do more to halt drug-trafficking. `` We're all looking for a way to have the military more involved in a meaningful way in the war against drugs,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON>, D-Ga., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> and the chief author of one anti-drug proposal The bill authorizes defense spending in the fiscal year starting Oct. 1 of $ 299.5 billion, the same total contained in a separate Pentagon budget bill passed Wednesday by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>. Differences between the measures will be worked out later by a <ORGANIZATION> House-Senate </ORGANIZATION> conference committee. The House bill contains a provision ordering President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to have the military `` substantially halt'' the penetration of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> borders by ships and planes carrying illegal drugs. The plan proposed by <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> is not as far reaching, but it would make the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> the chief federal agency in halting illegal drug-trafficking, and also would have the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> provide more coordination and communications to other drug-fighting agencies such as the <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION>. Making the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> the chief federal agency for anti-drug efforts would mean it would have to approve actions by all other federal agencies. Another proposal authored by <PERSON> Sens </PERSON>. <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, R-Calif., and <PERSON> Alfonse </PERSON> <PERSON> D'Amato </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.Y. </LOCATION>, would allow <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military personnel to make anti-drug arrests outside <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> borders, such as beyond the three-mile limit recognized by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON>, <PERSON> D'Amato </PERSON> and <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said they were trying to craft their separate proposals into a single bill, but the main sticking point was over whether to give the military arrest powers in international waters. The plan will not be approved before Friday, <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON> said. Asked about the reaction of <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> officials, <PERSON> D'Amato </PERSON> said, `` They're not happy. ... They're not doing cartwheels.'' The military is now barred from enforcing civilian laws by the Posse Comitatus Act, an 1878 law enacted to halt the practice of having the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> enforce laws in the post-Civil War southern states. That law was amended in 1981 to permit the military to provide some aid, and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military surveillance information is now passed along to some civilian agencies. In addition, <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> officials now travel aboard <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> ships patrolling the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> has offered to have the Pentagon do more in the anti-drug effort, although he opposes having the military make arrests. <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> said Thursday that the military can slow, but not halt, the flow of drugs. `` If the effort here is to reduce the amount of drugs coming into this country, it can be done,'' <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> said. `` If the effort is expected to stop drugs coming into this country, it can not be done. Unless you do it on the demand side, ways will be found.'' The military can track planes, <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> noted, but `` it's difficult to tell the difference between a civilian flight and one that is engaged in drug smuggling. `` We have ample military resources to be able to stop every aircraft at our border, but in fact that's a much more complex problem than I think most people realize,'' he said. As it worked through the bill Thursday, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>: _ Voted 57-39 to kill an effort to ban most <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> underground nuclear testing The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, in its version of the bill, approved an underground test ban, meaning the issue will have to be resolved by the conference committee. _ Voted 64-32 to restore a `` Buy America'' requirement which requires the Petnagon to buy <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> products, including anthracite coal The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> says it already has a four-year supply of the coal and does n't need any more. _ Killed, on a 60-37 vote, a proposal that would have halted the sending of any <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> combat troops to leftist-ruled <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> or its neighbor, <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> The troop ban was approved last week by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, meaning the issue will have to be decided by the conference. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has said repeatedly the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has no intention of sending combat troops to <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. _ Killed, on a 61-36 vote, a plan to reduce spending for the railroad version of the MX nuclear-tipped missile from $ 700 million to $ 200, using the extra $ 500 million to buy more non-nuclear weapons The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> proposes to spend only $ 100 million for the rail version of the MX. _ Rejected, 82-13, the latest proposal to have the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> express a formal opinion on <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> policy The amendment would have required a detailed report from <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> outlining his plans for <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> involvement in the war-torn region, and would have given <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> 15 days after that to formally vote on the policy.
