<HEAD>Illinois Bell Says Weeks Required To Restore Service After Fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES J. GANS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Phone service to <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s western suburbs will not be fully restored until late in June following a fire at a switching station that caused the worst service disruption in the company's history, <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Eibel </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION>'s vice president of operations, said `` significant progress'' has been made in restoring telephone circuits passing through its west suburban <LOCATION> Hinsdale </LOCATION> switching center, which was heavily damaged by fire Sunday. But he told a news conference it would take at least until the third week in June before all 35,000 customers affected by the outage have full service. Phones in all or parts of six western suburbs have been dead since the fire. `` This was the most severe service disruption <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> has had in its history,'' <PERSON> Eibel </PERSON> said of the 107-year-old company. `` The scope and complexity of the repair work far exceeds anything we've had in the past ... and that includes any natural disasters. <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> investigators have still not determined the cause of the fire. By overhauling damaged local switching equipment as a stopgap measure, the phone company hoped to restore 21,000 service lines by Sunday, <PERSON> Eibel </PERSON> said. But he cautioned that this was the most optimistic projection. <PERSON> Eibel </PERSON> said he could not guarantee the old equipment would hold up against corrosion caused by the chemical reaction from smoke and water sprayed by firefighters. Emergency service to hospitals, police and fire departments, the company's first priority, may be back in service in the next couple of days, <PERSON> Eibel </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> employees were working round-the-clock Thursday to install new equipment, which should be in place by June 1, although it will take another three weeks to restore service to all local residents, <PERSON> Eibel </PERSON> said. It normally takes 50 weeks to install a completely new system. The telephone company was having more success in repairing damage to 13,000 special lines used by businesses and the `` trunking service'' knocked out by the fire at the <LOCATION> Hinsdale </LOCATION> station. About half of the trunking service had been restored by Thursday, and all 118,000 circuits connecting the western and southwestern suburbs with the rest of the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> metropolitan area and long distance providers should be back in service by late Sunday, <PERSON> Eibel </PERSON> said. He expected that the business service lines would be fully back in operation by the end of next week. Special service lines are used by business customers for a variety of purposes, including data transmission. <PERSON> Eibel </PERSON> acknowledged a considerable delay in the time between when the fire was first reported at the unmanned switching station and the arrival of firefighters to fight the blaze. <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> received an alarm at 3:50 p.m. at a monitoring station in <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION>, more than 150 miles away, but it was not until 4:20 p.m. that a full fire alarm sounded, <PERSON> Eibel </PERSON> said. After another 30 minutes, an employee arrived to check out the alarm, but he had to hail down a passing motorist to alert firefighters because the phones were already out of service. Firefighters did not arrive at the scene until after 5 p.m. The phone company was reviewing its fire prevention measures in light of the fire, <PERSON> Eibel </PERSON> said. Meanwhile, residents were trying to cope as best as possible with the lack of phone service. People lined up at mobile trailers with public coin phone stations at six locations in the western suburbs. `` I ` ts been very inconvenient,'' said <PERSON> Sandy </PERSON> <PERSON> Barthick </PERSON>, assistant editor of a telecommunications trade paper in `` I've been doing all my phone work from my home in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>.''
