<HEAD>Chinese Herbs, Antiseptics Join Dental Arsenal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By A.J. DICKERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Chinese herbs and antiseptics are the newest weapons in the war against cavities and gum disease, researchers said Thursday. ` They're as common as the common cold,'' <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maryland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> microbiologist <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> said of gum problems and tooth decay. Speaking at the 88th annual convention of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Microbiology </ORGANIZATION>, she said her study involved having patients with gum disease dip special toothbrushes in a mild prescription antibiotic called chlordexidine, and then brush. Within one to three weeks, plaque-causing bacteria decreased, she said. ` This is an attempt to combine treatments, a mechanical cleaning with the use of a mild antiseptic,'' she said. ` The up-and-down scraping dislodge the bacteria.'' The seven patients in the test group used tiny, Christmas-tree-shaped brushes designed to get the antibiotic solution in pockets of infection near tooth roots. They use the technique in conjunction with regular brushing, said <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON>, who hopes to soon launch a larger study. Extracts of plants used in Chinese folk medicine also appear promising in the fight against tooth decay and gum disease, said <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Colorado </ORGANIZATION> microbiologist <PERSON> Christine </PERSON> <PERSON> Wu-Yuan </PERSON>. She started her research after a 1984 trip to <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>, where dentists prescribe herbs for patients. `` They know it works, but they do n't know why it works,'' she said. ` Chinese folk medicine is rich with plant-derived products used to treat gum disease and maintain oral health. We looked at herbs that can affect cavities and gum disease.'' She pulverized 40 kinds of plants that she found in Chinese markets in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, and mixed the extracts with bacteria commonly found in mouths. Forty-two percent of the extracts inhibited bacterial growth, including 10 percent that outright killed the germs, she said. She refused to name the plants used, saying corporations are pressing her for that information. Ms. <PERSON> Wu-Yuan </PERSON> said the next step is further research on the promising extracts _ using patients instead of bacteria _ and fine-tuning the amounts that could be used in a toothpaste or mouthwash. ` A lot of the time with gum disease, there are no symptoms, so people do n't take it seriously'' until their teeth are in danger of falling out, she said.
