<HEAD>Senate Rejects Attempt to Express Formal Opinion on Persian Gulf
Policy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Defense Spending</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday easily rejected the latest attempt to have the chamber express a formal opinion on President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s expanded policy of protecting shipping in the war-torn <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> voted 82-13 to table, and thus kill, an amendment to a <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> budget bill that would have required a report from <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> outlining his policy. The proposal would have required specifics about the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> goals, anticipated length of deployment and the rules under which <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> weapons would be fired. The plan was offered by Sen. <PERSON> Brock </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>, D-Wash., who again criticized his colleagues for refusing to vote on whether the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> approves of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s year-old policy <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>, a critic of the administration policy, told his fellow senators that `` for over a year we have danced around the issues.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s policy involves having the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> protect 11 reflagged Kuwaiti tankers in the gulf, which has been the scene of fighting in the long Iran-Iraq war. <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> is an Iraqi ally. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy recently was expanded to provide <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> protection to neutral merchant ships who are attacked and who seek <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> help from <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> warships. That expanded policy came in the wake of an April 18 clash between the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, in which the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> sank or damaged six Iranian vessels. It was the latest in a series of military fights between the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has yet to vote formal approval or disapproval of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s policy. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> also has rejected <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>' repeated efforts to invoke the War Powers Act. That is the 1973 law that would, under some circumstances, require the withdrawal of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces from situations of `` imminent danger.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has refused to invoke the War Powers law, arguing that it is an unconstitutional restriction on his authority. <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> and 110 other legislators have sued to invoke the law, but a federal judge rejected the suit and they are appealing that rejection. Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Warner </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Va </LOCATION>., a former secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>, led the opposition to <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>' proposal `` I think it would be ill-advised for the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to single out any particular military operation and say, on an annual basis, that we're going to appropriate money for that operation.'' <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>' proposal rejected by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> would have required the report from <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and then would have provided 15 days for <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to disapprove the policy. If no disapproval vote were taken, the policy would have been considered approved. Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ohio </LOCATION>, criticized <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s policy as `` foolish ... stupid'' but he opposed <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>' plan. He said it might mean that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces would be pulled out of the region. `` I do n't want to see us take an action in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> that would really mean we are willing to pull out,'' said <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON>. Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> McCain </PERSON>, R-Ariz., opposed the plan because `` this would require the president to be a prophet ... I'm not sure the president can provide a plan, given the fluid nature of events in that part of the world.'' <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> said his proposal `` is n't a withdrawal from the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>. ... I do not want to withdraw our forces.'' Sen. <PERSON> Strom </PERSON> <PERSON> Thurmond </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-S.C. </LOCATION>, said the plan `` is another example of what <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is criticized for. ... You ca n't have 535 secretaries of state,'' referring to the total number of <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> members.
