<SECOND>AM-India-Punjab,0692</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Killed in Golden Temple Fighting; Priests Arrested</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police arrested four of <LOCATION> Sikhism </LOCATION>'s five high priests and 26 followers as they prepared to march Thursday to the <ORGANIZATION> Golden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION>, officials said. Security forces killed at least three people at the besieged shrine. Indian commandos backed by paramilitary troops captured a strategic water tank on the temple complex grounds, where an estimated 100 Sikh militants have been holed up since Monday, officials said. About 2,500 police and paramilitary troops surrounded the militants at the temple, <LOCATION> Sikhism </LOCATION>'s holiest shrine. They have been fighting intermittently since Monday. The <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> government ruled out new negotiations with the militants and demanded they surrender. `` If they do not do so the state government will continue its pressure on them,'' <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> Governor <PERSON> S.S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> said in a statement issued in the state capital, <LOCATION> Chandigargh </LOCATION>. Talks Wednesday on ending the temple standoff were inconclusive and a cease-fire that took effect that day ended Thursday morning. The militants have been waging a guerrilla campaign since 1983 for more autonomy or an independent homeland for the Sikhs in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>. Sikhs, whose religion was founded about 500 years ago as an alternative to <LOCATION> Hinduism </LOCATION> and Islam, claim they are discriminated against by <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s majority Hindus. Sikhs make up less than 2 percent of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s 800 million people but are a majority in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>. Three more people, two Sikh militants and an unidentified man, were shot and killed by security forces on Thursday, raising the death toll in the fighting to at least 15, said <PERSON> A.A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Siddiqui </PERSON>, state police deputy chief. <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> said as many as seven Sikhs died inside the shrine Thursday. Indian commandos captured the water tank in the living area of the temple complex, said witnesses who spoke on condition of anonymity. The priests were arrested as they attempted to march on the <ORGANIZATION> Golden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION> from another Sikh shrine about a half-mile to the north, <PERSON> Siddiqui </PERSON> said. The priests were placed in custody for 15 days on charges of violating curfew orders, <PERSON> Siddiqui </PERSON> said. Among those arrested was <PERSON> Jasbir </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> <PERSON> Rode </PERSON>, the temple's head priest, who held talks Wednesday with government officials to try to end the confrontation. Rode has called for the militants to dismantle their bunkers and for the security forces to withdraw. Deputy Police Commissioner <PERSON> Sarbjeet </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> had asked them to call off their march because two bursts of gunfire were reported inside the temple Thursday after an overnight lull. `` We take responsibility for any firing from inside the temple,'' Rode told <PERSON> Sarbjeet </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, insisting that the march should be allowed to proceed. `` You take responsibility for firing from outside.'' Firing from the temple increased as the morning wore on. Police lifted a curfew in most parts of <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION> on Thursday, but it remained in force within 200 yards of the <ORGANIZATION> Golden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION>, Indian television said. Most of the shops and businesses in the old sector of <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION> which surrounds the temple remained shuttered even after curfew was withdrawn in the area. Security forces for the first time Thursday began blocking reporters from approaching the temple. They said Sikh militants might shoot the journalists. More than 940 people have been killed this year in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> in attacks blamed on the extremists. Most have been Hindus or moderate Sikhs opposed to the separatist campaign. The confrontation at the Golden Temple began Monday when militants inside the shrine opened fire on security forces who had gone to a nearby rooftop to look at fortifications the Sikhs were building on the northern edge of the complex. The temple complex covers an area equivalent to more than five city blocks. The temple sits in the center of a pool. The Indian army was sent into the Golden Temple complex in June 1984 to flush out Sikh extremists. More than 1,200 people were killed in the attack. Later that year, Prime Minister <PERSON> Indira </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> was assassinated by two of her Sikh bodyguards.
