<HEAD>U.N. Afghan Relief Boss Says Hundreds of Millions Needed</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghan Fighting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Prince </PERSON> <PERSON> Sadruddin </PERSON> <PERSON> Aga </PERSON> <PERSON> Khan </PERSON>, head of <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> relief for <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, said Thursday an international appeal will be launched in three weeks for hundreds of millions of dollars for refugee aid and reconstruction. `` We must see to equitable distribution and certainly relief would be without strings attached and should not be used for political manipulation,'' he told a news conference. `` The important thing is that the aid gets to the people who need it.'' The amount has not been set. The prince, a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> high commissioner for refugees from 1965-77, said he hopes to meet all parties concerned, rebels included. The rebels control much of the Afghan countryside and he indicated they could play an important part in relief distribution. `` I am concerned about the Afghan people as a whole and we need to find ways to get help where it is needed,'' he said. The 55-year-old prince was named Wednesday as undersecretary-general to coordinate all international relief efforts in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and resettlement of 5 million refugees. Facing him is the task of insuring that a vast amount of aid will be distributed fairly by <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> and other agencies. He must see aid is not exploited or manipulated by the pro-Soviet government in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> or by the anti-Marxist rebels, who reject the political accord on withdrawing Soviet troops. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> mediated the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> agreement between <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> providing for the 115,000 Soviet troops in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> to withdraw over a nine-month period. The prince emphasized that <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> relief efforts are separate from the political agreement. Answering a question, he said he could not give the amount of aid needed for relief, reconstruction and rehabilitation, but it would amount to `` hundreds of millions of dollars.'' He said Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> probably will launch the appeal to donor countries in three weeks. <PERSON> Sadruddin </PERSON> <PERSON> Aga </PERSON> <PERSON> Khan </PERSON> said he will shuttle between <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Islamabad </LOCATION> from his base in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> and that he will go to the area next week. He said his work will involve coordinating the work of many <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> agencies _ including the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Program </ORGANIZATION>, the Food and <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> and others _ as well as the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION>; the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Crescent </ORGANIZATION>, its Islamic counterpart, and other groups. He said many governments already have indicated their willingness to make generous contributions and have been awaiting a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> mechanism for distribution. He said his immediate task is to formulate an appeal and assure donors how their money will be spent. He said repatriation of refugees will be a major task and reception centers must be set up for displaced people wanting to return.
