<HEAD>General Assembly Endorses Blueprint for Central American
Development</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday endorsed a plan calling for $ 4.3 billion in economic development programs in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> aimed at fostering peace and democracy. The 159-nation body approved the resolution by consensus only a day after a military rebellion was put down in <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION>. That country represented the region during the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> debate. <PERSON> Nealy </PERSON> half the money, $ 2 billion, would be debt relief. The resolution puts the assembly's stamp of approval on an ambitious and wide-ranging program for regional reconstruction, emergency relief and long-term development that depends on the generosity of the international community. <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> officials have not indicated exactly how they plan to raise the money for the program. However, its coordinator, <PERSON> Augusto </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramirez </PERSON> <PERSON> Ocampo </PERSON>, has been trying to line up donors, particularly in <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. More than 45 nations, including most of the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>, signed on as sponsors of the resolution. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, concerned about the plan's call for debt relief, was an exception. `` We take the view that the matter of bilateral commercial debt is a matter between creditor governments and creditor banks,'' said <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, a spokesman for the British mission. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, which did not commit itself to contributing any money to the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> plan, shared <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s reservations about debt relief. Ambassador <PERSON> Lester </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Korn </PERSON> reminded the assembly that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has given $ 4 billion in direct aid to <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION> since 1985 and contributed an additional $ 1 billion to international organizations active in the region. `` The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is pleased that the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> is on record as supporting what the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has been doing for the past decade in this troubled area of the world,'' <PERSON> Korn </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Korn </PERSON> criticized the plan for being vague about sources of funding. Work on the development plan began shortly after five <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> presidents signed a regional peace accord last summer. The <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> development plans calls for $ 392 million to resettle the estimated 830,000 people displaced by the civil wars in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION>, and to provide emergency food and energy assistance. About $ 1.4 billion would be earmarked for long-term projects running the gamut from rebuilding roads to vocational training for the handicapped to encouraging tourism. The plan also calls for spending $ 600 million to revive a Central American common market.
