on which <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> campaigned, contained at least nine non-Socialists but only two figures who could be called centrists. <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>, whose <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> has moved toward the right, had made a point of appealing to centrists. But <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Alain </PERSON> <PERSON> Juppe </PERSON> said <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>'s talk of reaching beyond the ranks of the Socialists was but a `` pre-electoral trap for fools.'' <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Toubon </PERSON>, secretary general of <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>'s conservative Rally for the Republic party, said the Cabinet was `` a hard-core Socialist government.'' The announcement of the Cabinet, originally expected Wednesday, was reportedly delayed because of last-minute hesitation on the part of centrists wary of joining a Socialist government. Sen. <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Pelletier </PERSON> was named minister for aid and cooperation and Sen. <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Durafour </PERSON> was appointed minister of public works. Both were ministers under former President <PERSON> Valery </PERSON> <PERSON> Giscard </PERSON> d'Estaing, who is from the centrist <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> French </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democracy </ORGANIZATION>. They are both part of the center-right parliamentary majority. Among the non-politicians is judge <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Arpaillange </PERSON>, named justice minister, replacing <PERSON> Albin </PERSON> <PERSON> Chalendon </PERSON>. <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Fauroux </PERSON>, who had been director of the prestigious <ORGANIZATION> Ecole </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nationale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> d'Administration </ORGANIZATION> where most French politicans study, was named minister of industry and foreign trade. <PERSON> Jacq