<HEAD>Byrd Says No INF Debate Before Committees Act</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 3, 5, 16 to CORRECT spelling of Shevardnadze.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Soviet Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>, D-W. <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, insisted Thursday he will schedule debate on the US-Soviet medium-range missile treaty only after three <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> committees examine and approve a new anti-cheating But some senators of both parties objected, declaring it is imperative the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> begin work on the pact immediately so that President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> can take a ratified treaty to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> on May 29 for his summit with Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. Senate Republican leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> reported to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> that Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> believes he struck a `` completely satisfactory'' bargain with Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> on the outstanding disagreements involving the Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces, or INF, treaty. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said White House national security adviser <PERSON> Colin </PERSON> <PERSON> Powell </PERSON> will fly back from the meeting Friday to brief <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> leaders on what has been accomplished. If <PERSON> Powell </PERSON> can report that <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> has confirmed <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> will live up to the letter of the treaty, <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said debate on ratification should begin on Monday with the aim of taking a final vote before the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> summit. Sen. <PERSON> Claiborne </PERSON> <PERSON> Pell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-R.I. </LOCATION>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> will testify before his panel Monday afternoon and that <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s bipartisan leadership and the chairmen and the ranking <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> members of the <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> committees have been invited to attend. <PERSON> Pell </PERSON> suggested that if no further snags are uncovered, <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> debate could open on Tuesday. But <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> insisted he will not be `` driven by a calendar date'' and will not permit floor debate to begin until the on-site inspection plan is reviewed and approved by the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> and Intelligence committees. `` We were told all the I's were dotted and all the T's were crossed,'' <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> said. `` It was through the examination of these committees that it was found that this was not the case.'' `` If we make a mistake in this treaty and we find we have been hoodwinked or outsmarted, then you can kiss the next arms treaty goodbye,'' he declared. `` Let's do this thing right.'' But <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> said: `` I want our committees which have the responsibility for taking the microscopic look at the fine print to have the opportunity to go carefully into this and advise the joint leadership if these agreements adequately resolve the problems. `` Briefings are fine but the final word will be what these committees have to say,'' he declared But Sen. <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Alaska </LOCATION>, said the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> must do nothing to cause further delay and prevent `` this American president from being able to present before the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> people this historic agreement.'' `` If he goes to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> and faces the question of why he ca n't get ratification, I think we place the presidency in jeopardy so far as the success of future negotiations is concerned,'' <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> said `` Time is the commodity that's scarce now,'' he said. <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> on Monday shelved debate on the new treaty to give <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> and <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> time to resolve a serious dispute over the implementation of anti-cheating provisions. The dispute centers on what <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> inspectors will be permitted to see and what they will be permitted to do as they seek to learn whether the Soviets are living up to the requirements of the treaty to eliminate all medium-range missiles. Earlier, <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> told reporters a go-ahead for debate `` depends on who's giving the answers and what they look like,'' <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> said. `` I'm going to depend on the committees with jurisdiction to determine whether these matters have been resolved in the proper way ... whether these things that need to be fixed are really fixed,'' <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> said. `` We need to stand firm on these things,'' <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. `` The Soviets can not realistically expect us to now compromise away decisions which already have been negotiated and closed between the two parties.'' Calling the on-site inspection provisions of the new treaty the single most important aspect of the pact, <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> said that what happens in the next few days `` could be the beginning or the end of arms control.'' `` If the verification system is sound and stands the test of time, then the negotiations for future treaties will be given added chance of support and success,'' <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> said. `` But if now, when we are just on the verge of approval of the INF treaty, we allow its verification provisions to be unraveled by the Soviets, then the prospects of sound future arms control agreements will be dismal, very dismal indeed.'' <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> said the last-minute snag justifies the searching examination to which the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> put the new treaty since it was signed last December by <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. The process, he said, uncovered a number of flaws and unanswered questions, including whether or not the pact covered futuristic weapons such as those using laser or particle beams. `` If we had rushed in and approved the treaty, say a month ago, and then discovered these ambiguities and contradictions, the level of confidence of the country in our ability to reach good, solid agreements with the Soviets would have plummeted,'' <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> said.
