<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About 125 children and 30 adults suffered from smoke inhalation Thursday night after someone pulled the emergency brakes on an <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION> train while it was in a tunnel near Union Station, sending exhaust fumes spewing into the cars, officials said. The first and second cars of the Crescent, which operates daily between <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>, were evacuated. Approximately 125 school children and about 30 adult chaperones who occupied the first two cars were taken to several area hospitals where they were treated for possible smoke inhalation, said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON>, supervisor for the <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION>'s Emergency Ambulance Division The children and their supervisors had been planning to depart the train in <LOCATION> Birmingham </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>, said <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Clifford </PERSON> <PERSON> Black </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION> officials said the students are from <ORGANIZATION> Long </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Leaf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elementary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>. The Crescent departed <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> at 6:40 p.m. EDT going southbound with about 400 passengers and 18 crew members on board. It had two engines and 16 cars. `` At 6:45 p.m., as the train was in the tunnel, an unknown person for unknown reasons pulled the emergency brake,'' <PERSON> Black </PERSON> said. `` The train stopped with its emergency brakes applied in the tunnel'' as the second engine stalled or died. The train crew, thinking that an air hose that controls the brake system had parted accidentally, `` walked the train'' looking for such a problem, he said. After finding none, the crew searched the train's interior and found that the emergency brake handle in the first passenger car had been pulled, he said. Unable to release the brake, the crew shut down the remaining lead engine which was spewing out diesel smoke that entered the cars. Trains that leave <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> going south immediately enter a 3,900 foot tunnel that roughly goes under the grassy mall stretching from the Capitol to the Lincoln Memorial, <PERSON> Black </PERSON> said. Another Amtrak engine pulled the train back to Union Station, he said. By 9 p.m. buses were ordered to retrieve the children from the hospitals and take them to hotel for the night.
