<HEAD>Head of Cultural Office Brings Hope To Arts Community</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE CROCKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 On a recent Sunday, after a <LOCATION> Harlem </LOCATION> congregation prayed for a mother who threw her baby out a window and the pastor preached against drug abuse, a woman rose to advocate funding for the arts. `` We have some real problems. We have drugs. We have housing problems. We have a multitude of severe crises we have to face,'' acknowledged <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Schmidt </PERSON> <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON>, the city's cultural affairs commissioner. `` Why should we spend our time and our energy on culture? ... What claim do we have on the city's resources?'' she asked the flock of the <ORGANIZATION> Abyssinian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baptist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>, the city's oldest black house of worship _ the church made famous by the late <PERSON> Adam </PERSON> <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Powell </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>. And then she answered her own question `` Our culture,'' she said, `` has been our salvation.'' In the six months since <ORGANIZATION> Campbell </ORGANIZATION> succeeded <PERSON> Bess </PERSON> <PERSON> Myerson </PERSON> in one of the nation's most powerful arts posts _ overseeing a cultural budget that is second only to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Endowment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION> _ she has repeatedly argued for more arts money in a city where bridges are falling down, crime is ever escalating and level, untroubled ground is hard to find. She has also restored the morale of a department dispirited by the scandal that forced <PERSON> Myerson </PERSON> out of office and rekindled enthusiasm in the arts community. <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON> recalled the black heritage she and the congregation share: music and art dating back to the days of slavery in the <LOCATION> Americas </LOCATION>, and before that to the great kingdoms and societies of <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. When she mentioned the success of the Dance Theater of <LOCATION> Harlem </LOCATION> and noted that 98 percent of the young singers in the Boys Choir of <LOCATION> Harlem </LOCATION> go on to college, the audience applauded vigorously. Later, in an interview, the commissioner said, `` I'm really trying to accomplish a mentality, an attitude about the arts that recognizes that it is one of the most essential services that the city provides to its citizens. `` The real challenge for government is not to let itself get overwhelmed by its problems _ that is, begin to seek out and carve out real resources for opportunity.'' <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON>, 40, does not underestimate the difficulty of what she is trying to do. When she became commissioner last October, she had hopes of doubling the department's budget. However, two weeks after her appointment, the stock market crashed. Mayor <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> recently proposed that the agency cut $ 6 million from its current budget of $ 133 million for fiscal 1989. <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON> remains undaunted. Culture, she says, helps educate `` people who are going to be our leaders, who we have to think of as being the salvation for the city,'' and it helps in `` the reclamations'' of communities. Moreover, arts-related tourism is among the city's most important sources of revenue. During <PERSON> Myerson </PERSON>'s tenure, the importance of culture as something that was `` not just a leisure time activity ... had not been conveyed,'' said <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON>, quickly adding, `` not that I was critical of her personally.'' <PERSON> Myerson </PERSON>, a former Miss <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, was a glamorous presence at gala cultural events, and the public's interest in her put the relatively new and small Department of Cultural Affairs in the spotlight. The department is 11 years old -LRB- it had been lumped in with the parks department -RRB- and has about 55 employees. This year the department provided $ 66 million to 32 major cultural institutions ranging from the Metropolitan Museum of Art to <ORGANIZATION> El </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> del </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Barrio </ORGANIZATION> for operating and energy costs. It also distributed $ 13 million to arts groups in grant money for programs or projects such as the Metropolitan Opera's free performances in city parks. `` I think <PERSON> Bess </PERSON> was very concerned about bringing some visibility to the agency,'' said <PERSON> Kathleen </PERSON> <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON>, assistant commissioner for program services. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayworth </PERSON>, assistant commissioner for cultural institutions, agreed. `` She brought an immediacy, an understanding of the city's political life. But the controversy surrounding <PERSON> Myerson </PERSON>'s romantic involvement with millionaire <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> `` Andy'' <PERSON> Capasso </PERSON> took its toll on the department. She was accused of improperly influencing a judge presiding over his divorce case. `` It has been a difficult time for people here,'' <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON> said. `` I do n't think there's any denying that going through something like what we've been through in terms of publicity has an effect.'' <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON>, the daughter of a <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> family court judge, received a doctorate in humanities at <ORGANIZATION> Syracuse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, where she wrote a study of the late American artist <PERSON> Romare </PERSON> <PERSON> Bearden </PERSON>. As director of the Studio Museum of <LOCATION> Harlem </LOCATION> for 10 years, she transformed it from a struggling community arts project occupying two floors over a liquor store and fried chicken outlet into a premier fine arts museum focusing on black artists. It has a $ 2 million annual budget and is the only museum of its kind accredited by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museums </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON> also taught English literature for two years at <ORGANIZATION> Nkumbi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>, a school in <LOCATION> Zambia </LOCATION> for refugees from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. Those in the arts mainstream are eager to praise her. `` She's intelligent, energetic and a compatible person,'' said <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Segal </PERSON>, chairman emeritus of <ORGANIZATION> Lincoln </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> for the Performing Arts and chairman of the board of the upcoming <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Festival of the Arts. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Luers </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION>, said he's `` dazzled by her intelligence.'' `` One of the things that is difficult in government is to understand how museums work. She has come from a museum environment and she knows the issues. She knows the concerns, the weaknesses, the strengths,'' he said. <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON> knows, also, that <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> is the nation's cultural capital, and she is eager to exert <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s influence on the national scene.
