<HEAD>Sudan _ The Flight from Civil War</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DALIA BALIGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> once lived with her husband and five children in the relative comfort of a village in southern <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>. Today she lives in her nation's capital in a shack without water or sanitation, a refugee in her own country. A 5-year-old civil war in southern <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> chased the family away from their home, along with an estimated 820,000 other people, forced from their homes into lives of poverty, hunger and social ostracism. Mrs. <PERSON> Deng </PERSON>'s story is similar to those of many of the others. `` The army came into our village and took our cattle and killed many people,'' she said. `` My husband fled before me to get away from recruiters for both the army and the rebels. I joined him with our five children later.'' The Dengs are among the estimated 400,000 to 600,000 southerners who have crowded into eight camps around <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION>. They run in all directions, mainly toward <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>'s other cities, to become wards of an impoverished state More than a quarter million have fled even into neighboring, starving, war-torn <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>. Several thousand of those died because they arrived after long treks too weak to be saved. The refugees blame their plight on both sides in the war, rebels and soldiers, and the tribal and ethnic conflicts that are at the root of the fighting. About 6 million people remain in the south, where the population is mainly Christian and animist of African extraction. Sixteen million Arab-descended Moslems live in the dominant north. Because of the great religious and ethnic divisions between north and south, <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> has been torn by hostilities in the south for most of the 32 years since it asserted its independence from <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> on Jan. 1, 1956. But for hundreds of years before that, southern and northern tribes have fought over pastureland and water, northerners traditionally dominating as they do now. The current round of warfare began in the spring of 1983. The rebel leader, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Garang </PERSON>, is fighting for a greater share for the south of development money and of <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>'s potential wealth from petroleum and mineral reserves, mostly in the south. Southern tribes like <PERSON> Garang </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Dinka </ORGANIZATION> form the backbone of his <ORGANIZATION> Sudan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> SPLA </ORGANIZATION> -RRB-. The Sudanese army recruited <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> tribes and gave them modern weapons. `` In 1985, the government started a policy of arming <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> tribes to help in fighting the <ORGANIZATION> SPLA </ORGANIZATION>,'' said <PERSON> Sulaiman </PERSON> <PERSON> Baldo </PERSON>, a southerner who is a professor at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Khartoum </ORGANIZATION>. He told an interviewer the new automatic weapons enable <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> tribes to dominate in intertribal clashes. <PERSON> Baldo </PERSON> recently co-authored a book on an alleged massacre a year ago by an Arab tribe. He wrote that more than 1,000 Dinkas were burned to death as police and soldiers watched without intervening. The government denies the atrocity charges, maintaining that the victims died in cross fires. It also denies that it shirks its duty to displaced southerners. `` We give them help, but not just to anyone so that they do n't become encouraged and come to stay and be fed for free and not work,'' said el-Hag el-Tayeb, <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>'s acting commissioner for relief and rehabilitation The southerners in the <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION> camps, he added, are `` people who used to be producers and are now just consumers. They affect the city's already taxed infrastructure.'' In the civil war itself, the <ORGANIZATION> SPLA </ORGANIZATION> now controls most of the southern countryside, with government troops in control of a handful of large towns, diplomatic sources said. The fighting, nevertheless, has forced southerners to flee their cultivated land and their cattle. Non-combatant southerners who have remained in the combat area also are in a bad way, said a diplomatic source with access to military information. `` The <ORGANIZATION> SPLA </ORGANIZATION> go on recruiting trips into villages and attack them if the villagers refuse to support them,'' he said. `` The army troops view most Dinka youth as potential <ORGANIZATION> SPLA </ORGANIZATION> supporters.''
</TEXT>
