<HEAD>Japanese Leader Trying to Break Pro-U.S. Mold</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN K. PAULSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After six months in office, Prime Minister <PERSON> Noboru </PERSON> <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> still faces trade disputes with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and has been unable to break the pro-U.S. mold set by his predecessor, <PERSON> Yasuhiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Nakasone </PERSON>. His critics call his devotion to <PERSON> Nakasone </PERSON>'s policies his one big failure, while at least one admirer, <PERSON> Seizaburo </PERSON> <PERSON> Sato </PERSON>, an adviser to the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, said it is only natural for <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> to remain committed to them. `` <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> occupied many important positions in the Cabinet and the party, and he is committed to the policies of <PERSON> Nakasone </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Sato </PERSON> said. But others see signs that <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> finally is beginning to head off on his own course. `` I think he has not yet found his own way of solving problems, but he is on his way,'' said <PERSON> Rei </PERSON> <PERSON> Shiratori </PERSON>, professor of political science at <ORGANIZATION> Tokai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. But he added that one of <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON>'s biggest problems is `` the heavy burden left by former Prime Minister <PERSON> Nakasone </PERSON>, especially with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' Many Japanese feel <PERSON> Nakasone </PERSON> was too closely allied with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> himself has said the time had come for a change in Japan-U.S. relations. `` The international economic framework so long sustained by the overwhelming economic might of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is being transformed, and there is a need for <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> to join forces with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in supporting the international economy,'' he said in a policy speech. An editorial in the <ORGANIZATION> Asahi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shimbun </ORGANIZATION> in late April called on <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> to assert <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s independence from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policies. `` We want the prime minister to be aware that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> has become an important pillar for the West,'' the independent liberal newspaper said. `` It is now time for <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> to assert its own diplomacy, independent of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' On resolving major policy issues, <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> has a slim record so far. He achieved limited success in resolving a trade dispute with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> over lack of access to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s construction market, primarily because of the major influence of one of his Cabinet officials on <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s construction industry. However, talks with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials on liberalizing <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s beef and orange imports broke down, and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is seeking a resolution through the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade. <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON>'s administration was also unsuccessful in persuading President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to lift sanctions imposed last year on some Japanese products because of alleged violations of an agreement on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> access to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s computer chip market. <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> also was unable to prevent the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> from passing a sweeping trade bill that includes sanctions against Japanese companies. He is relying heavily on <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to veto the bill. The prime minister's major test at home will come later this year, when the Diet, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s national legislature, considers a tax reform package that <PERSON> Nakasone </PERSON> desperately wanted, but was unable to get. Many Japanese say the current tax system is unfair. New proposals call for taxes on capital gains from the sale of securities, the elimination of tax privileges for doctors, the cutting of provisions that allow some people to estimate their income, and taxation of farmland.
</TEXT>
