<HEAD>A Black Community Refuses To Move</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OUKASIE, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A government accustomed to getting its way has met its match in this ramshackle black township, which officially does n't exist. For years, white authorities have been trying to coax or coerce the people of <PERSON> Oukasie </PERSON> into moving to a newer township 12 miles away. Officials legally abolished <PERSON> Oukasie </PERSON> in 1986, but about 8,000 residents remain and are determined to stay. In April, the government declared the 55-year-old township an `` emergency camp'' subject to severe new regulations. Rents were raised by 50 percent, unauthorized visitors will be barred as of June 1, and permits are required to renovate homes, keep pets or take in lodgers. Members of the community believe the government seeks to demoralize them so they will give up and move. That would enable the authorities to eliminate <PERSON> Oukasie </PERSON> without resorting to forced removal, a policy the government claims to have abandoned. <PERSON> Oukasie </PERSON> residents say they wo n't give in to the pressure. `` Sometimes in life you get tired of being harassed and moved about,'' said <PERSON> Sello </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramakobye </PERSON>, a spokesman for <PERSON> Oukasie </PERSON>'s civic association. `` You decide it's time to resist.'' The official reason for <PERSON> Oukasie </PERSON>'s intended demise is that the government considers it an unhealthy slum, beyond rehabilitation because of `` astronomic costs.'' Residents commissioned a study of their own that found upgrading would cost 3 million rands -LRB- $ 1.4 million -RRB-. They say this would be cheaper than relocating all of them at the new township, <LOCATION> Lethlabile </LOCATION>, and they believe the government's real reason for wanting <PERSON> Oukasie </PERSON> shut down is that it is just a few hundreds yards from Brits, a white suburb 30 miles west of <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s capital. Brits is a stronghold of the far-right <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. Its white residents have displayed little sympathy for their black neighbors, who are able to walk to their jobs in Brits but would have to pay for transport if they moved to <LOCATION> Lethlabile </LOCATION>. Because of government funding, <PERSON> Lethlabile </PERSON> has advantages over <PERSON> Oukasie </PERSON>, and some of the 5,000 former <PERSON> Oukasie </PERSON> residents who have moved there are pleased with their choice. The new township's streets are smooth, its homes have electricity and plumbing A few houses are relatively lavish, with patios and two-car garages. <PERSON> Oukasie </PERSON> is overcrowded and dilapidated. Many homes are in ruins, demolished by former owners as a prerequisite for getting state compensation to move to <LOCATION> Lethlabile </LOCATION>. The only services provided are water from communal taps and removal of waste from bucket toilets. But <PERSON> Oukasie </PERSON> has certain charms. Trees, a rare sight in many townships, are abundant, and well-tended gardens adjoin even some of the sorriest-looking metal shacks. Two soccer fields are maintained diligently by local youths. `` Everything we want to do, we do it ourselves,'' said <PERSON> Elias </PERSON> <PERSON> Sithole </PERSON>, a 39-year-old former carpenter. He is one of an estimated 50 percent of the adult population that is unemployed, and says job-seeking from <LOCATION> Lethlabile </LOCATION> would be costly and difficult. Other jobless residents do n't want to move because they have improved their homes in <PERSON> Oukasie </PERSON> over the years and ca n't afford houses in <LOCATION> Lethlabile </LOCATION>, except for the small metal huts allocated to newcomers. `` The social structure in <PERSON> Oukasie </PERSON> is so coherent,'' said <PERSON> Ramakobye </PERSON>. `` It's wrong to destroy it. In <LOCATION> Lethlabile </LOCATION>, everybody is for himself.'' <PERSON> Oukasie </PERSON> residents also are wary of <PERSON> Lethlabile </PERSON>'s proximity to the nominally independent black homeland of <LOCATION> Bophuthatswana </LOCATION>. They fear the new township will be incorporated into the homeland, thus depriving residents of South African citizenship. `` No one is going to volunteer to go to <LOCATION> Lethlabile </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Sithole </PERSON>. `` The government thinks everybody is going to be scared into going, but it will take force. You should see the unity of these people.'' <PERSON> Sithole </PERSON> guided visitors to the edge of the nearby white suburb, where a concrete moat filled with dark green muck separates handsome, new hillside homes from a dirt road leading to <PERSON> Oukasie </PERSON>. `` How can they say it's too expensive to upgrade <PERSON> Oukasie </PERSON> when they upgrade their mountain?'' he said. Raw sewage from whites' homes runs into a gully next to the township. <PERSON> Sithole </PERSON> said <PERSON> Oukasie </PERSON> residents are somewhat cynical about white complaints that the black community smells.
</TEXT>
