<HEAD>Joseph Campbell's Mythology Featured on PBS</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BARR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON> made his career teaching about life, as comprehended in the myths or stories people tell about themselves and the universe. Half a year after his death, public television offers a stimulating seminar with the great teacher starting May 16 with `` The Hero's Journey,'' a one-hour documentary about <ORGANIZATION> Campbell </ORGANIZATION>. A week later, <ORGANIZATION> PBS </ORGANIZATION> begins a six-week series of <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Moyers </PERSON>' conversations with <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON> in `` <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON> and the Power of Myth. `` The Hero's Journey'' is a useful introduction to <ORGANIZATION> Campbell </ORGANIZATION>'s ideas about mythology and his core conviction: `` There is one mythology in the world,'' with variations called Christianity, <ORGANIZATION> Islam </ORGANIZATION>, Buddhism and so on A myth, in this sense, is not a lie, but a metaphor for the experience of life. So, to <ORGANIZATION> Campbell </ORGANIZATION>, the idea of God is not true or false. `` God is a metaphor for a mystery that absolutely transcends all human categories of thought, even the categories of being and non-being.'' The metaphor is valid, he says, if `` it is putting you in touch with the mystery that is the ground of your own being. If it is n't, it's a lie.'' Though `` <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON> and the Power of Myth'' is simply the two men talking, it may be the most compelling television series this year. The conversation is strewn with ideas that will be enlightening, provocative and at times maddening. The success of the series may be measured by the number of times a viewer will want to argue, and by the conversations that begin after the TV is switched off. <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON>, who taught at <ORGANIZATION> Sarah </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lawrence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> for 38 years, died Oct. 30 in <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION> at age 83. He left an extensive record of his work in books, including `` The Hero with a Thousand Faces'' and `` The Masks of God.'' `` He is a writer of important scholarship, but you do n't find the person in the writing,'' <PERSON> Moyers </PERSON> said in a recent interview. `` You find the mind there, but not the personality, not the power of the individual that comes through any great teacher. That's why I wanted to do so much with him. We would have his works, but we would n't have his teaching. Teachers have to be experienced, they ca n't be read.'' <PERSON> Moyers </PERSON> did n't know much about <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON> when they met in 1979 for an interview that appeared two years later on `` <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Moyers </PERSON>' Journal'' on PBS `` We had over 14,000 requests for a transcript, so I knew I had touched a chord,'' <PERSON> Moyers </PERSON> said. `` Even without the requests, I knew he had touched a chord because he moved me. He opened my eyes. He connected what had been unrelated phenomena in my own experience in life.'' For this series, <PERSON> Moyers </PERSON> taped 23 hours of interviews and spent many more hours in informal conversations. `` We became pretty good friends, more so than I usually do with somebody I put on the air because I do n't have that much time with them,'' <PERSON> Moyers </PERSON> said. `` I was his perpetual student, his graduate student for life.'' <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON> was raised as a Roman Catholic and fondly recalled that experience as `` powerful, life-supporting and beautiful.'' But, like many another believer, his faith was derailed by <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Darwin </PERSON>. `` The thing that saved me,'' he says, `` was the <ORGANIZATION> Upanishads </ORGANIZATION> _ <LOCATION> Hinduism </LOCATION>.'' In those texts, he says in `` The Hero's Journey,'' he found the same mythology as in <ORGANIZATION> Christianity </ORGANIZATION>, without the insistence that the stories were historically true. <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON> `` is the most spiritual man I ever met,'' <PERSON> Moyers </PERSON> said, but he knows that this series will not be welcomed by fundamentalists. `` What I took him as saying is that all religion is true, and if it works for you, fine,'' said <PERSON> Moyers </PERSON>. `` If it does in fact lead you to love the lord thy god with all thy heart, with all thy soul, with all thy mind and thy neighbor as thyself, fine. You do n't have to move on to this other angle of seeing ... `` Faith,'' <PERSON> Moyers </PERSON> added, `` is an excruciatingly personal choice or rejection. Your idea of God may be terribly dissatisfying to me, which is why I love the democratic way which is that you ca n't impose it on me. <PERSON> Moyers </PERSON>' interviews with <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON> are also the basis for a book, `` The Power of Myth,'' compiled by <PERSON> Betty </PERSON> <PERSON> Sue </PERSON> <PERSON> Flowers </PERSON>, a professor at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION>. It will be published this month by <PERSON> Doubleday </PERSON>. <PERSON> Moyers </PERSON> said the book was initiated by <PERSON> Jacqueline </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> <PERSON> Onassis </PERSON>, an editor at Doubleday. <PERSON> Moyers </PERSON> said Mrs. <PERSON> Onassis </PERSON> had been impressed by the earlier interviews in which <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON> talked about the mythic significance of <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>'s funeral and of the `` ancient mythological symbol, the widow who helps us all come to terms with our grief when the ruler is killed.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Elsewhere in television: BACK TO UNREALITY _ Due to the veritable abyss left in the entertainment world by the absence of `` That's Incredible!'' from the airwaves, hyperbolic hosts <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Davidson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Cathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Crosby </PERSON> and <PERSON> Fran </PERSON> <PERSON> Tarkenton </PERSON> will engage in a reunion special on <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> on May 22. <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> promises the one-hour special will include a man kissing a deadly cobra on the mouth, another putting a red-hot metal bar into his mouth and yet another blowing bubbles `` into unique and unusual shapes.'' Not to be mythed.
</TEXT>
