<HEAD>Oscar's Golden Touch Might Not Glitter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A month after the 60th Academy Awards, evidence persists that the Oscar's golden touch does n't always live up to its reputation. <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pictures </ORGANIZATION> had hoped that the sweep of nine Oscars by `` The Last Emperor'' would result in a box-office bonanza. But despite doubling the number of theaters to more than 800 after the awards, the Chinese epic has added only $ 10 million to theater grosses. After 164 days in release, `` The Last Emperor'' had sold $ 36.6 million worth of tickets in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. By comparison, the ghostly comedy `` ` Beetlejuice'' grossed $ 46.7 million in just 33 days. Still, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Spitz </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION>'s domestic distribution, maintains `` The Last Emperor'' has had a very good performance since the awards. `` Comparing ` The Last Emperor' to ` Beetlejuice' is like comparing apples to oranges,'' he said. `` ` The Last Emperor' will never have the teen-age audience that ` Beetlejuice' has.'' <PERSON> Spitz </PERSON> predicted the <PERSON> Bernardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Bertolucci </PERSON> film will continue doing good business through Memorial Day and will remain in distribution for a long time. `` Moonstruck,'' which collected acting awards for <PERSON> Cher </PERSON> and <PERSON> Olympia </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, has added $ 10 million since the Oscars, bringing its total to $ 69 million. The figure is impressive, since the film had been in wide release for more than two months. Much has been written about how winning Oscars can inflate actors' salaries. With one exception, this year's winners seem unlikely to boost their paychecks. Since `` Romancing the Stone'' and `` Fatal Attraction,'' <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> has become one of the most in-demand stars in <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>. His win for `` Wall Street'' will have little effect on <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON>, who sometimes produces his own films -LRB- `` The <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> Syndrome,'' `` Jewel of the Nile'' -RRB-. <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON>' next film is for <PERSON> Sherry </PERSON> <PERSON> Lansing </PERSON> and <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaffe </PERSON>, who produced `` Fatal Attraction.'' In `` Black Rain,'' he will play an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> police officer trying to solve a murder by the Yakusa, the Japanese Mafia. Having appeared in `` The Witches of Eastwick,'' `` Suspect'' and `` Moonstruck'' in 1987, <PERSON> Cher </PERSON> can afford a rest. No new films have been announced for her in the wake of the Oscar, but the scripts must be piling up at her door. Meanwhile, she will collect a fortune with her Las Vegas act. <PERSON> Sean </PERSON> <PERSON> Connery </PERSON>, winner as supporting actor in `` The Untouchables,'' needs no help from Oscar or anyone else in his career. He has been a top wage earner since his <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Bond </PERSON> days. He'll appear this summer in `` Presidio'' with <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Harmon </PERSON>, and works next as <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON> <PERSON> Ford </PERSON>'s father in the third `` Indiana Jones'' movie. <PERSON> Olympia </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> seems to be the major recipient of Oscar's beneficence Although a distinguished stage actress, she was little known before `` Moonstruck.'' Since her nomination, she has been able to decline two offers for television series. She has accepted a small role in <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Nichols </PERSON>' `` Working Girls,'' which stars <PERSON> Melanie </PERSON> <PERSON> Griffith </PERSON>, <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON> <PERSON> Ford </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sigourney </PERSON> <PERSON> Weaver </PERSON>, but her agents predict big things for her. The April 11 Oscar show drew generally poor notices but also the best television rating in years. `` The ratings show that we did n't lose our audience, even during a sweep -LRB- by ` The Last Emperor' -RRB-,'' said <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldwyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> who produced the show for the Academy. `` I tried to prevent that by putting a heavy load of comedy -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Robin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Williams </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> -RRB- toward the end. The audience stayed with us.'' <PERSON> Goldwyn </PERSON> recognized the problems in moving to the Shrine Auditorium with its poor acoustics, and the horendous traffic jam. `` But those problems can be solved. I think we benefited from having 6,000 in the theater; it was a much warmer audience.'' The Music Center, where the awards show previously was staged, held only 2,000 people. Most critics lambasted the 3 -LCB- - hour broadcast time, and <PERSON> Goldwyn </PERSON> commented that the Academy will have to address that problem `` There are certain things in the show that the Academy is interested in but the public is n't,'' he said. Efforts to eliminate such awards as short subjects, documentaries and animation from the show have so far failed to achieve Board of Governors approval. <PERSON> Will </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldwyn </PERSON> be around next year to help deal with such problems? `` Not on your life,'' he said. `` Two years is enough.''
</TEXT>
