 <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> bishops have consistently opposed <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military aid to the Contra rebels in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, but the bishops applaud humanitarian aid. It is `` a sign of hope that all sides may now be workng to forge a lasting and just peace,'' says Archbishop <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> May </PERSON> of <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bishops </ORGANIZATION>. He said in a letter to <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s Cardinal <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> <PERSON> Obando </PERSON> y Bravo that the aid both would help war victims and sustain the contras while the peace process goes forward.
