<TEXT>
 Although studies have indicated that most successful career women are single, divorced or childless, a study of successful Jewish career women finds that most are married and have children. In the study sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jewish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Lilith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Magazine </ORGANIZATION>, a Jewish feminist quarterly, questionaire responses from 944 Jewish career women showed 603 had married and had children. Most `` were embedded in a ` superwoman' syndrome, daily juggling multiple role obligations,'' the findings say.
