<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Methodist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> has developed a policy on AIDS in the workplace, saying the disease is not spread by casual contact and protecting the jobs and privacy of any employes who have it. If `` unable to perform their normal job duties because of their illness,'' workers with AIDS would be given disability leaves, the policy says. Employees who refuse to work alongside people with AIDS could go on unpaid leaves or apply for other publishing house jobs. The policy is `` to protect the rights of all our employees,'' says <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tippens </PERSON>, a vice president, who adds that so far, no cases of AIDS have been reported among the agency's 1,300 employes.
