<HEAD>The Two Educations of Afghanistan's Young</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCHEHEREZADE FARAMARZI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PESHAWAR, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Fourteen-year-old <PERSON> Noorieh </PERSON> <PERSON> Mazloumpoor </PERSON> has had two educations in her young life _ one Moslem, the other Marxist. She got her Marxist education in her homeland, <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. As a refugee with her family in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> for the past two years, her education has been based on Islam, her religion. She is typical of Afghan children who have been taught two conflicting ideologies over the past decade of war in their country. Now with the Soviet military withdrawal from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, the children who have had an Islamic education in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> will be returning home to join those whose education was wholly Marxist. The gap may be wide, but students interviewed here were confident it wo n't deter them from reuniting their country in the long run. <PERSON> Noorieh </PERSON> went to school in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s capital, until she was 12. In <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, she enrolled in a Moslem school run by the guerrillas fighting the Soviet-backed Afghan government. Like many of her classmates, she has had to switch from courses that taught Communist doctrine to interpretations of the Koran, the Moslem holy book. In <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, she said, she was taught that it was her `` duty to serve the country, the masses, the revolution and the fruits of history.'' At her refugee school in <LOCATION> Peshawar </LOCATION>, the blue cover of her Persian language text book has a map identifying her country as `` Moslem Afghanistan.'' Another map in the book carries the Koranic verse, `` There is no god but Allah. <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> is his prophet.'' Refugee books published by the guerrillas' Afghan education council also teach: `` The future of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> should be reconstructed on the principles of Islamic culture.'' `` Eventually we will have to reconcile the two,'' said <PERSON> Ehsanollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Poopal </PERSON>, 17-year-old 10th grader. `` It's going to take a lot of effort, patience. They have their reasons and we have ours.'' <PERSON> Poopal </PERSON>, however, said he will not accept the Communist teachings and will try to explain to his classmates back home why his beliefs are different. Another refugee student, 15-year-old <PERSON> Mehrafsa </PERSON>, said he thinks it is going to be difficult in the beginning. `` We are going to suffer first, especially to see our friends are led toward a corrupt path, taught bad values. But I do n't think it will be too long before we understand each other. I do n't think the gap will affect the country in the long run.'' <PERSON> Wassimeh </PERSON>, 24, a teacher at one of the refugee schools, believes Moslem education will continue when the children among the 3 million refugees in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> return home. <PERSON> Maliheh </PERSON> <PERSON> Malekzad </PERSON>, 28, an mathematics teacher, said she taught at a <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> school until two years ago. She added that unless a teacher was a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, there was no hope of promotion. `` It is very difficult for a Moslem not to be able to express her religious viewpoint and to be taunted for her belief,'' she said. Schools in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, according to the teachers and students here, have their own party recruitment bodies _ the scouts, the first stage of Communist `` indoctrination,'' and the youth organization, where Russian culture and language are taught, and where some are given schoolarships to study in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. The third stage is the older youth organization where advanced Communist books are read outside the school curriculum. Ms. <PERSON> Malekzad </PERSON> said the refugee schools here are good at teaching theories but poor in practical education. The walls and classrooms are adorned with guerrilla posters, and during class, the students sing: `` I cry for my motherland, I cry for its martyr. Wherever I turn, I see broken limbs.'' But 9-year-old <PERSON> Godsiyeh </PERSON> <PERSON> Amir </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> said she likes studying Islam because it will `` make me go to heaven.''
</TEXT>
