<NOTE>For Release Thu AMs, May 19, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Nile River Running Dry Bringing Threat of Egyptian Power Shortage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DALIA BALIGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> built the <LOCATION> Aswan </LOCATION> High Dam two decades ago as a safeguard against the whims of the <LOCATION> Nile </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. But the worst drought in 70 years has dangerously lowered water levels and threatens to shut down the dam's electric-power generators. The government is using television jingles and newspaper campaigns to urge Egyptians to conserve water and electricity. President <PERSON> Hosni </PERSON> <PERSON> Mubarak </PERSON> warned on television that thousands of villages could go dark this summer unless the eight-year-long drought upriver eases. He said the water of <PERSON> Lake </PERSON> <PERSON> Nasser </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Aswan </LOCATION> dam's 1,335-square-mile reservoir, is perilously close to a level impossible to sustain electricity generation The dam, built during the 1960s with Soviet help and inaugurated in 1971, was intended mainly to end annual killer floods. It also was to provide adequate Nile water to irrigate <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>'s agricultural heartland along its banks. In addition, it supplies 30 percent of <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>'s electricity. Experts say agricultural production has escaped serious harm so far but could be affected by another year of drought. Agriculture was the main casualty from the <LOCATION> Nile </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>'s last serious drought, which began in 1913 and continued for seven years. In the current drought, the high dam has been credited with sparing <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> the famine that has spread across <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> upriver. But the prolonged lack of rainfall at the Ugandan and Ethiopian headwaters of the White Nile and <ORGANIZATION> Blue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nile </ORGANIZATION> has lowered the river's level in <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> by more than 69 feet at the high dam. The water surface is now 508 feet above sea level. Summer rains in <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> normally provide the <LOCATION> Nile </LOCATION> with 84 percent of its water. This past January, the month when the river is always at its shallowest, houseboats were high and dry in <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION>, 600 miles downstream from <LOCATION> Aswan </LOCATION>, for the first time in anyone's memory. Nile cruises from <LOCATION> Luxor </LOCATION>, 450 miles south of <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION>, to <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Simbel </PERSON> were abandoned or started upstream from <LOCATION> Luxor </LOCATION>. Trans-Nile ferry service was halted at <LOCATION> Luxor </LOCATION> for a while last year, and long-time residents reported more land outcroppings in the Nile's dark, murky water than ever before. <PERSON> Maher </PERSON> <PERSON> Abaza </PERSON>, the minister of electricity and energy, sounded the alarm almost a year ago, cautioning against increased consumption and waste of electricity and water. Consumption continued to climb, however, and official figures indicate that at least 45 percent of <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION>'s share of the Nile waters is wasted by negligence and the city's outmoded water system. Current predictions hold that the water level at the dam will decrease to 495 feet above sea level by July, <PERSON> Abaza </PERSON> said in a recent interview. `` That will mean that the dam will be able to work only at half capacity, producing 900 megawatts,'' <PERSON> Abaza </PERSON> said. `` If the level goes under 147 meters -LRB- 485 feet -RRB-, ... production of the high dam will be zero.'' He added that generating plants are producing electricity as fast as they can now just to keep up with an ever-increasing demand. Much of the increase in demand has been in the countryside, where peasants returning from well-paying jobs in <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabian </LOCATION> oil regions have come home with electric fans, ovens and television sets. <PERSON> Mubarak </PERSON> said in his TV address that if high-dam generation stops, the government will have to keep factories working by cutting off power to some of the country's 5,000 villages. <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>'s 54 million people use 45 billion kilowatt-hours of electricity, increasing by up to 20 percent a year. Figures indicate that the steady increase is due to what Egyptians regard as luxury items, such as air conditioners and color television sets. `` Egyptians open their taps and find water, and switch on the light and everything lights up, and they think that it is easy and will remain that way,'' said <PERSON> Abaza </PERSON>. `` But they have to start cooperating and curbing their consumption or there are going to be serious consequences.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thu AMs, May 19</NOTE>
