<SECOND>AM-Chile-Watchers, Adv 20,0725</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv20</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri AMs, May 20, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>200,000 Volunteer To Watch Presidential Balloting in Chile</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDUARDO GALLARDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 With a little financial help from abroad and a lot of enthusiasm from 200,000 volunteers, opponents of <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>'s military government have launched a campaign they say will keep fraud out of this year's presidential election. Ten opposition parties, from left to right, have united in the campaign of door-to-door voter education, poll-watching on election day and independent vote counting afterward. Leaders of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democracy </ORGANIZATION> maintain that the system is necessary because they believe fraud tipped a 1980 plebiscite to approve a government-drafted constitution. <PERSON> Genaro </PERSON> <PERSON> Arriagada </PERSON>, secretary general of the command, said the 1980 plebiscite, in which the government received 67 percent of the vote, `` lacked the minimal conditions necessary to guarantee any honest election.'' That vote took place without voter registries, because the old ones had been destroyed by the military shortly after they seized power in 1973. Polling stations were manned only by government-appointed officials, without any opposition or independent supervision. <PERSON> Arriagada </PERSON> said a national census taken two years after the vote showed that in several cities the number of people who voted in the plebiscite was higher than the number of residents in the cities. The government has denied accusations of fraud. `` The upcoming presidential plebiscite will be very different,'' <PERSON> Arriagada </PERSON> said. He said voter registries now have reopened, `` and this time we have the capacity to guarantee a clean vote.'' In the plebiscite scheduled for an unspecified date later this year, Chileans will be able to vote `` yes'' or `` no'' on a single, military-appointed candidate for the 1989-97 presidential term. If the candidate is rejected by voters, a competitive election will take place a year later. President <PERSON> Augusto </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>, the 73-year-old army commander who has ruled since 1973, is considered the most likely candidate. <PERSON> Ricardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Lagos </PERSON>, leader of the <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and a key member of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION>, said 700 specialists are training the 200,000 volunteers throughout the country to work as poll-watchers on election day. He added in an interview that the opposition will be able to have three to five monitors at each of the 20,000 or so voting places. `` We can guarantee to every citizen that his vote will be properly accounted for, and that it will remain secret,'' <LOCATION> Lagos </LOCATION> said. Some volunteers have already visited hundreds of thousands of voters in the door-to-door campaign to `` explain to them that this time the vote will be totally clean,'' he said. <LOCATION> Lagos </LOCATION> added that part of the financing for the campaign has come `` from groups abroad interested in the restoration of democracy in <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>.'' He said the cost is relatively low, however. He estimated his <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> will spend the equivalent of around $ 100,000. <LOCATION> Lagos </LOCATION> did no identify the foreign groups sending money, but the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Endowment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democracy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> States </ORGANIZATION> and several West European foundations, especially in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>, have been officially reported in the past as granting financial aid to Chilean democratic dissident groups. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> also has organized a nationwide computerized vote-counting system to operate independently of the government system. <PERSON> Eduardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Arriagada </PERSON>, an engineer in charge of the Vote Counting Center said `` we will be able to quickly deliver a projection of the vote and complete returns.'' <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Campana </PERSON>, a leading electoral expert of the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, the largest in the opposition, said, `` The system we are implementing fully guarantees a clean vote. There will be no fraud this time. Chileans can rest assured of that.'' <PERSON> Campana </PERSON> said volunteers trained as poll-monitors show `` an enormous enthusiasm.'' `` Many of them are paying for their travel and other expenses connected with the campaign out of their own pockets.'' <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Gabriel </PERSON> <PERSON> Valdes </PERSON>, who works at the Vote Counting Center, said, however, old legislation granting the government emergency powers could still be invoked. `` That legislation, for example, would allow the government to prevent us from announcing the returns we will be gathering,'' <PERSON> Valdes </PERSON> said. That, said <LOCATION> Lagos </LOCATION>, is `` the only fraud possibility that remains open.''
</TEXT>
