 <PERSON> Koslov </PERSON> was stronger in his criticism of the secrecy. `` I think it was handled very badly. There was no reason why they could n't have informed the embassy personnel early on ... The lesson learned is to treat your people as though they have some intelligence.'' After the radiation problem became publicly known in 1976, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> denied press reports _ including a story in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> government newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION> _ that the problem was exacerbated by radio-frequency and microwave emissions from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> equipment. But a Dec. 5, 1975 <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> memorandum dealing with the Soviet beams said: `` Some embassy staff members probably have received much larger exposures of electromagnetic radiation due to leakage in coaxial cable shields for cables running through the embassy interior from transmitters to antennas. This problem may not be limited to the embassy in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>.'' In other documents, the <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Myers </PERSON> also expressed concern over high-frequency radio radiation induced in telephone and other wiring leading into the ambassador's ninth-floor office, due to spillover from a miniloop antenna mounted outside. The antenna was subsequently moved to a different location on the embassy roof. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Brodeur </PERSON>, author of `` The Zapping of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' a book dealing with the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> embassy affair and other cases of microwave exposure, said he had been told by intelligence sources, whom he declined to identify, that `` there was always a question whether our own electronic countermeasures within the embassy were responsible for some of the irradiation of the employees.'' `` A good many of the biological-medical problems at the embassy may well have been caused by our own efforts to jam the low-level incoming <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> signals,'' <PERSON> Brodeur </PERSON> said. The belated disclosure of the microwave bombardment prompted a series of administrative claims and lawsuits against the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government by employees and dependents who alleged that they had suffered health injuries because of exposure to the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> beams. To help defend itself against such legal actions, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> in 1976-78 funded a $ 1 million epidemiological study of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> embassy personnel, carried out under contract by the <ORGANIZATION> Johns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hopkins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hygiene </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION>. Dr. <PERSON> Pollack </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> medical consultant, said that `` without that <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON> study, State would be sitting in the soup, because there were about $ 250 million in tort actions on the books. And every one of those has been withdrawn without a penny being paid.'' `` There were about 100 some-odd actions,'' <PERSON> Pollack </PERSON> said. A <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> woman whose son was born with spina bifida, a serious birth defect, declined to comment in detail on the status of an administrative claim she brought against the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> in 1977. The woman, who asked that her name not be used, said regarding the possibility that her son's birth defect may have been linked to microwave exposure in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>: `` The only thing I can say is that it's impossible to know. ... There's no way we'll ever, ever know. That's the one thing I have learned.'' Another case involved a $ 1.75 million suit brought against the government on behalf of a boy born in 1973 with severe hydrocephalus, a birth defect of the brain and central nervous system. The boy's father had served in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> as a <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> security guard. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Danelo </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> attorney, said the suit brought in federal court in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> alleged injury due to microwave radiation as well as medical malpractice at <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> hospitals. The microwave part of the suit was dismissed by the trial court. The court cited what is known as the Feres doctrine, under which the federal government can not be held liable for injuries suffered by active-duty military personnel _ or, in this case, for a child's physical injuries derived from his father's active-duty injury <PERSON> Danelo </PERSON> said the malpractice part of the case also proved unsuccessful. <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rowan </PERSON> <PERSON> Gaither </PERSON>, an official at the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s Office of the Legal Adviser, said, `` we had a group of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> microwave files and they were all retired because they were not being actively pursued.'' He said he was unable to confirm <PERSON> Pollack </PERSON>'s figures on the total number and dollar amount of the claims because the files have been sent to a federal records storage center in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>. The <PERSON> Johns </PERSON> <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON> epidemiological study, released in November 1978, concluded that `` no convincing evidence was discovered that would directly implicate the exposure to microwave radiation by the employees at the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> embassy in the causation of any adverse health effects as of the time of this analysis.'' Critics of the study, however, have voiced concern over the use of employees and dependents from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> embassies and consulates in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> as a control group for comparison to the health experience of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> embassy personnel. A confidential draft version of the study report itself noted that some of the members of the control group could have been exposed `` to microwave surveillance.'' `` This was of concern, especially since several participants in the study informed us that there indeed was surveillance using microwave technology at some of the comparison posts,'' the draft document said. This section was deleted in the final version of the report. According to the minutes of an Oct. 17, 1978 meeting of Dr. <PERSON> Pollack </PERSON> with members of the study staff, it was deleted because it was `` really heresay.'' At the recommendation of the health study team, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> contracted with the <ORGANIZATION> Johns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hopkins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Applied </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Physics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> for preparation of a retrospective technical analysis of the complex microwave radiation fields monitored within the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> embassy. The findings of this technical analysis were evaluated by the <ORGANIZATION> Electromagnetic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radiation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advisory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, known as ERMAC, a now-defunct scientific panel that operated under the aegis of the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telecommunications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. In June 1981, a report issued by <ORGANIZATION> NTIA </ORGANIZATION> said the 14-member advisory panel `` agreed that there is no scientific evidence, nor are there any theoretical grounds to suggest that biological effects would be expected to occur from the type and low levels of exposure presented. Consequently, <ORGANIZATION> ERMAC </ORGANIZATION> concluded that no deleterious biological effects to personnel would be anticipated from the microwave exposures at the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>.'' However, several experts on non-ionizing radiation say they believe the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and ERMAC may well have jumped to scientifically unwarranted conclusions in seeking to rule out possible health effects on personnel exposed to the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> radiation. Among them is the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Steneck </PERSON>, who cited a variety of studies that have been done over the past few years _ since the 1976-78 <PERSON> Johns </PERSON> <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON> epidemiological survey _ finding significant effects at very low radiation power levels. `` I can see no reason why I would rest easier today than I would have 10 years ago,'' he said. `` ... As we learn more and more about the ways in which this radiation can interact with the body, we find that there are more subtle ways than we initially suspected.''
