<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here is a chronology, from public records, declassified documents and interviews, of major developments concerning the Soviet microwave bombardment of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>: October 1953: Embassy security officers initially detect intermittent Soviet-source microwave transmissions. Late 1962-early 1963: Electronic measurements confirm that the signal, code-named TUMS -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Technically </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unidentified </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Signal </ORGANIZATION> -RRB-, is a directional microwave beam aimed at the back of the embassy from a fifth-floor window of an apartment building 100 yards to the west. TUMS is a mix of frequencies ranging from 2.5 to 4.1 GHz -LRB- gigahertz -RRB- and operates at typical maximum power levels of 1 to 3 microwatts per square centimeter. April 4, 1965: The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> asks doctors at the <ORGANIZATION> Naval </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Bethesda </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, to conduct special eye examinations and electroencephalogram tests on personnel departing for and returning from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. April 16, 1965: The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Surveillance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countermeasures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> meets to discuss the microwave problem. It requests all member agencies to review medical records of personnel assigned to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> since 1953 for `` possible clinical changes'' that may be linked with exposure to the radiation. March 29, 1966: The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> signs a contract with <ORGANIZATION> George </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> for cytogenetic testing of blood samples from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> and control group personnel. The program is conducted under the cover story of a `` <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> Viral Study.'' June 23-25, 1967: Secretary of State Dean <PERSON> Rusk </PERSON> lodges a protest over the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> radiation with Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Andrei </PERSON> <PERSON> Gromyko </PERSON> during a summit meeting in <LOCATION> Glassboro </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION> Dec. 20, 1968: A scientific review panel begins to evaluate results from the Pandora Project, a secret research effort involving irradiation of monkeys with a `` synthetic <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> signal.'' April 21, 1969: The <PERSON> Pandora </PERSON> review panel recommends that the experimental program be expanded to include testing of human volunteers exposed to low-level microwaves for six to eight months. June 27, 1969: The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> decides to terminate the cytogenetic testing program, on the grounds that the test results were not confirmed by outside medical specialists. Jan. 12, 1970: The Pandora review panel recommends that the research project, conducted primarily at <ORGANIZATION> Walter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION>, be phased out because re-evaluation of the experimental data showed `` no clear and strong effects.'' March 1972: Another signal, code-named SMUT, goes on the air at power levels of less than 1 microwatt and operates intermittently until June 1975. With frequencies of 3.2 to 3.7 GHz, it is beamed from a transmitter about one-half mile northeast of the embassy. May 26, 1975: TUMS ceases operation. May 28, 1975: A Soviet signal code-named MUTS-1 begins daily operation from a transmitter on the roof of an apartment building 80 yards east of the embassy. It is a complex, broadband signal with frequencies in the range of 0.6 to 9.6 GHz and typical maximum power levels of 10 to 12 microwatts. Oct. 16, 1975: Another microwave beam, dubbed MUTS-2, is detected coming from the top of a building 80 yards south of the embassy, with a frequency range comparable to MUTS-1 but lower power levels of 1 to 2 microwatts. While TUMS had operated for about five to eight hours a day, MUTS-1 and MUTS-2 are in operation for up to 14 hours daily, with one or both the signals irradiating the embassy for a total of 18 to 20 hours a day. Jan. 26-30, 1976: A team of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> experts meets with Soviet officials in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> in an effort to persuade the Russians to cease irradiating the embassy. The talks prove fruitless, with the Soviets contending that the microwaves detected at the embassy are simply background radiation from broadcast and industrial sources. Feb. 6, 1976: Ambassador <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stoessel </PERSON> begins a series of classified briefings on the microwave problem for <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> embassy employees and dependents. Word of the briefings leaks to <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> correspondents. Security officers and military personnel start installing window screening to reduce penetration of the microwave beams into the building. Feb. 12, 1976: Secretary of State <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kissinger </PERSON> tells a news conference that `` this issue is a matter of great delicacy which has many ramifications.'' He declines to go into detail. Feb. 19, 1976: Members of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> AFSA </ORGANIZATION> -RRB-, a union representing <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> officers, express concern over the problem and the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s failure to brief personnel earlier. July 7, 1976: The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> announces that the intensity of the microwave radiation beamed at the embassy has been `` greatly reduced,'' down to 2 microwatts per square centimeter outside the building and a fraction of a microwatt inside. Also announced is the signing of a contract with <ORGANIZATION> Johns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hopkins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> for an epidemiological study of personnel assigned to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> and other posts in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. Jan. 4, 1977: A notice posted at the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> embassy discloses that about one-third of individuals tested have shown abnormally high white blood cell counts. It says the cause for this lymphocytosis condition is unknown. Nov. 20, 1978: Results of the <PERSON> Johns </PERSON> <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON> epidemiological study are released and come under criticism by <ORGANIZATION> AFSA </ORGANIZATION>. In a report with numerous caveats and limitations, the study team says `` no convincing evidence'' was found that would directly link exposure to microwave radiation in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> with adverse health effects. April 1979: The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> issues a report criticizing the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s handling of the microwaves affair _ particularly its failure to inform employees from 1953 to 1976 June 1981: A 14-member panel, the <ORGANIZATION> Electromagnetic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radiation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advisory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, concludes `` there is no scientific evidence, nor are there any theoretical grounds to suggest that biological effects would be expected to occur from the type and low levels of exposure presented'' in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. Nov. 10, 1983: Ambassador <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Hartman </PERSON> tells reporters in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> that he made a protest to the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> over a microwave beam aimed at the embassy between July 14 and Oct. 19, with a power level of 2 microwatts. March 3, 1988: A statement released by the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diplomatic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> says that `` microwave signals in the 5-11 GHz range continue to be detected at the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> embassy chancery. Typical power levels, it says, are 0.1 microwatt per square centimeter outside the building and 0.01 microwatt inside.
</TEXT>
