<HEAD>Oil Prices Mixed In Quiet Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Unleaded gasoline futures prices have moved higher in a mixed market, following a report showing heavy stock drawdowns last week. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, June contracts for wholesale unleaded gasoline closed up 0.63 cent at 52.25 cents per gallon Wednesday, while June wholesale heating oil dropped 0.28 cent to 47.46 cents per gallon. The June contract for <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION>, the benchmark <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude grade, closed at $ 17.49 per barrel, up 3 cents from Tuesday's close. Trading was extremely light, said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Beutel </PERSON>, assistant director of the energy group at <ORGANIZATION> Elders </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. He said many traders were reluctant to get too involved in the market until the June 7 meeting of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries. The cartel scheduled the meeting after failing several weeks ago to reach agreement on a proposal by several major non-OPEC producers for joint production cuts. Unleaded gasoline moved strongly higher because of weekly statistics issued late Tuesday by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, a Washington-based trade organization, <PERSON> Beutel </PERSON> said. The figures showed domestic gasoline production dropping by a half-million barrels, inventories slipping by 3 million barrels and imports dropping by 344,000 barrels in the week ended Friday. The shrinkage of supplies encouraged traders to buy in anticipation that shorter supplies might lead to higher prices, <PERSON> Beutel </PERSON> said.
