<HEAD>Tisch Says Goal Is Making CBS a Ratings Leader</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The chief executive of <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> says the company is trying to come up with programming that will regain the <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> network's leadership of the prime time audience ratings. But <PERSON> Laurence </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tisch </PERSON> was criticized Wednesday by some shareholders, one of whom said <PERSON> Tisch </PERSON> had destroyed a company that was the `` class of the industry'' by selling off several of its major businesses. <PERSON> Tisch </PERSON> responded by telling the company's stockholders at their annual meeting that the recent sales of the CBS magazine and music businesses had produced `` excellent returns'' and allowed the company to focus on its core broadcasting business. <PERSON> Tisch </PERSON> also said he was looking for opportunities to use some of CBS' $ 3 billion cash hoard to buy television or radio stations. <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> has four TV stations that cover about 20 percent of the country and, under federal rules, can buy additional stations extending that coverage up to 25 percent. <PERSON> Tisch </PERSON> also repeated earlier assertions that neither the <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> television network nor <ORGANIZATION> Loews </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s 24.9 percent stake in the company were for sale. In addition to heading <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Tisch </PERSON> is chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Loews </ORGANIZATION>, which has interests in insurance, tobacco and hotels. He said <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> had no plans to sell its <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> headquarters building, nicknamed <PERSON> Black </PERSON> <PERSON> Rock </PERSON>, a move that had been rumored for weeks. Since the last shareholders meeting, <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> sold its magazine group for $ 650 million and its CBS records operation for $ 2 billion. The <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> television network finished in third place in prime time ratings for the first time during the season that just ended. <PERSON> Tisch </PERSON> noted that asset sales had boosted the company's capital and that net interest income reached $ 51.7 million in the first quarter in contrast to net interest expense of $ 9.3 million in the same period of 1987. But <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Colin </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, a longtime <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> shareholder and an executive with the <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> division that was sold as part of the <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> records group sale, told <PERSON> Tisch </PERSON> he seemed more interested in `` running a closed-end mutual fund with the revenues derived from <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> assets'' than in broadcasting. He said the asset sales might have pleased Wall Street, but had demoralized remaining <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> employees and `` effectively destroyed something that was very near and dear to many of us _ a once great company, a company that many considered to be the gem, the class of the industry.'' Colin is among a group of <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> records executives who have sued <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION>, claiming they were wrongfully denied more than $ 1 million in bonuses for 1987. While <PERSON> Tisch </PERSON> did not comment directly on <PERSON> Colin </PERSON>'s statement, he said later in the 2 -LCB- - hour meeting that the network had some `` exciting new programs'' for the next TV season and that employee morale was `` very high. `` We are ready to take on the world in the battle to regain the No. 1 position,'' he said. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Paley </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> chairman, did n't attend the meeting, but sent remarks in which he said he had reviewed the pilots for next season and found them `` imaginative and exciting. I believe that they represent the first step in our recovery of our premier position in the industry.'' Assessing the outlook for broadcast advertising, <PERSON> Tisch </PERSON> said the first half of 1988 has `` not proved to be as strong as originally estimated, and the industry outlook for the third quarter is less optimistic than anticipated.'' He said this and the delay in the start of the fall television season due to the <ORGANIZATION> Writers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guild </ORGANIZATION> strike made it impossible to estimate <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> earnings for the year. But he added the company did not anticipate a severe drop in profit.
