<SECOND>PM-Canada-Stock Exchange, Bjt,0586</SECOND>
<HEAD>Toronto Market Weathers Drop, Seeks New Business</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BRADLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Still trying to rebound from October's world stock market crash, the <ORGANIZATION> Toronto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> has set its sights on grabbing business from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> markets. Exchange officials hope their advanced automated trading system, which has been licensed to several foreign exchanges, proves a key advantage in luring Canadian companies that now trade primarily in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The exchange, which lists 1,600 stocks and accounts for 77 percent of Canadian trading, got a jolt on Wednesday when share prices tumbled in the biggest one-day decline in four months, raising fears of an impending economic recession. The exchange's 300 stock composite index closed down 63.82 points at 3,228.68 on Wednesday, the largest drop since a 118-point tumble on Jan. 8. The drop, which mirrored a sharp decline on Wall Street caused by rising interest rates and recessionary jitters, was the latest setback for a market where activity has slackened significantly since the Oct. 19 crash. Since then, the number of investors has declined by 10 percent and the dollar value of trading has dropped 41 percent. In light of that trend and the increasingly global nature of securities trading, the agenda for exchange President <PERSON> Pearce </PERSON> <PERSON> Bunting </PERSON> and other officials is to use their market's technological assets to drum up business. The <ORGANIZATION> Toronto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> almost exclusively lists Canadian companies, but about 55 major players trade the bulk of their shares on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> or <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Bunting </PERSON> plans to promote his exchange via the Computer Assisted Trading System, known as CATS, that it pioneered and now licenses to the <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> stock exchanges. `` We will set up an electronic central order book system,'' he said. `` All bids and offers will meet electronically in the middle. In the end, you can envisage thousands of terminals around the world that would be connected with our system. `` It will give us the opportunity to be one step up on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>.'' The push for more business comes with the the October crash still fresh on the minds of local traders, especially during Wednesday's decline. `` There's a lot of nervousness out there and investors will jump on any bit of information,'' said analyst <PERSON> Laird </PERSON> <PERSON> Grantham </PERSON> of the firm <ORGANIZATION> Davidson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION>. `` They're worried about a recession.'' <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> led major developed countries last year with real growth of 3.9 percent. The strong economy, and the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Canada </ORGANIZATION>'s policy of maintaining a 2.5 to 3 percentage point interest rate spread over rates in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, helped boost the Canadian dollar to an exchange rate of 81 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cents from 69 cents since 1986. But government figures for January and February showed growth and job creation at a standstill. In six weeks, the leaders of the Group of Seven countries and the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> will gather in <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> for an economic summit to discuss how to avert another market crash and recession. But with President <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> in his final months in office, local traders were not confident the summit would tackle what they see as the epicenter of economic unrest: the huge <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> budget and trade deficits. <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Bainbridge </PERSON>, an equity trader for <ORGANIZATION> Gordon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, one of 75 members on the exchange, also said: `` Historically, after every American presidential election the market goes down for two years.''
