<HEAD>Question of Corporate Responsibility May Be Decided in Wisconsin
Steel Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Nearly 11 years after its ill-fated sale of <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Steel </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Navistar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> is being sued in a case that could answer the far-reaching question of how much a company can be obligated to pay retired and laid-off workers. <ORGANIZATION> Navistar </ORGANIZATION> is accused of selling the money-losing steel unit in 1977 to <ORGANIZATION> Envirodyne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> _ a <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles-based </LOCATION> engineering company with no steel-making experience _ in a bid free itself of multimillion-dollar pension payouts and other employee-benefit obligations. In a trial scheduled to begin today before <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Moran </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Pension </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Benefit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guaranty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the federal insurer of pensions, is seeking $ 145 million _ $ 63 million in unpaid benefits for the laid-off or retired steelworkers, plus interest. In the second lawsuit, <ORGANIZATION> Wisconsin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> creditors _ including an <ORGANIZATION> Envirodyne </ORGANIZATION> unit, the <ORGANIZATION> EDC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Holding </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> _ are seeking $ 177 million from <ORGANIZATION> Navistar </ORGANIZATION>, charging fraud and racketeering in the 1977 sale of the steel company. <ORGANIZATION> Navistar </ORGANIZATION>, known as <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Harvester </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in 1977, lent <ORGANIZATION> Envirodyne </ORGANIZATION> $ 50 million to finance the $ 65 million acquisition of <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> Steel. Harvester's own investme