<HEAD>Report: Agreement To Keep Shoreham Closed Is Near</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HICKSVILLE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Several `` agreements in principle'' that would bring about the abandonment of the <LOCATION> Shoreham </LOCATION> nuclear plant have been reached by the state and the <ORGANIZATION> Long </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Island </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lighting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a published report says. Under the agreements, which must be approved by Gov. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> LILCO </ORGANIZATION>, the state would gain control of <LOCATION> Shoreham </LOCATION> for $ 1 and shut it down, marking the first time a completed nuclear plant would be shut down before it began operating, the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> reported in Thursday editions. <ORGANIZATION> LILCO </ORGANIZATION> has agreed to pay the estimated $ 400 million to $ 500 million costs of the shutdown, the newspaper said, quoting state officials who spoke on the condition of anonymity. The Times said the agreements included guarantees to <ORGANIZATION> LILCO </ORGANIZATION> of annual rate increases of 4 percent to 5 percent for the next decade and the restoration of dividends to the company's shareholders beginning in 1989. Also, <ORGANIZATION> LILCO </ORGANIZATION> would take a $ 2.5 billion tax write-off for the plant, meaning it would pay no federal taxes for at least a decade, the newspaper said. And the state would let the utility float $ 100 million in tax-exempt industrial development bonds that could be used to refinance more expensive debt, the Times reported. The $ 5.3 billion plant has been a rallying cry for opponents of nuclear energy, politicians campaigning for office and the utility, which contends the plant's energy was essential if the island was to have enough energy into the next century. Although the plant was supported by state and local officials when construction first began in the 1970s, opposition grew as nuclear energy became less popular and more expensive and as the completion of the plant fell behind 10 years and 10 times over budget. State and local officials argued that <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> could never be quickly evacuated in an emergency and they refused to participate in any emergency plans for the plant, located 55 miles east of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. Meanwhile, the <ORGANIZATION> Long </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Island </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION>, created to consider a <ORGANIZATION> LILCO </ORGANIZATION> takeover, is continuing its proxy battle to elect three of its nominees to <ORGANIZATION> LILCO </ORGANIZATION>'s board of directors.
