<HEAD>Texas Will Appeal Federal Judge's Ruling On Florida Citrus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BROWNSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> will appeal a federal judge's ruling that blocks efforts to keep fresh <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> citrus out of the <ORGANIZATION> Lone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION>, an official said. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Filemon </PERSON> <PERSON> Vela </PERSON> ruled Wednesday that the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> did nothing wrong when it lifted a 3 -LCB- - year ban on shipments of the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> fruit to other citrus-producing areas `` We told the attorney general today that we'd like him to start putting the paperwork together'' for an appeal, said <ORGANIZATION> TDA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Max </PERSON> <PERSON> Woodfin </PERSON>. The <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> fruit was quarantined after an outbreak of citrus canker in parts of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> in August 1984. The <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> on Feb. 11 lifted the ban on shipments of fresh <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> citrus into <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and other citrus-producing areas. <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> officials had sought to have the quarantine reinstated and claimed the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> did not allow adequate time for comment when it lifted the ban. <PERSON> Vela </PERSON>'s ruling Wednesday was in response to a suit filed March 9 by the state of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, which was trying to stop shipments of the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> fruit to the state. The suit contends that the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> violated its own rules by failing to allow a comment period before lifting the ban. `` With all the information put before me, I am satisfied that the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> followed the law'' in promulgating the rule, <PERSON> Vela </PERSON> said Wednesday. The judge said the new protocol is so similar to one the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> proposed last fall but withdrew in January that there had been plenty of time for comment. Canker, which comes in different strains, can damage the plants and cause lesions on the fruit or make it drop prematurely from trees. <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> citrus producers say an outbreak of canker would devastate the state's $ 65 million citrus industry concentrated on 30,000 acres in <LOCATION> Hidalgo </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Cameron </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Willacy </LOCATION> counties in the Lower <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Grande </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>. `` We've maintained all along that the risk of our getting canker is relatively small, but it's a risk we do n't believe we ought to take,'' said <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Prewett </PERSON>, director of <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Citrus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mutual </ORGANIZATION>, a McAllen-based industry group. <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> officials have maintained that the canker is under control.
