<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Mostly Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Grain and soybean futures opened lower Thursday on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> as scattered showers dampened parts of the <LOCATION> Corn </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Belt </LOCATION> and weather forecasters predicted heavier precipitation this weekend. Soybean futures posted the steepest early declines after five straight days of sharp increases that were based on dry weather conditions and an <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> report predicting dwindling soybean stockpiles. `` The market is relatively quiet after all the excitement and hoopla about Tuesday,'' when the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> issued the report, said <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Gidel </PERSON>, an analyst with G.H. <ORGANIZATION> Miller </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. `` We're starting things off on a little more of a so-so situation here. Losses in wheat futures were limited by the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>'s offer late Tuesday of 1 million metric tons of subsidized <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat to <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Gidel </PERSON> said. In early trading, wheat was -RCB- cent lower to \ cent higher with the contract for delivery in May at $ 3.02 \ a bushel; corn was unchanged to 1 cent lower with May at $ 1.96 -RCB- a bushel; oats were 1 -RCB- cents to 2 -LCB- cents lower with May at $ 1.56 a bushel; soybeans were 1 \ cents to 4 -LCB- cents lower with May at $ 7.08 a Cattle futures were mixed while pork futures were mostly higher in early trading on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Live cattle were .13 cent lower to .13 cent higher with Ju