<FIRST>r f BC-Panama-Economy     05-12 0650</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Panama-Economy,0673</SECOND>
<HEAD>Difficult Recovery Seen for Panamanian Economy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 If <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s political crisis were resolved tomorrow, it would take at least two years and a vigorous recovery program for the devastated economy to return to the levels of early 1987, according to five of the country's top economists. In the absence of a prompt solution to the crisis, which stems from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and local efforts to topple strongman Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> could be headed for collapse of its productive apparatus, hunger and totalitariansim, the five said Wednesday. Economist <PERSON> Ruben </PERSON> <PERSON> Carles </PERSON> provided The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> with a copy of the report, entitled `` A Proposal for Economic Reconstruction.'' <PERSON> Carles </PERSON> is a director of a local bank and adviser to several major multinational and Panamanian enterprises. The other authors _ bankers, consultants and academics _ are <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Valencia </PERSON>, <PERSON> Marco </PERSON> <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON>, <PERSON> Guillermo </PERSON> <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Galan </PERSON> <PERSON> Ponce </PERSON>. They are all, in varying degrees, opponents of the military-dominated government. But the government also recognizes the dire economic consequences of the crisis. Treasury Minister <PERSON> Orvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Goodin </PERSON> said Tuesday the gross national product would decrease by up to 20 percent this year. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration has for the past 2 -LCB- months imposed increasingly severe economic sanctions on <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> hoped the measures would force <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> to resign and leave the country, but he has resisted the pressure and appears firmly entrenched. The general, who is commander of the Panamanian defense forces, is the country's de facto ruler. In February, he was indicted in federal courts in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> on drug smuggling and money laundering charges. He denies the accusations, contending they are part of an attempt to replace him with a leader amenable to a strong <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> presence in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> into the next century. The 1977 <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION> treaties oblige <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to hand over complete control of the waterway and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military bases along it by Dec. 31, 1999. The authors of the report say the crisis and resulting sanctions have produced a more than 50 percent decrease in the amount of money circulating in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. `` That allows for maintenance of likewise less than half the production and transactions normally carried out in the country,'' says the report. Banks, which had been closed for nine weeks, reopened Monday, but with severe restrictions. `` Economic activity is principally dedicated to liquidation of stocks, given that imports are almost nil and it is extremely difficult, if not impossible, to finance production,'' the report says. The authors say that, in recent months, unemployment has risen from about 12 percent of the workforce to approximately 20 percent. They say that, even with a political solution in the coming weeks or months, more than 40,000 more people stand to lose their jobs because of the shrinking economy. That would raise unemployment to 26 percent of the workforce. <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> uses the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar as its currency. The report's authors said one option open to the Panamanian regime would be `` intervention or nationalization of the banking system and the emission of a local currency with attendant extremely grave economic consequences that would imply a transition toward totalitarianism.'' They propose a series of steps contingent on solution of the political crisis, which would include abandonment of power by <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>. The report says extensive international relief will be needed to alleviate hunger among the poor, who have been battered by the crisis. It says international financial support totaling hundreds of millions of dollars will be necessary. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> would have to provide ample credit to Panamanian banks and the foreign debt of $ 3.9 billion would have to be renegotiated, according to the recovery plan. `` Our plan ... takes as a starting point the recognition that it will take a period of no less than 24 months to return to the levels of production and employment of the first semester of 1987,'' the report says.
</TEXT>
