<NOTE>For Release PMs Friday May 13</NOTE>
<HEAD>The Market Is a Bigger Loser Than Stocks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Day by day it becomes clearer that one of the big losers in the stock market is the market itself. Business is off and layoffs are rising. The public is disaffected with the way the market operates, especially its volatility and seemingly senseless changes of direction. The publicity is negative. Various study groups complain, in effect, that the market has become an assembly of institutional sharpies who skim profits by means of technicalities and sophisticated computer programs. The most devastating criticism comes from within the system itself. Some of the biggest brokers have agreed to shut down their in-house program trading operations, which seek almost automatic profits on technicalities, because angry customers feel such operations work against their interests. The head of a prominent small-investor brokerage house, <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwab </PERSON>, has referred to program traders as manipulators. And <PERSON> Schwab </PERSON>'s own operation has been criticized because investors could n't reach brokers on Oct. 19. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Ball </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said a poll by his company showed individual investors, who generally invest on the basis of a company's management and earnings, feel cheated by market manipulators. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Regan </PERSON>, blunt-speaking former <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> secretary, told the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> this week that the public has a right to believe the marketplace is rigged. `` It is,'' he snapped. <PERSON> Regan </PERSON>'s criticism is especially damaging because in his pre-White House years he was one of the most promiment of all Wall Streeters, head of <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> and a leader in bringing individual investors into the markeplace. Anger is also being directed at the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> and at the <ORGANIZATION> Commodities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trading </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, whose jobs are to protect the public from shenanigans that inevitably arise and must be squashed. The worst of these practices appears to be that of capitalizing on gaps in prices of stock traded on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> and stock index futures traded in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. The players often are brokerage houses themselves. When these gaps appear _ gaps that have nothing at all to do with basic values _ they can produce wild price swings as money jumps from one to the other in an attempt to skim off profits. Small investors can not take such advantage. They have too little capital, they have too little time, they have too little sophistication. Gaps are discovered by those with immediate access to data and instant communications. These automatic trading practices, mindlessly initiated by electronic programs that spot opportunities, are believed to have triggered, accelerated and reinforced the crash of last Oct. 19. Oddly, little comment and criticism has been heard from the companies whose stocks are affected. But that criticism is sure to come. Companies such as <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION>, for example, know that <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> investors are inclined to buy <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> products, and they seek to exploit that relationship with reminders in their quarterly reports to shareholders. If these shareholders are n't protected from marketplace shenanigans, it is fair to expect that they will lose their enthusiasm for investing, hurting the value of the corporation's stock and, quite likely, its sales as well So pervasive are the negative comments about program trading that it has, for the time being, overwhelmed concern about the legal problems that had begun to unfold before the Oct. 19 crash and are about to make headlines again. Investigations already have led to jail sentences for several traders, including <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON>. But those investigations continue; they are expected to bring in other promiment parties, perhaps on criminal charges. Criminality, according to government investigators, is rampant rather than existing on the periphery of the marketplace. In a pre-sentencing memo in the <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON> case, government officials said they found `` criminal conduct is at the heart of a substantial amount of market activity by established securities industry professionals.'' In short, the marketplace has an odor that drives away customers.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Friday May 13</NOTE>
