 British <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. PLC, the world's fourth-largest oil company, said Thursday its first-quarter, after-tax profit sank 43 percent from a year ago because of lower oil <ORGANIZATION> BP </ORGANIZATION> said its profit fell to 263 million pounds in the first three months of 1988 from 458 million pounds in the year-earlier period. In dollars, that worked out to $ 473 million as opposed to $ 705 million in the 1987 first quarter, the company said. British companies' accounting method can not be directly compared to the method used by American companies, because of differences in determining the value of inventories. Using the American method, <ORGANIZATION> BP </ORGANIZATION>'s profit rose by 26 percent, to 408 million pounds, compared with 324 million pounds in the first quarter of 1987. In dollars, that worked out to $ 734 million vs. $ 499 million in the first quarter of 1987. First-quarter revenue fell 8.3 percent, to 6.49 billion pounds, or $ 11.7 billion, from 7.08 billion pounds, or $ 10.9 billion. `` The first quarter of 1988 was characterized by a return to lower oil prices as the market forces of excess supply prevailed, despite continuing political tension in the Gulf,'' <ORGANIZATION> BP </ORGANIZATION> said. The fall in the crude price resulted in an inventory loss of 145 million pounds, or $ 261 million, in the first quarter, compared with an inventory gain of 134 million pounds, or $ 206 million, a year ago, <ORGANIZATION> BP </ORGANIZATION> said. In terms of operating profits, which do not include interest and tax payments, the company said: _ Exploration and production fell to 407 million pounds, or $ 733 million, from 462 million pounds, or $ 711 million, due to lower crude oil prices and adverse exchange rate movements _ Refining and marketing earned 140 million pounds, or $ 252 million, down from 177 million pounds, or $ 273 million _ Chemical operations jumped to 133 million pounds, or $ 239 million, from 51 million pounds, or $ 79 million, largely due to strong demand for petrochemical products _ Minerals earned 58 million pounds, or $ 104 million, up from 10 million pounds, or $ 15 million <ORGANIZATION> BP </ORGANIZATION> ranks fourth after <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dutch-Shell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Mobil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>.
