<FIRST>r f PM-NaturalGas 1stLd-Writethru   05-12 0457</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Natural Gas, 1st Ld-Writethru,0467</SECOND>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 9 grafs new with figures released by Interior Department.
Picks up 3rd graf pvs, Energy Department.
^By GUY DARST</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Estimates of the nation's economically recoverable but so-far-undiscovered offshore oil could be 27 percent lower than previous estimates, according to preliminary figures released today by the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. The department released new estimates for offshore oil and gas supplies and backup material for onshore estimates released in March. By coincidence, the new material was released shortly after the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said it believed the nation had a 35-year supply of natural gas at prices under $ 3 per thousand cubic feet, and a $ 5 price would bring forth only another 10 years supply. Estimates of undiscovered onshore oil released by the Geological Survey in March were down about 40 percent from previous figures, in part because of drilling disappointments but also because lower prices keep explorers from even considering high-cost pools. Today's numbers were broken down by area, and department officials refused to supply totals, citing their desire to avoid giving any impression the figures were unchangeable. But simple addition showed that the mean estimate _ that estimate which there is a 50 percent chance of exceeding _ was 8.87 billion barrels of oil, down 27 percent, and 74 trillion cubic feet of natural gas, down 18 percent. Expressed in terms of equivalent energy content, the new estimates would be 22 percent below the old ones. The same estimates in 1984 were 12.2 billion barrels of oil and 90.5 trillion cubic feet of gas. The decline, according to an <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> analyst who spoke on condition he not be identified, can be attributed to drilling disappointments, notably in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, and lower prices. The new estimates assume oil costs $ 18 a barrel, about the current price. The old estimates assumed oil costs of about $ 30 a barrel. Energy Secretary <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Herrington </PERSON> said in announcing the new reserve estimates that `` natural gas has not taken its rightful place'' in the nation's energy supplies and the department was trying to allay public fears of short supplies left over from pipeline curtailments in the severe northeastern winters of 1976-77 and 1977-78. If price were no object, current technology could recover about 1,029 trillion cubic feet of natural gas, the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> study said. At $ 3 per thousand cubic feet or less, 583 trillion cubic feet could be produced. An increase in price to $ 5 would bring only an additional 174 trillion cubic feet. The nation uses about 17 trillion cubic feet of natural gas per year. The average wellhead price last year was $ 1.83, which the department's semi-independent <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> predicts will reach $ 4.02 in the year 2000.
</TEXT>
