<HEAD>Davis Bid for TV Producer That Agreed to Takeover by Warner</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CULVER CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Investor <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> renewed his bid for ailing television producer <ORGANIZATION> Lorimar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telepictures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. Thursday, just two days after <PERSON> Lorimar </PERSON> agreed to become part of <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, who previously offered $ 17 per share for the maker of such hit TV series as `` <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>'' and `` Knots Landing,'' notified the company he would pay $ 15 cash per share, or $ 679.5 <PERSON> Lorimar </PERSON> values the tentative agreement it made with <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> Tuesday at $ 1.18 billion. That agreement includes assumption of $ 550 million in <LOCATION> Lorimar </LOCATION> debt and financial penalties if <PERSON> Lorimar </PERSON> backs out and merges with a third party. Pending review of confidential financial information, <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> said in a letter released by <PERSON> Lorimar </PERSON>, `` we are prepared to consider increasing our price in a negotiated transaction.'' A spokesman for <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, an oil man and investor who formerly owned <ORGANIZATION> Twentieth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Century </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fox </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Film </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, declined to comment. Lorimar officials declined immediate comment on the impact <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>' offer might have on the <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> transaction. That match was seen as a way to solve <PERSON> Lorimar </PERSON>'s cash problems and make <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> a leader in television production as well as its present strength in movies and music. The deal was conditional, but <ORGANIZATION> Lorimar </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Merv </PERSON> <PERSON> Adelson </PERSON> made it clear at the time he saw the tax-free stock-swap deal with <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> as the ideal marriage. <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>' $ 15-per-share figure for Lorimar matches the minimum value placed on the stock swap that forms the basis of the <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> deal. That merger, tentatively scheduled to close in September, would trade .415 shares of <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> stock for each of the 45.3 million outstanding shares of Lorimar common stock. In addition to the stock swap, valued by the companies at $ 630 million, <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> would assume about $ 550 million in <LOCATION> Lorimar </LOCATION> debt. <PERSON> Lorimar </PERSON> is allowed to back out if <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION>'s stock value does not bring <ORGANIZATION> Lorimar </ORGANIZATION> shareholders at least $ 15 per share, a figure <PERSON> Lorimar </PERSON> calculates would be met if <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION>'s stock price averages $ 36 a share. If <PERSON> Lorimar </PERSON> cancels, the agreement commits it to pay <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> $ 10 million. If <PERSON> Lorimar </PERSON> is acquired by a third party, <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> has the right to buy 18.5 percent of the outstanding shares at $ 15 a share.
