<FIRST>r f AM-WheatTour     05-12 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wheat Tour,0414</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Evaluators To Examine Wheat Fields In Seven States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT LEE ZIMMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHAMPAIGN, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A team of evaluators will examine wheat fields in seven states next week to check on the condition of the crop as it approaches harvest. `` The wheat is starting to head out,'' said <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Quinton </PERSON>, a grain analyst for the AgriVisor marketing service in <LOCATION> Bloomington </LOCATION>. `` It is in a very critical stage _ the reproductive stage.'' <PERSON> Quinton </PERSON> has organized the wheat evaluation tour, which will focus on the nation's key soft red winter wheat states of <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> this week issued its first estimates of the season for wheat production across the country based on May 1 conditions. It said the harvest is expected to be up 4 percent for all winter varieties. `` We do feel it would be worthwhile to go out and get a mid-course correction,'' <PERSON> Quinton </PERSON> said Wednesday. He said soft red wheat production is projected to be 426 million bushels from this summer's harvest, up from 348 million bushels in 1987. `` This very likely is not so much a yield increase as an acreage increase,'' said <PERSON> Quinton </PERSON>, noting farmers planted 1.7 million more acres last fall than the previous year. The states in which evaluators will examine fields have nearly 7 million acres of soft red winter wheat out of a total of about 10.5 million in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Quinton </PERSON> said. Evaluators will begin the tour Monday, covering several routes and stopping about every 15 to 20 miles to check fields. The team will include people from the grain trade, the milling industry, the government, producer groups and the news media. In each field, participants will check the soil moisture condition, the stage of development of the wheat, the size of the stand, and the potential number and size of grain heads. They also will look for any evidence of disease. <PERSON> Quinton </PERSON> said most of the soft red winter wheat seems to be in good condition. Most was planted in a timely fashion last fall, and cool, dry spring conditions have favored the development of much of the crop. Soft red wheat is milled to make fine flours that are used in things like cake, cookies and crackers. It is the hard wheat grown farther west that is used for breads.
</TEXT>
