<FIRST>r f AM-Germany-EEC     05-12 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-EEC,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>EEC Finance Ministers To Discuss Proposal for a Common Currency</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Finance and economics ministers from the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> meet Friday and Saturday to discuss an idea which some key observers say may be an impossible dream: creation of a single EEC currency. `` I doubt that the governments are prepared to make such a far-reaching decision,'' <PERSON> Karl </PERSON> <PERSON> Otto </PERSON> <PERSON> Poehl </PERSON>, president of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s central <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION>, told reporters last week. The community's finance and economics ministers as well as central bank presidents from the 12 <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> nations are to hold a closed-door session in the Baltic Seas coastal resort town of <LOCATION> Travemuende </LOCATION>, near <LOCATION> Luebeck </LOCATION>. Several key West European leaders, including West German Foreign Minister <PERSON> Hans-Dietrich </PERSON> <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON>, have proposed creating a common EEC currency as well as a central <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> bank to manage it. In February, <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON> urged the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> to appoint a team of experts to come up with a definite plan. The proposals for a common currency are expected to be a major topic of discussion at the Travemuende meeting, according to finance ministry officials here. Other possible means of strengthening the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>'s exchange-rate system, the European Monetary System, are also expected to be topics at the meeting. <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON>, French Finance Minister <PERSON> Edouard </PERSON> <PERSON> Balladur </PERSON> and others say a common EEC currency would strengthen West European unity and help smooth the way for the creation of a barrier-free internal market throughout <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> by 1992. But skeptics of the plan, including <PERSON> Poehl </PERSON>, say they do n't think <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> governments are ready to take steps that could lead to denting their currency autonomy. <PERSON> Poehl </PERSON> and others have pointed out that many EEC nations including <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> are not even full members of the European Monetary System. `` At a time that most of the EEC countries are not even able to fulfill their obligations to this very limited system, it's a little premature to talk about something new,'' <PERSON> Poehl </PERSON> said. Only <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> are full members of the monetary system, which works to stabilize currency exchange rates within the EEC. <PERSON> Poehl </PERSON> has also repeatedly warned that any steps towards creating a central European Bank could infringe upon the constitutional independence of the <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
