<FIRST>r f AM-RetailSales 1stLd-Writethru   05-12 0673</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Retail Sales, 1st Ld-Writethru,0692</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sales Show First Downturn in Six Months</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 3 grafs with White House comment and interest rate
background after 11th graf, ``Total economic''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Retail sales fell 0.6 percent in April, the first setback in six months, with the decline blamed on an early Easter, bad weather and a bigger federal tax bite for some people. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said consumers spent a seasonally adjusted $ 131.6 billion at retail stores last month, a drop of $ 815 million from the revised March figure. Sales had not fallen since a 0.8 percent setback last October, but economists said they were not particularly concerned by the weakness, especially since sales in March were revised upward to show an increase of 1.7 percent. That was the fastest sales advance since last August and almost twice the originally estiated 0.8 percent gain for the month. Both the big jump in March sales and the April decline were blamed on the fact that Easter occurred on April 3 this year, meaning that consumers did their spring shopping in March, siphoning off sales that would normally have occurred last month. `` The April retail sales figure is very misleading because of Easter. Consumer spending is still holding up well,'' said <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinai </PERSON>, chief economist of the <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Analysts said other factors that played a role in the April decline were unseasonably cold weather in some parts of the country that discouraged sales of such items as garden equipment and higher tax bills some Americans faced at filing time this year They noted in particular that sales at restaurants were down 1.6 percent, while sales at furniture stores were off 0.2 percent. `` Some people did get shocked by the new tax law. They may have filled out their tax forms and decided they could n't afford to eat out for the rest of the month,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyss </PERSON>, an economist with <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Megan </PERSON>, an economist with <ORGANIZATION> Evans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economics </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> forecasting firm, said he was not concerned by the April sales dip because with unemployment now at a 14-year low of 5.4 percent, consumers are confident about the future `` With employment and incomes still growing, we expect consumers will keep spending,'' he said. Total economic activity, as measured by the gross national product, rose at an annual rate of 2.3 percent in the first three months of the year, far better than the recession some people were predicting immediately after the October stock market collapse. However, the surprisingly strong growth has raised inflation concerns. Many economists believe the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> has moved in recent days to tighten up on interest rates as a way to dampen demand and keep inflation under control. Major banks on Wednesday boosted their prime lending rate one-half percentage point to 9 percent, reflecting the tighter credit conditions. At the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said the weak report on retail sales `` may serve to dampen inflationary expectations.'' The April retail sales report showed that car sales declined 1 percent during the month, the first drop since last November. Analysts said this reflected the phaseout of various sales incentive programs that had lured consumers into showrooms in earlier months. Without the weakness in car sales, total retail sales would have been a slightly lower 0.5 percent in April. Sales at hardware and building supply stores were up 1 percent. Analysts attributing some of this strength to a boom in home remodeling as more homeowners choose to renovate rather than move to bigger houses. Sales of non-durable goods dropped 0.6 percent overall. Within the category, sales at department stores dropped 0.5 percent, erasing part of the 2.1 percent jump in March. Both months were influenced by the early Easter. Sales at grocery stores fell 0.3 percent in April, while sales at gasoline stations were off 1.3 percent and sales at restaurants dropped 1.6 percent. Sales of all durable goods, items expected to last at least three years, dropped 0.6 percent.
</TEXT>
