<HEAD>Proposal Seeks Higher North American Content in U.S-Canada Auto
Trade</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> has tentatively agreed to authorize the president to negotiate a higher <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> content for automobiles coming under the proposed U.S.-Canada free-trade agreement, the staff of Sen. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Riegle </PERSON>, D-Mich., said Thursday The proposed treaty requires that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> or Canadian parts, components and labor account for half the content of cars moving duty-free across the border. Critics of the treaty, <PERSON> Riegle </PERSON> among them, have said that level is too low. <PERSON> Riegle </PERSON>'s proposal would authorize the president to negotiate a higher domestic-content rule with <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, in the hope of raising it to 60 percent. If negotiations succeed, the president would be able to begin the higher requirement through a proclamation, rather than returning to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> for consent, <PERSON> Riegle </PERSON>'s staff said. Under the terms of the free-trade negotiations, both houses of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> must accept or reject the treaty as is, without amendment. However, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has the power to tie its acceptance of the treaty to the fulfillment of certain conditions, or to pass other legislation authorizing the president to try to renegotiate parts of the agreement. `` My goal has been to improve the implementing language so that the agreement is better,'' <PERSON> Riegle </PERSON> said. `` We are making some significant progress.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> has not completed its work on the bill. The 50 percent North American content requirement has been criticized by the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> and parts suppliers. A level that low would allow manufacturers to import engines, transmissions and other major components. Another heavily criticized provision would allow <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> to retain until 1996 agreements giving preferential duty treatment to manufacturers outside <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> who have Canadian production. Extending the preferential treatment will allow Canadian suppliers and Japanese manufacturers to forge agreements that will shut out <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> suppliers from part of the market, critics have said.
