<FIRST>r f AM-Banks     05-12 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Banks,0390</SECOND>
<HEAD>GAO Report Raps Big Banks on Foreign Debt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banks are undercapitalized and underregulated and have failed to write down approximately $ 28 billion in uncollectable foreign loans, the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> said in a report released Thursday. The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION>, an investigative arm of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, found fault with federal regulators such as the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deposit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> for creating a lenient classification system for developing country debt. Using today's secondary market as a guidepost, the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> calculated that the average Third World loan is worth 54 percent of its stated value. Under this criteria, the report estimated that <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> banks have reserved $ 21.1 billion of foreign loans when a more realistic figure should be $ 49 billion. In contrast, the criteria regulators developed only required $ 2.3 billion in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bank write-downs of uncollectable loans, the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said. Rep. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Leach </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Iowa </LOCATION>, who asked for the report, said, `` In this ` audit of the auditors,' it can be inferred that the record first-quarter profits recently announced for banks engaged in overseas lending are a shibboleth and that these institutions should write off this year loans of a greater magnitude than they did last year. `` Bank earnings are only as sound as their loan portfolios and those portfolios, the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> finds, are overvalued,'' <PERSON> Leach </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bank loans to developing countries decreased from $ 139.7 billion in June 1982 to $ 107.6 billion in December 1987, while <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bank capital increased from $ 66.2 billion in June 1982 to $ 129.2 billion in December 1987. As a result, from June 1982 to December 1987 bank loans owed by developing countries decreased from 211 percent of bank capital to 83 percent. During this time, developing country loans owed to the nine largest money center banks decreased from 323 percent of these banks' capital to 139 percent. `` While these figures reflect a prudential improvement in circumstances for <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> banks, developing country loans are still large compared with bank capital and are disproportionately concentrated in a small number of money center institutions,'' said <PERSON> Leach </PERSON>, a ranking Republican on the House Banking, <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> and its international finance, trade and monetary policy subcommittee.
