<HEAD>Soybean Rally Stalls, Prices Plunge As Rain Falls</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 A five-day rally that pushed soybean futures prices to four-year highs ended Thursday as rainy weather forecasts persuaded traders to take profits. Grain futures also closed lower on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>. On other markets, pork futures continued to climb; cattle futures were mostly higher; precious metals posted slight gains; energy futures slipped a bit; and stock-index futures edged higher. Soybean futures prices had climbed more than 32 cents a bushel _ a gain of nearly 5 percent _ in the past week and set new contract highs on Monday, Tuesday and Wednesday. But the rally stalled Thursday as rain dampened parts of the <LOCATION> Corn </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Belt </LOCATION>, improving the growing conditions for newly planted crops. Weather forecasters predicted precipitation all the way into next week, prompting traders to offset their long positions and take profits, analysts said. `` After three straight days of new contract highs in the beans and meal, any market needs a pause to catch its breath,'' said <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Lespinasse </PERSON>, a trader for <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` It was an orderly correction,'' he said. `` It was n't anything unusual or out of the ordinary.'' Buying interest dried up in the soybean meal market on a lack of orders for <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, where most businesses were closed for a four-day holiday, said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Bartholomew </PERSON>, an assistant vice president at <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. `` They were providing big support yesterday,'' he said of the Europeans. `` Essentially what we had Wednesday was a condensing of three days of potential activity into one day.'' Analyst <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Gidel </PERSON> of G.H. <ORGANIZATION> Miller </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, also noted fairly heavy notices of intent to deliver corn and soybeans against the May contracts, an indication of adequate near-term supplies. Wheat settled 1 -LCB- cents to 4 cents lower with the contract for delivery in May at $ 3.01 \ a bushel; corn was 1 cent to 1 -LCB- cents lower with May at $ 1.96 a bushel; oats were 2 \ cents to 3 -LCB- cents lower with May at $ 1.55 \ a bushel; soybeans were 5 cents to 8 cents lower with May at $ 7.07 Strong cash hog markets helped boost pork futures for a second day on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. `` The cash market is phenomenal,'' said <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Hare </PERSON>, an analyst in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> with <ORGANIZATION> Smith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Barney </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Harris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Upham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` The daily average price in <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION> two weeks ago was 40.93 cents -LRB- a pound -RRB-. Yesterday it was 46.23 cents. That's such a huge increase in a couple of weeks that you've got everyone convinced that it's going to keep going.'' A reduction in the number of hogs coming to market supported notions that the market has entered its seasonal downturn in supplies, he said. Most cattle futures also advanced on strong cash markets and indications of strong retail demand for beef, <LOCATION> O'Hare </LOCA