<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> skilled trades workers have rejected a <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> contract ratified by other union members, <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> officials said Thursday. The rejection does not change the overall ratification, but could lead to new negotiations solely on skilled trades issues such as apprenticeships, according to union officials. The union scheduled a meeting Friday in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> to review the matter with its <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> skilled trades officials, who represent more than 10,500 of the No. 3 automaker's <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> members. The two-year contract, covering 66,000 hourly and salaried workers in 15 states, was ratified Wednesday by 54 percent of those voting. Skilled trades _ such as machine tool makers _ and salaried workers have additional, separate contracts covering issues unique to them. The two groups vote as one on whether to ratify or reject both contracts, which were approved by the salaried workers. <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Joyce </PERSON> said he had no figures on the skilled trades rejection or the salaried approval of the contract. There is at least one skilled trades delegate for each of <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s nearly 50 <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> local unions. If the skilled trades rejection was based on issues contained in the main contract, such as economics, neither new negotiations nor a new skilled trades vote would occur, union sources said. Part of the purpose of Friday's meeting is to determine whether or not the rejection was based on issues unique to the skilled trades. Union officials who asked not to be identified said they believed the rejection was economic. If so, the meeting will be the only action on the rejection and skilled trades workers will have to live with the contract ratified by everybody else. The meeting was called by <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Owen </PERSON> <PERSON> Bieber </PERSON> and Vice President <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON> and will include those delegates on the <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION>'s 140-member national <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> council who represent skilled trades workers
