<HEAD>Continental Airlines Frequent Fliers To Be Credited Millions Of
Miles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL BATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WICHITA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> has entered into an agreement with <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> officials under which the airline will credit millions of miles to members of its airline's frequent flier club, Attorney General <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stephan </PERSON> said Thursday. <PERSON> Stephan </PERSON> said that as recently as May 3 <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> advertised minimum credits of at least 1,000 miles per flight segment while it had been making minimum entries of only 750 miles since Jan. 1. Members of frequent flier clubs accumulate mileage credits that can be used for free or reduced fare airplane tickets. Besides the mileage credit discrepancy, <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> advertised that members of its `` OnePass'' club could receive frequent flier award travel to <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, but the airline did not make such trips available, <PERSON> Stephan </PERSON> charged. <PERSON> Stephan </PERSON> said the brochures and in-flight magazine advertisements were deceptive. He said the company attempted to save millions of dollars worth of award travel tickets nationwide. In the agreement it signed with <PERSON> Stephan </PERSON>'s office, <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> denied it violated <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> consumer protection laws, although it agreed to pay $ 20,000 in costs and investigation fees. The Houston-based airline said that when it announced its triple mileage program in a Jan. 21 letter to OnePass members, it clearly stated the mileage minimum being tripled was 750 miles. The company also said a March 1988 brochure used the 750-mile figure. <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> said in the agreement it depicted <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> as a frequent flier award destination because members wishing to go there could earn credits to make that trip by flying on sister airline Air <LOCATION> Micronesia </LOCATION>. The airline agreed to credit OnePass members at the 1,000-mile rate retroactively and keep the 1,000-mile rate in effect through July. It also agreed to withdraw any remaining advertisements and brochures using the 1,000-mile figure. The airline said it would add <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> as an award travel destination through Dec. 31. <PERSON> Stephan </PERSON> estimated there are more than 2 million active OnePass members. During the first 16 weeks of 1988, <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> enrolled an average of more than 45,000 members a week, he said.
